animal.description:
Gizmo is 8 and 24 lbs of total cuteness. He's best for a more quiet home without kids where he can feel confident, and give you and get all the loves. An older person looking for a pal can work, too!

Gizmo wants to be the only pet, doesn't appear to like other animals much, maybe in due time. We know people are that way, too, so why not a doggie?

Gizmo is a loving boy with people he trusts, but it takes him a little time to befriend new people but then his heart is yours. He is so loyal and extremely loving. He loves snuggle time. He is always so happy to see you walk in the door. He talks a lot with his funny and cute ways, telling you when he wants to eat or such, super comical and darling. He also is a neat and tidy boy.

One of his fave things to do it go on car rides!

Gizmo will thrive in a home with a yard. He loves his walks and we have tips on how to keep him focused so he isn't barking at other dogs. If your neighborhood is quiet, it is perfect for him! He thrives in the outdoors on long walks, esp on the beach, in the woods or wherever else great sniffing is offered!

Gizmo is a barker and we can provide tips but it is why we are seeking a more quiet neighborhood. He currently lives in a busy place and he may do really well right off the bat in a place with room. He also is fiercely protective of his owner. We have tips and can help with introduction techniques so he learns who in the family is cool as a cat.

He is now updated on all shots, neutered and chipped! His adopt fee is $295.

We cover the medical to prepare the pet for adoption and the adopt donations go directly to cover those costs and range from $295-$495. Thank you for stepping up to save a life!

To expedite to meet with this dog, please go to our site at www.savinggreatanimals.org and fill out an application. We look at the first applications to arrive, so we hope to hear from you soon!

animal.description:
Because we are all volunteers, Illinois Doberman Rescue Plus only considers approved applicants to meet our orphans in our foster homes. Please read our eligibility requirements and apply on our website: www.ildoberescue.com/adopt. After an application is submitted, additional inquiries can email PlusDogs@ILDobeRescue.com. Our adoption radius is 3 hours from the Chicagoland area.

Back in March, Zola came to IDR+ after she was picked up loose, loaded with worms, and emaciated, and a prong collar was embedded in her skin. Animal control contacted her owners, but they didn't want her anymore since she lived outside on a chain for the past 7 years. Zola's wonderful foster home treated her parasites, healed her skin, and put some healthy weight on her. After all of that, her foster parents decided to keep her. But Zola's neglectful past made living with another dog difficult. She was used to defending herself at the end of a chain, and she does not appreciate the company of other dogs in the home or while walking on a leash. Therefore, Zola's ideal home would be as the only pet with a privacy fence. She does not need to go for walks around the neighborhood--she would be perfectly happy prancing around her yard as the queen bee. This was a difficult decision for her home the past several months, but this is the best for Zola. She loves to sunbathe, eat, snuggle, and get attention. She might even give you a cute little "howl" if she is looking for more attention. Zola is fully potty trained and knows several commands. She loves to be praised and rewarded for being the sweet girl that she is. Zola is on an easy medication for her bladder leakage. Her medicine is not expensive and stops the leaking, so she will need to stay on this medication.  Zola is very well mannered.  She stays out of garbage, doesn't counter surf, and will stay off the furniture if you ask her. Zola is very sweet-natured and would love to find a forever home that she can run around, chase balls, and be so loved. Zola will not be placed with cats, but she has been great with kids she has met. 

The biographical information provided is correct to the best of our knowledge while the animal is in our care or includes what may have been provided by a previous owner. We strive to be honest and accurate, but animals can change their personalities and behavior when they settle into a new home. IDR+ makes no guarantees based on the information we observe and provide.

animal.description:
Zoey is a goofy playful girl who loves all sizes of dogs. She is 2 years old and 80 pounds
She would greatly enjoy a dog playmate in her forever home.  Poorly socialized for her first 18 months, she is very leery of strangers and needs a securely fenced yard, privacy fencing recommended... large enough for some good running play and fetch.  A quiet neighborhood to live and enjoy walks in would be best.    She is fantastic at playing fetch, dropping the ball right back into your hand. She has perfect house manners, And greets you with enormous zest when you get home. Strong, physically fit, experienced dog owners are recommended for this tall powerful girl. 
She is good with kids, but it takes her a long time to warm up to any new people she meets. For this reason, potential adopters need to be in the Johnson City, Tennessee area so that multiple meet and greets can occur before adoption takes place.
She is not recommended for a house that has frequent new visitors.
She walks good on a leash, loves car rides, cats not recommended due to breed. Contact irondawgs13@gmail.com for an application.

animal.description:
Dewey

Dewey is a very special boy who will need a very special adopter. He is about 6 years old and he came to us from a shelter in Louisiana. Coming from that part of the country, he was positive for heartworm, which we have treated. Unfortunately, he has a residual cough, and he may have heart issues as he gets older because he had a pretty heavy case of heartworms. Dewey loves the company of other dogs and he gets along with cats. We don’t know what his past was like, but he is pretty terrified of men. He is shy around women as well, but he warms up to them more than to the guys. The ideal home for Dewey would be an all-girl home with another dog. His adopter will need to be patient as he learns to trust people. We have seen dogs like Dewey come around, but it does take time and patience. Because of his heart issues and his fear around people especially men, Dewey’s adoption fee is our special needs fee of $75, knowing that the adopter will need to put time and effort into helping him to forget his past and move on to being a happy family member. If you would like to adopt Dewey, please got to our website and fill out an application. https://docs.google.com/.../1SnhudHYFJaPfZyCeKy36.../edit

This dog's adoption fee is a minimum $75.00 donation to help us save more dogs. Southern Arizona Beagle Rescue, SoAZBR is an all-volunteer group. One hundred percent of your donation is used for the care and treatment needy beagles. Your donation is 100% tax deductible, too.

We URGENTLY need fosters so we can help save more dogs.  If you can help, please contact us.

animal.description:
Carolina Boxer Rescue is a volunteer run, 501(c)3 non-profit organization. Our mission: To balance the health, safety, and welfare needs of Boxers in the Carolinas (and parts of Virginia and Georgia) by providing a loving and safe environment for stray, abused, impounded and owner surrendered dogs by placing them in foster homes and ultimately - forever homes.

________________________________________________________________________________________

Dog's Name: Chance

Dog's Approximate Age: 2-3 years

Gender: Male

Dog's Size: Medium (50lbs to 70lbs. as adult and healthy weight)

Dog's Weight: Don't know yet

Good with small dogs?: Yes

Good with big dogs?: Yes

Good with cats?: Don't know yet

Good with kids?: Don't know yet

Any medical issues?:

Crate trained?: Yes

House trained?: Yes

Heartworms?: Yes

11/2/20: Hi! I'm Chance and I'm new to CBR. Glad to be a part of this great organization. I've been with my foster mom for 5 days and she says I check off ALL the boxes! 1) Handsome boy, 2) No accidents inside, completely housebroken, 3) Friendly to all dogs and humans, 4) Crate trained- not particularly fond of it but will stay there when foster mom does errands, 5) Loves to ride in the car, 6) Walks well on a leash- love daily walks but do like to add in a bit of squirrel hunting (SO many in this neighborhood!), 7) Sleeps through the night and even has to be awakened in the morning, 8) Loves to play ball in the backyard and is GOOD at it!, 9) Proving to be a loyal and faithful companion- quiet and not hyper at all!

10/14/20: From Thor: I had to take this scary ride in a car to a new home. The strange woman was nice to me, pet me, gave me kisses and treats but I was very nervous in the car. This woman, she said she was my new foster mom, whatever that is, showed me where I would be staying. There was these two small dogs that look a lot like toys but the yell at me. I am very curious about them and want to get to know them but every time I get too close, one of the little ones yells at me. Hopefully in time they will grow to trust me and know I am a big happy teddy bear. I think my size makes them nervous. Foster mom says I'm settling in good and tells me all the time what a good boy I am. I like to eat to my dog food! I like treats sometimes, I am picky about them. I love to give big sloppy kisses and love to get hugs and pets in return! I have been in the new home for a little less than a week so I'm still getting used to it. I'll give you all an update later!

From Foster Mom: Thor is a gentle giant! Strong, mighty and majestic, he is! His fur is like velvet. He has so much love to give! He is very nervous when riding in cars. He seems to know some basic commands such as "sit" and "lie down" and "come". We are working on "stay". We are working on using the bathroom outside only. He is heartworm positive so he is getting treated for that now. He is kenneled when I am not home as he is a bit too curious at this time. He does not like going into the kennel but once in it, he is fine. He gets along with my male chihuahua just fine, my female chihuahua yells at him when he gets too close to her. He just stops and looks at her and then goes about his business. No signs of aggression at all. He loves his human and wants all the love and pets he can get!

_____________________________________________________________________________

Carolina Boxer Rescue is a volunteer run, 501(c)3 non-profit organization. Our mission: To balance the health, safety, and welfare needs of Boxers in the Carolinas (and parts of Virginia and Georgia) by providing a loving and safe environment for stray, abused, impounded and owner surrendered dogs by placing them in foster homes and ultimately - forever homes.

________________________________________________________________________________________

Dog's Name: Willa Rae

Dog's Approximate Age: 4-6 years

Gender: Female

Dog's Size: Pocket Boxer (under 50lbs as adult and healthy weight)

Dog's Weight: 47 pounds

Good with small dogs?: Don't know yet

Good with big dogs?: Yes

Good with cats?: No

Good with kids?: Yes, all ages

Any medical issues?:
Willa Rae has an ACL injury that requires surgery as well as being heartworm positive and will soon undergo treatment.

Crate trained?: Don't know yet

House trained?: Yes

Heartworms?: Yes

12/23/20: This update will be from Willa Rae's foster mommy because I have so many wonderful things to share about Willa Rae! I have said over and over to everyone I know that it would be so easy to keep her because she is perfect. But for that reason I know that she will be perfect for pretty much any family or any environment. She LOVES all people. She is content to just be with you and touching you. That is what makes her truly happy. if I am not sitting down and she cannot be in my lap or resting her head on my shoulder (which is her favorite thing to do) she goes to find her fur foster siblings and snuggles with them. She simply just wants to snuggle at all times. She is spunky in the cold weather outside and likes to run down the ramp into the yard and zoom underneath the deck and pop out on the other side and surprise her fur foster brother and sister. Just this week she finally barked and it is not near as deep sounding as I expected and its cute just like her! Willa Rae does not play with toys out in the open, instead she goes into my bedroom with her toys and plays in there. I come home from work in the afternoon and there is a pile of various toys in my bedroom along with my shoes. She does not destroy anything (except for a corner of the dog bed one day) and she likes the sound my shoes make when she tosses them in the air and they make a thud. She has the silliest little personality that shows more and more each day. The ONLY thing that I think Willa Rae should not have in her new home is cats or any type of small animals such as bunnies, birds, chickens. She has given some bunnies a run for their life in the yard and based on that behavior I would be concerned about her ability to co-mingle safely with small farm animals or small animals in general. I recently found her on the bed with my resident boxer and that was another first for her. She loves to come say good morning now when the alarm goes off and she greets me with gentle kisses. She is truly beautiful with the most soulful eyes, is a gentle girl with one of the sweetest personalities I have ever known, and is going to bring so much joy to someone's life when she is done with surgery and treatment and ready to go to her forever home.

11/9/20: Hi everyone! Foster Willa Rae here! I have all sorts of new things to share with you today! I have been in my foster home for just a little over 2 weeks and my life has changed so much. When I first got here I was so unsure and scared. Now, I know I am safe and loved and I seek out foster moms attention and I love to be loved. I give lots of snuggles and sweet chin kisses to make sure foster mom knows I'm grateful to be here. I have been living in my safe foster room and have not been allowed to meet the other doggies here except through the baby gate but that all changed yesterday! The nice lady who pulled me from the shelter came to visit yesterday and I was so happy to see her again. I made sure she knew I remembered her and gave her kisses. Then today foster mom said it was time to meet my foster brother and foster sister. I was a little nervous but we all sniffed each other, walked in the yard together, and I showed foster mommy being with everyone in the living room was just what I needed! I snuggled up on the couch with foster mom and I am just so happy now. Foster mom says feeling secure and loved looks good on me! It's a secret, but I'm a little smitten with my foster brother....I really like him, so I would do fine with a very mellow fur brother or fur sister in my forever home as long as we move slow like we did here. I won't be ready for a little while to come live with you because foster mom says I have worms in my heart that are making me cough and I have to have surgery to fix my leg. Don't worry though....I'm not in pain and I know soon I'll be feeling much better. My soft bed, tons of treats, a soft couch, and foster mom snuggles along with my new friends here are making me very happy. I'll update again soon....sweet kisses and tail wags....Willa Rae

10/26/20: Hi everyone. My name is Willa. I was at the shelter for 10 days waiting to see if anyone would claim me, and when no one did, this really nice lady I had never met before came to pick me up. Even though I did not know her I was so glad to get out of there and I gave her lots of sweet gentle kisses to tell her thank you. Then she drove me straight to this place called the vet because I needed to immediately get taken care of because my right hind leg was hurting and I hop because it hurts to put it on the ground. They were very nice to me there, but it sounds like I hurt my leg pretty good and they said its something called an ACL injury. I was able to get back in the care with the nice lady that picked me up. She took me to this house with a really nice soft bed and blankets. She told me she had to leave, but that my new foster mommy would be there soon and she would take care of me. I waited patiently for a few hours in my bed and then this other lady came home to meet me. She told me that she was going to be my mommy for a while because I need some love and care for a bit while we get my leg fixed and get rid of these worms in my heart. My temporary mommy gives me lots of snuggles and pets and I love that, and she also gives me tons of treats and a really good dinner every night. She says I am the sweetest girl. I am a very shy girl and I am still not ready to meet the other dogs in the house. The girl barks at me and the boy stands outside my room whining. We all see eachother through the gate but I am much more comfortable in my room for now away from them. Foster mom puts them behind the gate sometimes and we hang out in the living room and she gives me lots of love. Do you notice something? I REALLY enjoy foster mom and love. I got a bath on Saturday. I was a little bit scared, but afterwards I sure did feel better. It seems like foster mom snuggles me a little tighter now that I smell good. Guess what else? I have the most perfect potty manners of any foster that has ever been here. Foster Mom told me so. She said I am the best girl and she appreciates me making it easy on her. I love belly rubs too, so if you enjoy a sweet little girl that will give you the cutest little spotted belly to rub....its me....Willa. I can't wait to get all better and meet you!

From Foster Mom: Willa is simply the sweetest! She wags her tail at me whenever I talk to her and she just loves to lean into me for attention, or lay her head in my lap. When she arrived at my home her eyes were so sad and it just broke my heart. I can tell at some point in her life she was loved and an indoor pet and she truly does have perfect house manners. She is starting to get her glimmer and happiness back in her eyes and does not seem so scared or confused. Next steps for Willa will be ACL repair and heartworm treatment. This sweet girl will then be ready for her forever family.

_____________________________________________________________________________

Come visit carolinaboxerrescue.org to learn more about me and see more pictures. Learn about our adoption process too!

_____________________________________________________________________________

You can make an appointment to meet available dogs at our ADOPTION CENTER by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet and available cats at MEOW PALACE by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet1.

For animals in FOSTER homes, please submit an online application and an adoption team will reply with next steps. We thank you for your patience as we work to keep saving lives during this difficult time.

PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE: http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/

Meet Dan the man! Okay, Dan the dog, but a cute dog at that. This 3 year old, staffordshire terrier is a handsome fella with a beautiful brindle pattern. Taco Dan is a sweet boy who is a sucker for the ladies! Prior to coming to Homeward Trails, he was picked up as a stray in Fayette County, WV. Relationship is the key to Taco Dan's success in a home. Since your new relationship is so important to him, he only asks that you plan on spending a few playdates and training sessions with him before taking him home. Taco Dan needs to be adopted by an adult only house hold. If you believe you can provide that for our amazing boy, please submit an application to meet him at our adoption center soon!

Adoption Coordinator: Adoption Center
Location: Adoption Center
The adoption fee for this dog is $475. This fee includes spay/neuter and microchip.

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

We also provide free online workshop with a professional dog trainer at Fur-Get Me Not within the first 30 days of adopting - just for HT adopters in the Arlington/Alexandria/Falls Church/DC area. Start your new dog out on the right foot with this valuable, expert guidance FREE!

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program

I HAVE A SPONSORED ADOPTION - $0 TO ADOPT ME!  

Dr. Dennis Boelter owned Akron (Ohio) Animal Clinic and Metropolitan Veterinary Hospital (Akron, Ohio) for 43 years. A tragic accident took Dr. Boelter’s life in December of 2017.  As a tribute to Dr. Boelter, a very special Canine Castaways supporter will pay the adoption fee for this dog's adoption..   For more information on "Boelter's Bunch", please visit http://www.caninecastaways.org/special-adoption-programs

Please consider opening your heart and home to a senior dog!

IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THE FIRST STEP IS TO FILL OUT AN ADOPTION APPLICATION ON OUR WEBSITE AT:  
https://www.caninecastaways.org/adoption-application
IF A PET IS LISTED THEN THEY ARE AVAILABLE - WE KEEP OUR LISTINGS UP TO DATE AND REMOVE AS SOON AS ADOPTED.

NAME:  Mabel
BREED:  Chihuahua
SEX: female
COLOR:  cream/tan
AGE:  12 years plus 
WEIGHT:  7.5 lbs



FOSTERED BY:   Vicki
LOCATED IN:  Pt. Charlotte


NOTES FROM FOSTER FAMILY:

Mabel just moved to her foster home a week or so ago - here is what her foster mom had to say about her:  Mabel has picked my bathroom as her bedroom, she stays in there most of the time and seems like a safe spot for her.  When she's up she does follow me everywhere but if I'm sitting she still walks around and doesn't seem to want to settle anywhere but in her "bedroom".  

She loves to eat and is first in line when I go in the kitchen.  No accidents, seems to have good potty habits.  She is getting pretty good about coming in without picking her up but I still need to carry her out.  Sleeps really good at night and usually have to wake her in the morning whether it's 6:00 a.m. or 8:00 a.m. and she does sleep a lot.  

There are hearing and vision issues but still hard to tell how much but her pacing has changed and it seemed like she was mapping the first few days and now just walks around.   Got a little tail wag the other day, will tolerate a little stroking on her back but still is nervous about it.  I'm just letting her do her thing even though I want to love on her so much.  So far so good.  Hopefully in time she will seek attention, she is just such a sweetie. 

Mabel did come to us with mammary masses which have been removed.  They were were NOT cancerous but there is always a possibility she could have another pop up down the road.  At this time it is not an issue but it is something we want a potential adopter to be aware of.  

Due to COVID-19 we are a little more limited on volunteers and the availability (and safety) of home visits.   Local applications are given first priority and some out of town areas will not be able to be processed.

At this time, we will only be able to process applications that have an excellent current vet history.  If you haven’t had a pet or verifiable vet history we will not be able to process your application.   

If you are interested in adopting please complete our Adoption Application by copying and pasting the following link into your web browser: http://www.caninecastaways.org/adoption-application

For a full list of dogs we currently have for adoption use this link:  https://www.caninecastaways.org/adoptable-dogs


MEDICAL INFO: 
The following has been or will be done for this dog...
- Basic Exam by Veterinarian
- Spayed or Neutered
- Heartworm Tested
- Placed on heartworm preventive
- Geriatric Bloodwork
- Microchipped
- Intestinal Parasite Exam and medication
- Vaccinations
- Placed on flea preventive
- Dental, if needed


ADOPTION DONATION: 
$150 

This adoption donation helps to cover the vet expenses for this dog including heartworm preventive which is dispensed at the initial vet visit and then goes with the dog at adoption. All vet records will be provided to adopter.


Visit us at www.caninecastaways.org

Orion was surrendered to Save A Pet by a good samaritan who took him in from a less than ideal situation. While we do not know the details of his previous life, we do know that he was not very well taken care of. That has not stopped Orion from being a wonderful little happy boy. Orion quickly won over the hearts of the shelter staff. He can be a timid and shy little pup but quickly warms up to everyone he meets! He is currently working on leash skills, it's evident that he's never been walked on one until now... he will catch on though! 
Orion plays great with the other young dogs at Save A Pet and would love a home with another furry brother or sister to show him the ropes. He is definitely more of a submissive type and could benefit from a confident dog to learn from. 
Orion weighs about 35 pounds and is approximately 5 months old with a birthday around mid June 2020.
If you are interested in learning more about Orion, please call the Save A Pet shelter at 478-994-3882. You may also send a direct message via Petfinder.com

animal.description: For a young boy, Dracula is already quite a collector - of toys! He has a horde of toys, and is always looking for a new one to add. Of course, he loves playing with them just as much as he loves his people - and all humans he meets. This friendly boy is disabled. His spine was injured, causing the loss of use of his back legs. But that hasn't slowed down his playfulness. He loves being petted and snuggled, and he wiggles when his humans come close. He will scoot himself right over to be held and cuddled. As an active, curious boy, he loves being outside, scooting around freely with his front legs to see everything in the outdoor world, and chewing sticks to his heart's content. He'll pull himself halfway across the yard to grab a new stick when he already has one to chew - so cute! He's a smart boy, eager to learn, and listens to corrections well. He sleeps all night in his crate. He might also be fitted for a wheelchair as he matures. Dracula's disability causes incontinence, so he needs adopters who will be gentle and loving with him, help with his bladder and bowel control, and are always willing to patiently change his diapers. He'll reward them with so much love. Come meet this survivor!

A LITTLE BIT ABOUT ME! 
11/8/20: HELLO, MY NAME IS ELMER AND I AM A BUNDLE OF LOVE AND A TOTAL CUDDLE BUG! I NEED A FOREVER HOME WHERE I CAN BE LOVED AND SAFE.  
I APPEAR TO BE A PUGGLE OR TERRIER MIX AND AM ABOUT 18 POUNDS AND APPROXIMATELY 1. 5  YEARS OLD. 
I LOVE LOVE LOVE OTHER DOGS AND AS CAN SEE IN MY PICS AM ALWAYS CUDDLING WITH ALL SIZES OF DOGS & CATS TOO. 
I ALSO LOVE TO CHEW ON MY FOSTER MOM'S HANDS. DON'T HURT HER JUST LOVE TO DO IT.
I WAS A STRAY SO IT WILL BE IMPORTANT TO FIND A HOME WHERE I CAN'T SLIP OUT THE DOOR AND GET LOST AGAIN.  
I ALSO AM LOOKING FOR A SPECIAL HOME WHO WILL KEEP ME CURRENT ON MY SEIZURE MEDS. THEY CAN BE PRETTY SCARY TO WATCH BUT THE MEDS ARE WORKING ONCE MY VET GOT THE RIGHT DOSE FIGURED OUT.

animal.description:
Dell is a 6 year old Border Collie mix who's looking for his forever family. Typical for his breed, Dell needs an active family and some "work" to keep his brain entertained. He'll retrieve a ball all.day.long. He loves walks and is doing much better on a leash. He's extremely smart & learns new tricks and behaviors quickly. He's a cuddle bug and loves belly rubs.

Dell has some anxiety issues and can be whiny if not given enough exercise or when overly excited. He does need medication for storms to keep him calm.

He's crate trained and house broken. He's dog selective and prefers non dominant dogs. He's living with cats now but is not a fan..

Dell LOVES kids but will "herd" smaller kids by nipping at their heels. Dell needs a home without small children.

Dell is a silly boy who always keeps us laughing with his weird sleeping and lounging positions. He's affectionate and loves to be snuggled.

Are you active and looking for a new buddy? Dell could be your guy! Apply today at Needy Paws.

Dell

6 years old,

50 lbs

Black / white / brown patches (one brown eyebrow!)

House Trained

Crate Trained

Needs a fenced yard

Can be only dog or a slow intro to a new sibling

Has storm anxiety and needs medication

If you are interested in meeting Dell, complete the Adoption Application on our website at www.NeedyPaws.org and we will contact you. Adopters must live within an hour's drive of St. Louis, MO.

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Straight out of Detroit comes another beautiful dog in need of a new home! A Buster foster mom spotted Shuri across from her home and after speaking to some other neighbors she learned the pup was abandoned. Well, our foster mom did what any Buster volunteer would do, grabbed a leash scooped her up, and got her inside and safe. Her new name is Shuri, and besides some fleas and being underweight, she is decent shape. She is still getting used to being inside and has been calm, quiet, and easy going. She gets nervous when left alone outside, as we would expect. However, she is VERY good in her crate and relaxes quickly. She appears to ignore other dogs; however, we won't know for sure until she has a chance to settle down. Her foster mom thinks she will be medium to high energy level and will be around 80 pounds, once she gets back to her proper weight. For that reason, we recommend no young kids.Notes from her Foster mom: Shuri is an amazing girl! She loves every person she meets. She's great in the house, has never chewed something or gotten into things. She is fully housebroken and is great in her crate with things to keep her mind busy. This high energy girl would love an active home. Her favorite thing is to play and run, but when playtime is over she is the best cuddler! She even knows to wait for an invitation to get on the couch. Shuri is incredibly smart and learns really quickly. Check out the video of her starting to learn agility. This is less than a week into practice! More obstacles are coming soon, we'll add more videos as she learns. In addition to agility, Shuri is learning obedience and can 'sit', 'down', 'wait', 'stay', 'off', 'drop', and 'leave it'. She walks well on a leash, but does react to other animals. She would be great for an experienced owner that loves to teach their dog new things as she is eager to please. Unfortunately, before Shuri was abandoned by her family on the streets in Detroit, it seems like she had a pretty sheltered life. As a young girl gets very excited in new environments. We are working on exposing her to different situations and teaching her appropriate reactions, but she will need continual practice. She's learning the joy of different toys and to be a happy confident dog in various situations. :)Shuri would prefer a home without small animals, but may do well with a stable male dog with very slow introductions. She can't wait to meet with her perfect forever family!

She is getting better every single day on leash. She is a master of 'sit' and 'paw', and is excited to master 'lay down' and 'fetch'. Describe cuddling behavior/affection level: Acorn's favorite thing to do is cuddle and give kisses. She especially appreciates kisses between her ears, and she will happily return the favor. Describe play behavior and favorite toys: Acorn loves to play with her toys! Acorn enjoys toys like Kongs and puzzle toys that keep her motivated and stimulated. She also likes a nice rope to chew on. Describe Acorn's activity level: Acorn is a medium-high energy dog. She is athletic- a fast sprinter, a strong jumper, and she's even got some goofy dance moves. However, she tires quickly, she is calm around the house, and will gladly focus her energy towards some intellectual exercise. What are the best adjectives to describe Acorn? 1) Loving- she eagerly gives us kisses and cuddles, and shows excitement when we come home 2) Intelligent- she has the ability to quickly learn new tricks! 3) Emotionally intelligent- she understands when we need space, are feeling frustrated, or when we're too tired to play. Any cute behaviors? One of Acorn's cutest behaviors is that she will walk between your legs just to receive pets. Ask Acorn's volunteer advocate, Megan, about her: meg1995.mw@gmail.com ACORN IS ENROLLED IN THE GOOD DOG PROJECT AT PACC - Read a message from her case manager here: tinyurl.com/gdpmessage - Ask her case manager about him: rachel.jones@pima.gov

Due to the rising costs of veterinary care, premium holistic dog food, gasoline prices, and boarding fees, which are paid for out of our own pockets, we recently were forced to raise our fees. We are not funded by anyone - adoption fees help to offset only a part of our cost of getting the dog ready for adoption. All dogs > 6 months are vetted, up to date on vaccinations, spayed/neutered, microchipped, heartworm tested, wormed and have a goody starter bag. Puppies

animal.description:
Meet Ranger!

Ranger came to us from the Humane Society of Imperial Valley. He is approximately 8 years old and weighs 70 lbs. Ranger gets along well with other dogs in our play yards, and he passed the cat test, too. As for people, Ranger LOVES everyone and even thinks he's a lap dog!

Ranger enjoys going on our weekly Frosted Fakers hikes, and he is the perfect example of a Frosted Faker, a senior dog who acts younger than his years. At only 8 years old, Ranger is on the young end of being a senior, and he's a great walking buddy. Volunteers have taken him running, and he's up for it! Ranger would be a great fit for an active family.

Ranger went on a two week Frosted Fling for the holidays, and his Fling family decided to foster him until he's adopted! His now-Foster Mom shared what they've learned about this special boy:

"Ranger has been living with us for one month! We have learned so much about this love bug:

*Ranger is a perfect gentleman in the car, he likes to ride in the back and take a nap

*Ranger likes to move his body, either hiking or walking around the neighborhood. I would call his energy moderate. We started out with 5-6 miles a day to get the worries out, he would be great with a 2-3 miles a day when he's comfortable in a home. He is a great running partner, too!

*Ranger met our neighbor's small black doggo on a leash and did great with him.

*Ranger is 100% potty trained. He can hold it for a work day, no problem!

*Ranger sleeps like a champ in his crate for 8-10 hours with his blankies. He snores, but it soothes me right to sleep.

*Ranger loves being touched. If he thinks you are going to love on him, he will give you his belly.

*Ranger started off as a picky eater, but as he's gotten more at home he's been broadening his food repertoire, but raw veggies are still a no go. He really loves chicken or beef stock on his food and his coat is getting silky!

* Ranger sings to you when he is excited about an upcoming activity. It's music, y'all!

*Ranger adores being close to his person and if he can't be close to you, he will settle nearby. He is ALWAAYS up for lounging in the couch (doggo beds work too!!)

* Ranger would be a great body guard (does anyone know about an open position?). I feel like a movie star walking about the house. He has got to know what I am working on and if I need any assistance.

Ranger DESERVES a loving home. His people are out there. Until then, I will snuggle Ranger's big head and love on him."

If you're looking for a fun and sweet buddy, apply to meet Ranger: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm.

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees, and we help with medical costs!

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

Updated: 1/30/21 KG

animal.description:
Link is a 4 year old 50lb pit mix, who was rescued from a rural high-kill shelter, and is now so happy to be in a home setting. He is very sweet and loving and just wants all your attention! He is house trained and kennel trained, and is very treat motivated. He needs a little bit of work on his greeting manners, as he gets very excited to see you! But he is also happy to curl up and quietly nap once he’s gotten in some playtime. He is very smart and wants to please, so he is picking up basic commands and walking on a leash quickly!
He would do well with another dog that is not too dominant, when introduced properly. He would do better in a home without cats. He is neutered, and up to date on all his shots. He has tested positive for heartworm, has already started treatment and is so excited to begin his happy forever with you! 

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2020 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

animal.description:
Whisper is a sweet, very chill Boxer mix (possible Rottweiler). He has an old soul and a gentle spirit. He loves going on walks through the neighborhood and is also a great jogging buddy in the mornings. He’s great with apartment living and perfectly content chilling out while you work or watch movies at home, and he’s working on new commands. At the dog park he’s the most behaved dog (never barks, never jumps) and is gentle and happy to play with dogs of all sizes. He also quickly adjusts to new surroundings and is house trained and crate trained. He loves belly rubs at night before bedtime. Whisper would be perfect for a loving home or family looking for a sweet companion.


You may read more about our adoption policies and procedures at www.truenorthrescue.org. Please submit a complete application on our website - meet and greets are only scheduled with approved applicants. Please be sure to answer every question as thoughtfully as you can, this will help your chances. Incomplete applications will not be reviewed, and we unfortunately can not contact all applicants to inquire about missing information.

Do not email through Petfinder because we won't be able to answer. Please email adopt.truenorthrescue@gmail.com to check on the status of your application. All applications can take anywhere from 24-72 hours to be processed and only approved applicants will be contacted.

If a dog is listed here on Petfinder, they are still available. Please don't email just to ask if they're available - they are! With the high volume of emails we receive daily, it is not guaranteed that we can reply to every inquiry. As a fully volunteer run rescue, we make every effort to reply in a timely fashion, but please allow 24-48 hours for a response.

We strive to have accurate and up to date bios, and regularly check in with our fosters to ensure we are providing the most relevant information. If there is no mention of a health or behavioral concern, then it means we have not been informed of one!

animal.description:
Roni is a high energy 1 year old mixed pup of hidden origins who loves to run and play.  She is spayed, up to date on vaccines, micro chipped and has undergone heart worm treatment (hence the stripes on her back where she got her injections).  She is now ready to find her forever home.  

Roni would do best in a home with a physically fenced yard, kids who are 8 years old or older and no other small pets/ animals.  She likes to be the alpha and would do best in a home with a bigger dog.  She is about 40 lbs currently.  She has a great personality with people and just loves attention.  She can be a vocal dog, so she is not suitable for apartments, townhomes or condos.

She is in our indoor/outdoor kennels but does appear to have some house-training experience, but may need some refreshers when coming into a new home.  All dogs need time to decompress, get familiar and comfortable with new people, new routine and that just takes time.  Since she is still young, we would suggest either crate training for when you are not home until she gets a bit older and more accustomed to being in a home.

If you think you can be that family for Roni, please fill out our adoption application on our website at www.safehaventn.com .  We are happy to set up a meet and greet for the approved application.  Her adoption fee is $150.00 and she is located in Cookeville, TN.

animal.description:
Apple (female, about 2 years old) and Andy (male, about 1 year old) are a very sweet, bonded pair, born in separate litters to the same mother. They are calm and gentle; they love cuddling together and can be walked together.

Apple and Andy were rescued from an abandoned house. Apple had a face full of porcupine quills, and Andy had a broken hind leg that could not be repaired and required amputation. They must be adopted together. 

Andy is shy and will need to be with people who are patient with him. Apple is his protector, and Andy is braver when she is with him. They have excellent house manners. They chew on their toys and leave the people shoes alone! They like to sit on the couch and look out the window. While they quietly watch the squirrel who lives outside through the window, they are not as tolerant of the rabbits down the street and will probably do best in a home without cats.

Their foster mom reports that they were very good about not pulling on their leashes when they first came to her but have started pulling a bit. They will probably need and respond well to a positive training program. They seem to be curious and happy to see other dogs when they’re out walking.

This loving pair had a tough start but are ready for a forever home where they are loved and loving. They will give you a rewarding relationship and lots of snuggles!

Apple and Andy’s adoption fee includes spay/neuter, basic vaccinations, rabies vaccination, and heartworm tested negative.

Apple and Andy’s adoption fee includes spay/neuter, basic vaccinations, rabies vaccination, and heartworm tested negative.

https://forms.gle/5eSBjHrWv7pTEEzUA

animal.description:
Annie is another long term resident at the Shelter.  She came to the shelter at 12 weeks, in August 2017, and is still waiting for her Forever Home.  She knows that the right home is also waiting for her... we just need to get you together!

We do not recommend children and it is unknown if he is good with cats.  Ziggy does like other dogs and living with another confident dog might be good for him.  We have been taking our time with placing Ziggy into the right home.  Email us today if you think you'd be a good fit for our special guy.

I'm GARBO!  And I'm not a perfect pointer!  I belong to Southwest English Setter Rescue.  If you're interested in me please go to http://www.swesr.org/Apply-to-Adopt.html and fill out their application.  Do not respond electronically to this post because it will go to Utah's Perfect Pointers.

I was turned into the shelter by my family because they said I was "guarding" my toys, etc. from their other dog.  For goodness sakes, I'm a kid and I didn't know any better.  My approx. DOB is 2/13/2020 so I still have a lot of learning ahead of me.  I was very good when I was visiting at Casa UPP.  I would have liked to be a bossy little girl, but UPP rescue lady told me that was her job and I could "stand down".  I decided to let her be the boss.

I played well with the other dogs for the week I was at Casa UPP.  I wasn't particularly trustworthy with the cats.  I really need a male dog in my new home to help me become a respectable adult.  I also need humans who know my breed and particularly my age.  Teenagers are a lot of work!

I have a lovely coat that doesn't tangle but will benefit from brushing.  It's also nice and calming for me so it's a nice way for me to spend some quiet time with my favorite people.

I'm going to grow up to be a wonderful dog in the right home.  If you're interested in me please contact http://www.swesr.org/Apply-to-Adopt.html

animal.description:
Description of pet
Our adoption area is limited to UT, NV, ID, OR, WA and MT with a home visit. If you are outside of this area please do a search for your local GSP/GWP/Pointer rescue group.

--------

I'm PIXEL! And I'm totally beautiful little girl.  I came to UPP from a rural shelter with a shattered right elbow.  X-rays showed that it was an old injury (a couple of months) so it couldn't be repaired.  I had a drastic amputation right to my shoulder and wouldn't you know it........... the next day I was ready to go out and run in the yard.  My rescue lady is trying to keep me quiet but that's not a particularly easy task for a young, mostly GSP girl.  I may be purebred but my ears are a little short and set a little high on my head so my rescue lady isn't sure.  I'm at least 90% GSP, particularly when it comes to my energy level.  My approx. DOB is 2/24/2020 so I'm the perfect age to be a great companion for many years.

I'm becoming house trained (mostly). I love my people and being outside with the other dogs. I need a home with a well-trained, well-socialized male dog who can show me the ropes in my new home and help me wear off some of my excess energy.  I'm not a good "starter" dog.

---------

GENERAL APPLICATION NOTES:

We strongly urge adopters to consider a male canine companion if they already have a female GSP/GWP. We get asked several times a year to take in one member of a 2-female GSP family because there are control issues between their girls that result in pretty ferocious fights. Interestingly that never happens among males. Go figure.

Dogs under 2 years of age need to go to a home with another well-socialized canine companion of a similar size (when grown) and within a few years of the pup’s age. This is how they maintain and continue their learning/socialization process. Socialization outside the home is important but doesn’t replace the in-home learning that is so important as the pup ages. https://www.facebook.com/ UtahsPerfectPointers/posts/ 1460968517254816

Most older dogs aren’t interested in having a puppy incessantly chewing on it and demanding attention. If you live outside of the Salt Lake area and are sure that your older dog just loves puppies, please arrange a visit at your home with a 2-4 month old pup for a couple of hours and make sure that your older dog feels the same way about this that you do. Please video the interactions and send it to us.

Just a word of caution........ most pointer types need jobs. Otherwise they're not good pets. They need to be able to utilize their brains and no amount of exercise without a "work" or "thinking" component is adequate. The job doesn't need to be hunting. But it does need to be something that satisfies their genetic predispositions - nose work, agility, tracking, dock diving, etc. The job cannot just be obedience. If they can't use their innate senses they're just never going to be the dog you want for the next 15 years.

A physical fence is required for most of our dogs.

As far as other breeds go, the pointers are generally good with most other breeds with the exception of the Arctic breeds and bulldogs. I'm not sure why, but if there's ever an altercation in daycare between a UPP dog and another dog, it's generally one of those two breeds. It may be the difference in energy levels. It may be some ancient behavior we know nothing about...... Not sure.

Utah's Perfect Pointers is a very small rescue group and doesn't have the resources to adopt to states except for the ones noted above. If you are interested in adopting a GSP please contact the closest groups below. Keep in mind that not all of their dogs may be listed on their sites.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

GRUMPY OLD MAN SEEKS ROOMMATE: 9 year old 22 lb. pug/terrier mix ARCHIE is seeking a furever home where he WON'T be showered with affection. This guy has a a cattitude - he will let you know when he wants attention and belly rubs - and when he's had enough. Archie is a 4 on the floor guy - he needs to keep all 4 paws on the ground. If you let him take possession of the sofa or the bed he will and he doesn't like to share. Little Archie has plenty of energy and does like to play. He loooves car rides and likes to go for walks. He's not going to shower you with kisses but he's perfectly content to be your companion. He's completely housebroken and does not need to be crated, which is good because he doesn't like crates. Archie lost his furever home when his person passed away, and we're having a tough time finding a home that's the right fit for his independent personality. People expect him to be a cuddly lapdog, but he's just not that dog. We know the right home is out there for this guy, and we're hoping this very honest description will help us find the right home for Archie. If you'd like to meet Archie, please fill out a foster-to-adopt application at dreamhouserescue.org.

All of our fully-vetted adoptable dogs go to prospective homes for a one-week trial foster-to-adopt period to make sure the dog and home are the right fit before an adoption is finalized. We only adopt dogs into homes where all current pets are spayed/neutered and current on vaccines and heartworm and flea and tick prevention. We do check veterinary references to make sure adopters are compliant with standard veterinary care.

animal.description:
Pixie Stix is a beautiful Labrador - Airedale mix puppy with beautiful blue eyes! Wow!  What an unusual beauty!  She was born 9-19, currently weighs about 18 lbs and will grow to be a medium sized to large dog.  Mom is Sharla, an Airedale mix.  Daddy was apparently a traveling salesman.  Pixie Stix is a bundle of normal puppy energy and affection.  Pixie Stix’s foster mom says she is curious, adventurous and loves to “talk.”She also has adorable blue eyes. 

OWR will cover the costs of all puppy shots and spay. Adopters must live in the Tulsa or OKC area so that the pups can be treated at one of our partner vets. 

If you’d like to meet Pixie Stix, the first step is to complete and submit an adoption application on our okwestierescue.com website and we’ll get the process started. 

Please allow 1-2 weeks to finish processing your application, but please know our volunteers are working hard on it. 

Pixie Stix’s adoption fee is $300 and is tax deductible. 

NOTE: You must complete and submit an application and be approved to adopt prior to being able to meet the dog.  The requested tax-deductible adoption donation is $400 for our puppies, $300 for up to age 7 and $150 for ages 8 and older.

We do not ship our pets.  Be prepared to travel to Tulsa, OK, or Oklahoma City, OK, or the location where this dog is fostered to pick up your dog in person if your application is approved.  Once you are approved, you may adopt any of our dogs that is a good fit. 

We are a non-profit organization that spends our adoption fees and donations on vaccinations, surgeries, various medical tests, medicines, food and supplies needed by our dogs. Our fees do not cover the overall expenses incurred by the care of our dogs, but they do help defray the costs involved.  We thank you for your support. 

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always try to select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dog’s needs and try to find the best match for both dog and human. 
We leave a dog’s profile online until either it has been adopted, has received several applications, or is not able to be adopted for some reason.

Pete is a curious, young guy who is looking for that forever kind of love! When Pete came into our care as a stray, he was shy, nervous, and reserved. For the past several months, he has been growing and learning in a loving foster home. Pete is a smart guy who is eager to learn. He enjoys tasty snacks and would benefit from enrichment activities like solving food puzzles or using his keen brain to learn new skills. He already knows ''sit'' and ''shake''! Pete enjoys the company of other dogs and would do best sharing his forever home with a social, canine friend.

Because of Pete's history and behavior, his new home must include the following:
- Must be an indoor pet
- Never left outdoors unattended, or on a tie out or in a kennel
- Secure fenced-in yard
- No children under the age of 12 years old

Pete may be best suited as a homebody type of dog and will likely not be well suited to many adventures away from the home. Given time, patience, love, and understanding, Pete will make a fun, loving canine companion for the right family or individual.

animal.description:
Sumari is a truly special dog in need of a special home. Sumari has a history of being a shy, fearful dog but in the time that he has been in our care, he has experienced tremendous growth and progress. Given time, patience, and understanding, Sumari can learn to trust and enjoy humans. Once he is comfortable, Sumari absolutely shines. He loves playing with stuffed toys and tossing them in the air! He enjoys using his keen brain to solve food puzzles and learn new skills. Most of all, Sumari is our ''helper dog'' and has been given a job at the shelter: to help us gauge the behavior of all incoming dogs. Sumari adapts to whatever any new dogs need, whether it is a playmate, or some space. He has been instrumental in helping many new dogs feel at ease in the shelter environment. Although Sumari has thrived in many ways, he can still be unsure in certain situations.

Due to his shyness, there are specific requirements for Sumari's forever home:
-Must be an indoor pet
-No children under the age of 10 years old
-Securely fenced in yard - but not to be left outdoors unattended, on a tie out, or in a kennel
-Another social, friendly dog in the home preferred

Sumari has an unknown history with cats. Sumari may be best suited as a homebody type of dog and will likely not be well suited to many adventures away from the home. Given time, patience, love, and understanding, Sumari will make an incredible companion for the right family or individual.

animal.description:
Kevin is an all around good dog who deserves the chance at a good life. Kevin came into our care as a stray so his history is a mystery, but since then, we have enjoyed getting to know Kevin! Kevin enjoys the simple things in life: good meals, comfortable beds, and enthusiastic attention from caring humans (he loves when you say hi to him!) He's an easy-going low maintenance kind of dog, but don't let his mellow demeanor fool you! Kevin is a smart boy who loves to give ''high five'' and will likely prove that old dogs CAN learn new tricks! Kevin can be a little unsure about his dog friends and may do best in a home without any other pets. Kevin is currently living in a wonderful foster home, on a farm, where he has been able to meet other animal friends of many different species. We are happy to share that Kevin doesn't have any interest in chasing chickens and may be able to safely live around chickens! He is very curious about his foster family's cat, however, but the cat is not interested in playing with Kevin. Kevin has also met horses. His foster mom describes him as having the most wonderful energy - ''he is curious about everything, and obsessive over nothing.''

Recently, Kevin was diagnosed with cancer. We're so hoping that Kevin will find a family that will shower him with love and care (and snacks!) Kevin deserves to know a comfortable life in a loving forever home.

Our adoption area is limited to UT, NV, ID, OR, WA and MT with a home visit. If you are outside of this area please do a search for your local GSP/GWP/Pointer rescue group.

--------

I'm COLTER!  I'm a stunning, active guy.  I'm a nice, solid boy, about 50 lbs and 24" at my withers.  My approx. DOB is 4/30/2019 so I'm still pretty young and very, very active.

I'm house trained and will whine/run to the door when I needs to potty. I sort of know: Sit, (lay)Down, Shake, Kennel, Drop it, Get it, and Off. My recall is NOT good and I'm not particularly happy about "staying".

I spend my outdoor time chasing birds, playing with the other dogs, or lounging on the yard furniture. I also like to have toys to play with - nylabones, soccer balls, etc.  I'm pretty good in my crate at night.  I'm still a counter surfer so everyone's happier if I have some control on my wandering when my people are asleep.
   
I like to dig so it's a good idea not to leave me outside unattended.  I totally love playing tug-of-war and chewing on nylon bones. I can't have fluffy toys because I shred them or try to eat the whole thing. Additional talents include  swallowing socks or small fabric items comparable to socks.

I'm great with adults and OK around children if I'm monitored.  I'm good with  other dogs with the exception of Arctic breeds. I lived with a hound mix, golden retriever mix, and a catahoula mix in my past life and I'm doing great with the other dogs and handlers in daycare.  

---------

GENERAL APPLICATION NOTES:

We strongly urge adopters to consider a male canine companion if they already have a female GSP/GWP. We get asked several times a year to take in one member of a 2-female GSP family because there are control issues between their girls that result in pretty ferocious fights. Interestingly that never happens among males. Go figure.

Dogs under 2 years of age need to go to a home with another well-socialized canine companion of a similar size (when grown) and within a few years of the pup’s age. This is how they maintain and continue their learning/socialization process. Socialization outside the home is important but doesn’t replace the in-home learning that is so important as the pup ages. https://www.facebook.com/ UtahsPerfectPointers/posts/ 1460968517254816

Most older dogs aren’t interested in having a puppy incessantly chewing on it and demanding attention. If you live outside of the Salt Lake area and are sure that your older dog just loves puppies, please arrange a visit at your home with a 2-4 month old pup for a couple of hours and make sure that your older dog feels the same way about this that you do. Please video the interactions and send it to us.

Just a word of caution........ most pointer types need jobs. Otherwise they're not good pets. They need to be able to utilize their brains and no amount of exercise without a "work" or "thinking" component is adequate. The job doesn't need to be hunting. But it does need to be something that satisfies their genetic predispositions - nose work, agility, tracking, dock diving, etc. The job cannot just be obedience. If they can't use their innate senses they're just never going to be the dog you want for the next 15 years.

A physical fence is required for most of our dogs.

As far as other breeds go, the pointers are generally good with most other breeds with the exception of the Arctic breeds and bulldogs. I'm not sure why, but if there's ever an altercation in daycare between a UPP dog and another dog, it's generally one of those two breeds. It may be the difference in energy levels. It may be some ancient behavior we know nothing about...... Not sure.

Utah's Perfect Pointers is a very small rescue group and doesn't have the resources to adopt to states except for the ones noted above. If you are interested in adopting a GSP please contact the closest groups below. Keep in mind that not all of their dogs may be listed on their sites.

animal.description:
Candy Corn is a beautiful Labrador - Airedale mix puppy. She was born 9-19, currently weighs about 18 lbs and will grow to be a medium sized to large dog.  Mom is Sharla, an Airedale mix.  Daddy was apparently a traveling salesman.  Candy Corn is a bundle of normal puppy energy and affection.  Her foster mom says she is as sweet as her name!  Candy Corn has one blue eye and one brown, which makes her pretty special. 

OWR will cover the costs of all puppy shots and spay. Adopters must live in the Tulsa or OKC area so that the pups can be treated at one of our partner vets. 

If you’d like to meet Candy Corn, the first step is to complete and submit an adoption application on our okwestierescue.com website and we’ll get the process started. 

Please allow 1-2 weeks to finish processing your application, but please know our volunteers are working hard on it. 

Candy Corn’s adoption fee is $300 and is tax deductible. 

NOTE: You must complete and submit an application and be approved to adopt prior to being able to meet the dog.  The requested tax-deductible adoption donation is $400 for our puppies, $300 for up to age 7 and $150 for ages 8 and older.

We do not ship our pets.  Be prepared to travel to Tulsa, OK, or Oklahoma City, OK, or the location where this dog is fostered to pick up your dog in person if your application is approved.  Once you are approved, you may adopt any of our dogs that is a good fit. 

We are a non-profit organization that spends our adoption fees and donations on vaccinations, surgeries, various medical tests, medicines, food and supplies needed by our dogs. Our fees do not cover the overall expenses incurred by the care of our dogs, but they do help defray the costs involved.  We thank you for your support. 

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always try to select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dog’s needs and try to find the best match for both dog and human. 
We leave a dog’s profile online until either it has been adopted, has received several applications, or is not able to be adopted for some reason.

animal.description: Rocco was previously a yard dog (and talented escape artist), but he was obviously loved. He was also, er... 'very well nourished'. He was overwhelmed by the shelter environment but immediately settled well in foster and no longer needs anxiety meds. Rocco does not like to be alone (inside or outside) and will cry, moan, or howl if he cannot be by your side. He is an adamant lap cuddler. It's hard to stop him. He is housebroken. He crates well at night in the bedroom. He does not chew forbidden items. Rocco played well with three neighbor children (7-10) one time. Otherwise, children are an unknown. Rocco came with some prior obedience training. Rocco needs lots of work on leash walking. He is very active and would like to go faster. Rocco currently thinks bicycles are related to dragons and he is the hero of the story. There's no doubt he LIKES other dogs. He is an energetic playmate and is VERY tolerant of much rougher dogs. He defers in social interactions and takes turns during play. A smaller, a more sedate, or an older dog may dislike playing as much as he wants. He has very high prey drive; recommend no small animals. The resident confident, indoor cat eventually tamed him with help from resident giant dog, but it was a nailbiter. Protecting the resident chickens has been a battle. With health precautions in mind, he should meet any animal buddies and also perform his own on-site, on-leash fence inspection prior to adoption. Videos of his escape artistry can be provided. This is one smart cookie.

Please note donations using the SPONSOR ME tab will not go to Fluffy Dog Rescue.

To Locate Our Application go to http://rescue.fluffydog.net/how-to-adopt.html

Our listings are updated throughout the day. If there is an applicant, it will say PENDING ADOPTION next to the dog's name. If not, please submit an Application that can be found on our site, www.fluffydog.net. 

MY AGE: approx. 6 months (1/6)  WEIGHT: approx. 45 lbs. (1/9) WHERE I AM FROM: AL (arrival 11/11) 

MY STORY: 1/9 Uno is smart and food motivated. He learned to sit, stay, lay, and shake in the first couple of days he was with us. This handsome boy is absolutely adorable with his expressive ears and silky fur. Uno likes to be with his people and needs time to warm up to strangers. Once he is comfortable, his tail starts wagging the moment you walk in the room, and his silly, affectionate personality comes out. Uno loves being with the kids and running with them in our big green space. He needs an active family to help him run his energy out (or a fenced yard), then he is happy to chill inside. Uno has been great with other dogs and gets so excited to play with them. He has had no known exposure to cats but plays gently with small dogs.

Uno is housebroken and trained to ring a bell on the door when he wants to go outside. This clever fella LOVES the snow and will sometimes ask to go out just to play. Uno is excellent in the crate at night but would prefer to be with people during the day. He will happily follow us around the house and patiently waits for us to finish our tasks. Uno loves chewing on bones and toys. His favorite spot is napping next to the kids on the one sofa he is allowed on, and he is so good about staying off all the other furniture in the house. With Uno’s sweet personality, he is going to make a great addition to someone’s family.

This dog does shed and is not hypoallergenic.

HOUSEBROKEN?   GOOD WITH DOGS?  Yes  GOOD WITH CATS?unknown

ADOPTION FEE: $450

To adopt the FIRST STEP is to complete an APPLICATION. The application can be found on our site www.fluffydog.net, or by clicking on the purple Fluffy Dog Rescue wording found in the left corner of this page under the dogs name.

Our dogs are located in foster homes throughout the state. We do not have a facility. Adopters must be 24 years old.We can not adopt to families with children under the age of six. We also adopt in WI, IL, and parts of MN. Most of our dogs are strays, so the breed is our best guess.
WI License #270548.
 
Check out Fluffy Dog Wellness on our Home Page. Great Solutions to Enhance Your Pet's Health. www.fluffydog.net

animal.description: Hello, my name is Blue! I am a loving, playful, strong, energetic, and fit 60 lb red-nosed pitbull (possibly mixed), and although I'm already pretty big, I still have some room to grow into my paws. I love attention and cuddles and am told my fur feels like suede. I like playing tug-o-war and fetch over short distances. I am house-trained, know "sit", and I am learning "stay". In my foster home, I am crated when my fosters are not home and enjoy supervised free roaming time when they are with me. I am still young and am learning which things are mine and are allowed to be chewed on- I love toys and I want to please you- durable chew toys, supervision, play time to get my energy out, and positive reinforcement are the ingredients to my success. I like play time with other dogs and love time with my canine friends in my foster home- I have a dominant personality so it has to be the right match and I do best with slower introductions. I love food and treats (don't you?!) but I need to be fed separately because I resource guard food (don't worry, it's easy because I am fine eating in my crate or a separate room!) I like all people- I live with kids and love to give them kisses and play with them! Due to my size and energy, I might be best with bigger kids so I don't accidentally knock down little ones with my excitement. Really, I am just a girl looking for love. Maybe you are just a family, looking for me?!

Panther's owners surrendered her to the New York City Animal Care Centers - They New York City municipal shelter.  due to biting an infant.  The owner didn't see what happened but turned around and found Panther bit the baby.

In her foster home, she learned basic manners and working with a trainer on her behaviors.

It's now time to find her forever home.

These are her stats:

Name:  Panther
Weight:  40 lbs
Age:      2 or 3
Breed:  Pit Bull Mix/Lab mix
Gets along with Cats
Gets along with Dogs


This is what her foster mom has to say:

Preferred forever home for your foster?
Panther would flourish in a stable home with a single adult or couple who could give her the support she needs, and help work on some of her anxiety-driven reactiveness. She’s friendly and submissive for other dogs and excited for a cat friend like in her original home. She’s not high-energy around the house but would probably love to be a jogging partner or have a yard to run around in. 

Interesting quirks/behaviors:
Her favorite place to sleep is under her foster mom’s bed. She likes carrying around and snuggling with toys but still isn’t necessarily sure how to play with them. Would love to be a lap dog, but is just slightly too big.

HAPPY HEARTED PANTHER LOVES DOGS & CATS! This Sleek Black Lady Enjoys Pets . Panther's owners surrendered her to the New York City Animal Care Centers - They New York City municipal shelter. Panther Is an outgoing, energetic 100% ebony beauty. Panther is as sleek as the great cat whose name she bears. But that is where the comparison ends. Because PANTHER is sweet, loveable, good with other dogs. Just a youngster and only 40 lbs, this pint-sized cutie is always in motion and always sporting a big happy smile. Panther is waiting and hoping for someone who can understand her needs of a laid back home but active in taking longs walks, hikes, or perhaps even a swim when the weather is hot and sultry. She needs an experienced handler who understands her need for structure and consistency. Someone who can understand her needs for nonchaotic life inside your home. waiting for the next chapter in her life. We are told by previous owners that she has a knack for playing with her ball and chew bones, (while not so keen on sharing them, and understandably so - not everyone wants to share their favorite things!). She was a frequenter of dog parks and appears to like the company of not only dogs but even the resident cat. Panther seeks a home that can give her time and space to adjust, as becoming friends with her is quite a treat! An adult-only home would best suit this pup, 


This is what her foster mom has to say:

She’s friendly and submissive for other dogs and excited for a cat friend like in her original home. would love to be a jogging partner or have a yard to run around in. Her favorite place to sleep is under her foster mom’s bed. She likes carrying around and snuggling with toys but still isn’t necessarily sure how to play with them. Would love to be your lap dog, Panther is a Rockstar ready to shine with a heart of gold looking for her forever kind of love.

PLEASE KNOW THAT AS CUTE AND ADORABLE AS PANTHER IS, SHE WILL NEED AN EXPERIENCED HANDLER TO UNDERSTAND HER FEAR BASED INSECURITIES. If you don't understand what this is, you're not the right adopter for her.

Thanks..

As sweet as her name, Peaches savors the closeness of people. The 64-pound white and tan beauty who lives to be loved on, adores being petted, touched and having her back legs and butt scratched. A happy honey, calm and quiet most of the time, she gets along best with older children and not only loves playing with stuffed toys, but removing the stuffing and chewing on it! Taking food and treats very gently - apples are her new favorite snacks -- she knows her name, "sit", "stay" and "down" when her fosters are eating, walks well on leash using a harness to minimize her tendency to pull, and is housetrained to a doggy door.

Animal Rescue of the Rockies believes that every pet should find a wonderful, caring home. To ensure each pet finds the best possible home, we ask that you fill out our Adoption Application so we can learn more about you and your household. We review each application we receive and will contact you within 48 hours. If your home sounds like a good match for you and the pet,

the next step is to set up a "meet and greet." After meeting the pet, if you would like to proceed with adopting, we'll ask that you read and sign our Adoption Agreement and pay the adoption fee. Our adoption fees help cover the costs of saving more lives!

A home visit will be scheduled within one week of your new pet going home with you.

The adoption fee for this pet is $300. Our adoption fee covers the following:

- Spay/Neuter, Microchip

- DAPP vaccinations as age appropriate for dog - adopter shall be responsible for all DAPP boosters after adoption.

- Rabies vaccinations as age appropriate for dog - adopter shall be responsible for any rabies vaccinations after adoption.

If you are interested in adopting, please fill out an adoption application by clicking

here

.

We want our pets to go to a lifelong new home, so thank you for your patience during the adoption process!

Please email ARRColorado@gmail.com for more information, as we can not accept calls at this time.

Our adoption process is:

1. Fill out our Adoption Application online. We'll contact you within 48 hours to answer any questions you may have about the pet.

2. If the pet looks like a great match, we'll schedule a meet and greet and ask you to fill out our online Adoption Agreement if you'd like to proceed with adopting. Once you've completed the Adoption Agreement and pay the pet's Adoption Fee, you can arrange to pick up your new furry family member!

animal.description:
Registered Name:  Fireball Shots
Call Name: Fireball
Birth Date: May 24, 2018
Color: White and Black with Ticking
Pedigree: (Djays Octane--Magic Verizon)
PRISON TRAINED GREYHOUND!

Fireball is a friendly, happy boy.  He is a larger greyhound at 77 lbs., and as you can see from his photos, he is very colorful, black and white with ticking, (ticking refers to his large black spots.  Fireball likes to be near you so you can pet and adore him!  He loves attention and is gentle and affectionate.  He gets along well with the other greyhounds in his foster home and loves everyone he meets.  He also loves van rides and will hop right in.  He settles down quickly in his crate for the evening and sleeps through the night.  And he loves to eat!  He  cannot wait for you to feed him! Fireball competed in 15 races at Palm Beach and Derby Lane in St. Petersburg.  He only won one race before being retired.  In his lineage, there are some famous greyhounds, including Flying Penske, Kelsos Fusileer, and Gable Dodge. Fireball has not been cat tested. We tried him in a home as an only dog, and he was very unhappy, so we are looking for a home for him where he will have the companionship of at least one other dog.

Fireball just graduated from the Greyhound Advancement Center's greyhound training program at Hardee Correctional Institution.  Fireball knows all of his basic commands: sit, lie down, leave it, stay, wait at the door, go to place (his bed or mat), come on recall, heel, and leave it.  The training program is excellent for the inmates as well as the dogs.  The  inmate trainers can earn training certifications which they can then use to gain employment when they are released.  The dogs enjoy being at the prison and get lots of treats. We have had the training program for awhile now, and have graduated over 700 greyhounds!  
Fireball's $600 adoption fee includes his neuter, teeth cleaning, vaccines, Bordetella (to protect against kennel cough), microchip, leash and collar, adoption guide, BAGA identification tag, and prison training. Your adoption fee helps us to defray some of the veterinary and care costs we have incurred for Fireball, and will help us to continue our work on behalf of the greyhounds.   For more information or to meet this beautiful young greyhound boy, please contact us at us at BAGA@tampabay.rr.com. For more information on greyhounds as pets, or to submit an application to adopt  this greyhound, please go to our website: www.bayareagreyhounds.org.   Fireball is being fostered in the Tampa Bay area until he enters prison training on November 20th.  We will be happy to reserve him for your family with an approved application and a $100 deposit.
