animal.description:
Kelsey is a shy 5 month old lab mix. 

Poor Kelsey was brought to a shelter in TX as an owner surrender. It was clear she had not been taken care of. She is very shy, and nervous of new people. She has some hairloss but with some TLC she will look better in no time. She has had a very stressful and hectic life so far. She needs someone patient to show her the good life. She deserves all the love in the world! 
From the foster: This girl is very sweet but is scared. She's been picked up by the local shelter, gotten fixed, given shots, and then ended up at my house to stay before transporting to CO. Kelsey wasn't taken care of before all of this. She has been relaxing at my house, she mostly stayed in her room (even when door was open). She has started coming closer to me but is not sure of being petted still. Kelsey will take treats from my hands though. She is learning that the house life is good.


If you are interested in adopting the first step is to fill out an adoption application on our website aaanimalrescue.org. We are currently very busy! Please reach out to allaboardanimalrescue@gmail.com if you have an approved application on file! Please fill out an adoption application on our website if you are ready to adopt! 

Thank you for your patience and understanding during this difficult time! We are on a mission to find everyone companions, we will continue to rescue dogs weekly! We update our page every Monday evening. We are not currently hosting any Petco adoption events for the public. We will be hosting meet/greet adoption appointments!


Breed and size disclosure: As a rescue all of our dogs come to us from high-kill shelters or other rescues, so we do not get a lot of background or information on these dogs. We occasionally receive the mother with the puppies, but in most cases both parents are unknown. Because of this we do not know the full breeding of the dogs. We are required to list the dogs based on the breeds provided to us on their records, but they are all mixed breeds as far as we know, and we cannot guarantee the actual breeds of any of these dogs. Since the full breeding of the dogs is unknown we can also only give you an educated guess on the full-grown size of the dogs. All of the current information we have on the dogs is listed in their bio above. More information may be available at our adoption event, since a lot of the fosters turn in report cards on how the dog has done in their care when they drop them off. 

Adoption Process: If you are interested in adopting from us, the first step of our adoption process is to fill out an application online at http://aaanimalrescue.org/adoption_app.html. It takes us 24-48 hours to process your application and get back to you, via email. Applications turned in Friday afternoon or Saturday morning will not be processed since we are preparing for or at our adoption event. We do have applications on site at our events, but are not always able to approve them at that time and many of the dogs will already have holds on them, so we suggest you fill out an application prior to attending an adoption event. We can place a hold on one dog per approved applicant after a deposit fee has been received, please do not ask to hold a dog if you have not turned in an application and been approved, for the first hour of our adoption event, so that they can get the first chance to meet and hopefully adopt that dog. After the first hour of the event all dogs are available on a first come, first serve basis. If you already have an approved application on file, there will just be more paperwork and the adoption fee at the event, but you will be able to take home the dog/puppy that day. animal.description:
Do you love long walks and hikes, but also sleeping in and lounging on the couch? Are you looking for a perfectly sized pet with all the bells and whistles? How about a car companion? Reggie Wayne is the total package. He absolutely LOVES being outside, but after a nice long walk, he wants nothing more than to stretch out and take a nap. Reggie Wayne is the best listener and so eager to please. He can sit, stay, laydown, boop your hand, shake. On walks down a busy street, he will sit nicely by your side at every crosswalk, looking to you for the all clear to cross the street. He is housebroken and will even trot to the door and nose the handle to alert you that it's time! Taking a drive and want to bring Reggie along? He'll sit quietly in back seat, once he makes sure all is clear out the windshield. He loves to watch tv, with or without his foster mom, so he makes for a good Netflix buddy too. Go ahead and fill out that app today for your new best friend Reggie Wayne!

Reggie Wayne is about 5 years old and weighs about 65 pounds.

If you're interested in meeting Reggie, please visit our website to learn about our adoption process and to fill out an application, www.gatewaypets.org/adopt

All of our dogs and cats will be micro-chipped, spayed or neutered, and up-to-date on vaccinations at the time of adoption. For more photos of Reggie, follow us on Facebook Gateway Pet Guardians and Instagram @gatewaypets ... #gpgReggie. 

To view other adoptable pets from our shelter, please visit, www.gatewaypets.org/adopt

Gateway Pet Guardians is proud to offer a variety of mixed breed dogs available for adoption. However, please keep in mind that we rarely know the genetic background of the animals we rescue and, as such, we cannot guarantee the exact breed combinations found within this dog. However, we do not know his/her actual genetic makeup. Just know that this dog is probably a variety of several different breeds that have combined to create one very amazing and unique animal.

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email Michelle at mhunt@k-9lifesavers.org
You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.
Dog's Name: Roxie
Estimated Breed : Labrador Retriever Mix
Approximate Age: 2 years
Approximate Weight: approx. 50 lbs
Currently Living at: Foster
Adoption Fee: $375
DOG'S DESCRIPTION
Roxie is just the sweetest girl who would love to find her forever home with you! She loves to give kisses, has done phenomenal with housetraining (no issues at all and goes immediately once we go outside), and has mastered 'sit'. Unfortunately, she is not a fan of cats. Due to her excitability, she might not do well with young/small children in the home. She is also dog select, so might not do well with another dog in the home - it will depend on the dog.
She is heartworm positive, but just received her treatment, and in a few weeks will be without any restrictions and ready to conquer the world!
Are you in the mood for some Roxie love?

Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org
Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!
For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.
Please "like" our Facebook Page for the most current events and new dogs.
Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
Hi, I'm Marco and I have a heck of a story. I wish I could tell you! But apparently I've been bumped around from place to place, including a homeless camp and the pound. I'm kind of hyper, but I'm working on it. If I go for 2-3 nice walks during the day, I can be a couch potato. I get very excited when I meet new people and new dogs, but I'm very friendly and while I might be a bit too excited for little kids, I get along great with all people and other dogs once I settle down. If you're into hiking and walking and activity, I'm your dog. I can be a little picky about food, but I do eat, you just need to remind me that your food is not my food! I don't mind people touching my face, and I like my dog toys, sleeping in my crate (working on it with the door closed), and I love car rides (because it means I'm going on an adventure!). 

If you are interested in meeting this pooch, please download the Adoption Questionnaire (farescue.org/pdf_files/questionnaire_canine.pdf), fill it out and email it back to us at info@farescue.org or fax (310) 362-0321. You can also meet this and/or other available dogs at our weekend adoptions.

[Marco is 3 years old and weighs 54 lbs.]

(2011)

animal.description:
Meet Willie, a 1 year old Beagle mix who came into our rescue in October, 2020.  Willie is a very loving guy who will sit on your lap for hours just wanting attention.  He loves the snow and running in his fenced yard with the other dogs in his foster home.  He goes on daily walks and is very good on a leash.  Willie does not  have a mean bone in his body.  

After being in his foster home for awhile, we noticed how many accidents he was having and had him seen at our vet and treated for a urinary tract infection.   The infection went away but the peeing did not.   After being seen by another vet for a second opinion and going through numerous tests, the conclusion is that his issues are behavioral.  

We are looking for a home for Willie where he may have to be in a heated barn or kennel with indoor and outdoor access at all times.  He definitely needs to be around people and other dogs as he would not be very happy if isolated.

Please contact Best Buddy Pet Rescue at 248-622-6097 for more information or to talk to Willie's foster mom.

Lucky is an American Foxhound and true to his breed, he is sweet natured and sensitive yet relatively quiet.  He does well with strangers and all people and gets along well with the fosters'  two dogs - he has not been tested with cats.  He is a 5 year old neutered male that lost his home due to reasons unrelated to him.  This guy would do well in a home that knows about hounds and their noses - he will follow his nose and could get lost if you aren't watching.  So a fenced in yard is required.  We are looking for a home owner who lives near the Twin Cities area who understands hounds.  Lucky is good in the home and will be placed as an indoor only dog.  This means he will live inside with his family and only be outdoors when the family is outdoors.  He truly is one of the sweetest hounds we've ever met.  

Lucky is in the rehoming program of Blue Sky Rescue of MN, a 501c3 rescue that screens all applicants.  He is up to date with vet care and comes with vet records and an adoption agreement.

animal.description:
Tank is a mild alpha who will spank other dogs who he feels need correcting.  For that reason I suggest him with larger dogs, even alpha dogs, since he does not try that funny business with our larger or other alpha dogs here.  

Good with all female dogs.  

Not a guy for small kids even though he seems to like them very well here, 

Children ages 10 and up for this guy.  

He LOVES attention and will jump on our guests trying to get it.  

He is athletic, possibly a prospect for Agility for a beginner or as a project for a youngster, but he is not wild and crazy.  He seems pretty confident however. and he is smart.  

Tank has been treated for heartworms and is ready to find that permanent home.  He was one of two male dogs abandoned by a renter in our area.  He likes to hunt so a fenced in yard or an home in the city would be GREAT for him. Not a couch potato.  So we are looking for someone to hike,  bike, walk, run or just do some fun stuff with this guy.   

Adoption fee is $250.  Call Marilyn at 573-722-3035 to adopt from 9:30am t o9:30pm Central Time.  

We adopt dogs all over the USA.  Flights are very difficult to arrange, however on the East side of the USA we use a transport company called ALPHA DOG TRANSPORT.  Check out their website for pick up dates and locations as well as cost.

animal.description:
This handsome Pyrenees mix boy is Greg and he is a sweetheart. Greg is doing well in foster and although he is shy, he is starting to seek out affection and learning how nice humans can be. Greg came into rescue from a neglect/cruelty case with multiple dogs who were starved and had mange. They were largely ignored and unsocialized so he has really come a long way in rescue care. He is good with other dogs and came into rescue with his buddy or maybe his sister Guinn. He is such a good boy as he looks out for her and cares for her. Greg is coming along so nicely now! Initially he would just freeze as he was frightened of new people but now, his tail wags when he sees a friendly face and he is learning to like walking on leash. He is not a huge boy, but he is a gentle boy who is learning everything he needs to know. It is so nice to see him coming around, getting friendlier each day, so he will need a kind, patient human to continue working with him. He likes to chase cats so a cat free home would be best for Greg. Greg could really use a home where he can continue to learn how great life can be. It is so nice that he has come so far in a short time, we know he will continue to do better and better. Greg is currently in boarding and we are looking for a foster or adopter who will continue to guide him.

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
NGPR dogs are in foster homes throughout the U.S., NOT Beacon, NY. View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
This sweet boy is Jack.  He is a 5 month old Shepherd mix who weighs 40lbs but will be about 75 lbs full grown. 

Jack has a lot of personality.  He is an excellent napper but also playful.  He lives with many other dogs of all sizes and does great with all of them.  He is very lovable.  He is excellent with new people when they come over to his foster home.  He even did well with kids (age 7) who came over.  He has done excellent welcoming new foster dogs into his foster home as well.  

However, when Jack is outside of his home, he is VERY nervous when meeting new people and new dogs.  He may pee meeting a new person at first but he does warm up fairly quickly to people.  Warming up to new dogs in a new home will take him some time often more than a day or so.   He lives with multiple dogs and has welcomed new dogs into his home but in a new place he is just so very nervous so is going to take time and patience and understanding.  

Jack would like a home where he is loved like crazy and treated like a member of the family.  He will need a home ready to give him the exercise he needs and the love and care he deserves.  He needs someone that will give him a few days to see him come out of his shell before giving up on him.  He really is an absolutely amazing dog if given the time.  

He is leashed trained,  pretty much house trained and will sit on command.

Jack is neutered, microchipped, and current on his vaccines.  His adoption fee is $175.

If you would like to adopt Jack and make him a part of your family, please contact ForeverYoursOKC@gmail.com.

animal.description:
Daphne is a super sweet shy kind of gal approximately 4 years old. She was returned to her foster home after 6 months with her new adopters. She wasn't bonding with her new family. Daphne was adopted to a quiet home with no other dogs and Daphne's foster Mom now feels that a better fit would be with at least one other outgoing playful friendly dog. Prior to adoption she was living with her foster Mom's 9 personal dogs and fit right back into the pack once she returned. She loves sleeping with her foster Mom and the rest of the gang. She would also do best with a family that is home a bit more than gone. Polite children could be a possibility since she loves attention. Her foster Mom sees tiny bits of a cute personality that hasn't 100% surfaced yet. Daphne is potty trained with or without a dog door, she does not bark and rides well in a car. Daphne will need leash training so best she goes to a home with a yard. She currently weighs about 9.5 pounds and is full grown.
She is spayed, up to date on vaccines, and microchipped. Her adoption fee of $300 includes a complementary vet visit. Home check required prior to adoption.
Please email her foster mom at lscott00001@gmail.com if you need more information or are interested in meeting her.

animal.description:
Free to the right home. 

Bruser was left behind at a boyfriend's house.  Mom had enough... so he and five other dogs she collected which she said were found as strays, came to our rescue.  

Bruser has been an outdoor dog all his life.  We learned he has been neutered most of his life. However he is an alpha over the food bowl (and he looks it too).  

He also has chronic ear infections.  So we just started him on a total raw meat diet and anytime we have done this in the past the dogs health GREATLY improved.  

He requires about 8 ounces daily.  So we suggest the DINOVITE Raw Diet plan, using their supplements if you want an easy diet plan.  

Also, study the raw  diet on DOG'S NATURALLY Website for all the smarts of feeding raw.  10% raw bone, 10% organ meat and the rest muscle meat.  For the organ meat provide beef or poultry liver, gizzard, heart.  Liver is the BEST of them all.  

I have found the raw diet also to improve temperament on a small dog we rescued.   It calmed him down in the dog pack and when in the crate waiting for his yummy meals. 

FREE to a home.  

Call Marilyn between 9:30am to 9:30pm Central Time at 573-722-3035> 

We adopt out dogs all over the USA.

animal.description:
CARLEIGH MUST HAVE A FENCED YARD. Note from Carleigh's foster Mom: CARLEIGH is a quiet and affectionate girl who loves to cuddle. She is shy but very sweet.

CARLEIGH is a purebred Jack Russell who is shy and fearful of new people. She needs a quiet home with someone willing to work with her to get over her fears. CARLEIGH would love a home where she can enjoy plenty of activity indoors and out.

WHAT'S NEXT? If you would like to meet, foster or adopt this pet, please fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY! Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date! *** This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives. Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. BY APPOINTMENT ONLY: Meetings at our Adoption Center are by appointment only (no walk-ins). An online adoption application is required and must be approved prior to meeting any animals. Adoption appointments are set up by email by our Adoption Coordinator (no phone calls, please). This process ensures our dedicated time to the animals in our care, as well as full attention to adopters at scheduled times. Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details. To fill out an adoption application, go to: https://www.animalalliancenj.org/fosteradoption-application/

animal.description:
Meet Maggie and Trouble! They are a bonded duo looking for a home together! They came to us when their owner went into hospice care and didn't have anyone to take care of them. We have learned that they are a sweet pair when they get to know you. 

Maggie (cream) is very sweet and easy going, she warms up quickly. Trouble (tri-color) takes a little longer to warm up but once he does he's as sweet as can be. Both love to lay next to you or on a comfy bed. They are good with other dogs, mostly house trained and crate trained. They would do best with older kids. 

To set up a meet and greet or inquire about a dog, please first fill out an application at https://savinghoperescue.org/contact. It doesn't obligate you, but it is the first step. We don't get to all of the inquiries but respond to all applications. Thank you for choosing to rescue!

animal.description: Contact foster at HSDOGFOSTERMOM@GMAIL.COM Ronald is one of the most loving dogs I have ever fostered. He wants nothing more than too give you love and kisses and to receive love and affection in return. He's so happy when you are petting him. Loves to cuddle. Good in the car; content to have his head out the window or just sit and check things out. Loves squeaky toys, tennis balls and his favorite is Kong squeaky ball. If you throw the tennis ball or squeaky he'll go fetch it but he's not going to give it back ?? He just likes to carry them around. Gets along with my 3 senior dogs. He is very excited when meeting new dogs so needs slow introductions. Initially on two occasions he overstayed his welcome sniffing one of my dogs and she growled at him and he appropriately took the social queue and backed off. Knows how to use the doggy door and is housebroken. He had never chewed on anything in my house when I left him at home but he does have the company of other dogs so not sure how it would react if he was the only/sole dog. I have NOT crated him. Knows how to sit and shake and appears to understand the word no Does not seem to be food motivated. He does eat fast so I just watch to make sure he does not loiter around others who are still eating. Initially he followed me everywhere but as time has goes on he seems to be getting more comfortable with going outside and/or chilling in the living room on the dog bed. Needs training with regards to walking. If no distractions he is fine but if he sees a dog, cat, squirrel or rabbit he will pull. Typically for any creature outside of a dog, if I keep saying no Ronald he will stare but keep walking. NOTE: I do not have cats or children so I cannot speak to his behavior but as noted above he is one of the most loving dogs I have fostered so would not anticipate issues with children. The Animal Control staff indicated he did not do well with cats.

animal.description:
This big, stocky boy is full of love and joy!   He came to a high volume shelter with major skin problems, worms and grossly underweight.  He was rescued by SCP and what a transformation (see the pics)!  He's all fixed up and ready for his new home. He's still young (est EOB 1/31/2020) and weighs over 50 pounds now. He is dog and kid friendly.  He has not been around cats but he's young and not aggressive so he’d likely just try to get them to play with him, which may be too much for some cats.  He loves all balls and squeaker toys.  He’s sneaky and curious so you’ll need to be careful when opening the front door because he’ll want to go exploring.   His favorite time of day is any time food is involved so he'll be easy to teach new skills and tricks using food as an incentive. This boy loves to eat!   He is house and crate trained though he’s not a fan of the crate.  He’s proven himself trust worthy so has free reign with the other dogs but still eats in his crate because he'd gobble his food down and go looking for more in other dogs dishes. If you are interested in a lovable, fun, snuggle-bunny, please send an email to scpdogworld@gmail.com to get more information on how to fill out an application and have a great meet and greet to see if we are a match made in heaven.

Adopter for this dog must reside in the immediate Houston/Galveston area and be at least 25 years old.  A home visit may be required prior to this dog going to any home. The adoption fee for a dog is $190 (or $245 for puppies) which includes State of Texas sales tax. All dogs are microchipped, on heartworm protection, spayed/neutered, vaccinated, de-wormed and treated for fleas.

animal.description:
Meet Sadie, a wonderful loving old lady!
Sadie was sadly surrendered due to her owner's passing. But, never mind the sad part of this story, let's focus on what a wonderful girl she is.
Sadie has hip dysplasia and a bad knee but, don't let that fool you, this gal gets along pretty well and while she has good days and bad days, she has managed very well. Due to this, Sadie needs a home with little to no stairs for her to navigate on a regular basis and a home with carpet everywhere she will travel.
Sadie is a super sweet, calm pup but she will take a while to warm up to you, or anyone for that matter. When we have guests to our home, she will head into our bedroom and hang out in her bed. With loving encouragement, she will join everyone and warm up but it does take time. Once she warms up to you, be ready, she loves with all of her heart!
Like all wiggle butts, Sadie enjoys being close to her family but she has done very well when we leave her. We suspect that this is partly due to the other 2 boxers in our home. She will do very well with a companion pup so long as that pup is respectful and understands that Sadie is older and not looking for rough and tumble play.
Her adoption fee is $250 Please put in an application at www.eapl.com

animal.description:
*	I have soooooo much to say about this boy Brett!
*	I love them all but there are a few that stomp on our hearts big time and Brett is one of them. 
*	This boy is a goof ball. He is approximately 1 year old and he's all that in energy. 
*	He is a lab mix and can talk a big talk when trying to get your attention. 
*	With that said, he'd do best in a home with a fenced in yard. 
*	He LOVES to play with his humans and has many dog friends. 
*	He LOVES to get loved on and kisses on his snout. 
*	His energy level is pretty high but he'd make the BEST BFF ever. He'd love someone or a family who is SUPER active and wants to bring him along. 
*	He'd love access to water since his favorite activity at the rescue is playing with his favorite peeps, the hose and the water monster! Like I said a goof ball!!! 
*	But OMG the love factor with Brett is HUGE. 
*	Call today to make your appointment and see if Brett is a good fit for you!!!If you wish to meet me, please call the Humane Society of York County at (803)-802-0902 to schedule an appointment. Adoption consultations are by appointment only.

Please refer to our website for adoption requirements: https://humanesocietyofyorkcounty.org/adopt/adoption-process.html

To learn more about the HSYC, please visit our website at www.humanesocietyofyorkcounty.org, Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/HSYC.animals/, or on Instagram at HumaneSocietyofYorkCounty

Thank you for your support.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Georgia! Here's what my foster family has to say about about me:

""Georgia loves to be loved and has a lot of love to give. She loves everyone she has ever met and shows no signs of aggression to people. Georgia has some special needs due her neurological issues, but once you learn her quirks, you will love her as much as we do. Unfortunately, Georgia does not like our dog, our dog is too much for her. She would likely do well with a older, calm dog. My cats ignore her, and she ignores them. 

She would do best with a fenced-in yard. She is getting better with walks, although we sometimes have to remind her what we are doing. She walks best with a harness. Georgia can run and play, but is not always steady on her feet. She has some vision problems, mostly in her right eye, but her nose and ears work just fine. She LOVES treats!! 

We are so sad that we can not keep her, we have grown to love her so much. She needs someone with a little patience and a lot of time and love!!""

If you're interested in adopting me, please fill out an application today: https://us01.sheltermanager.com/service?account=ah0334&method=online_form_html&formid=5To complete an adoption application, go to: http://almosthomeanimals.org/applications/adoption/

animal.description:
Hi there!

My name is Henry! I am 8 years old and I weigh 70 pounds!
I was a stray that was found in South Houston. I was very skinny and had bad mange and was heartworm positive. I had been hanging out at a childrens park in a neighborhood and people finally realized that I was not going home with anyone but just following anyone I could home. I have scars all over my head and I look like where ever I came from was pretty tough but I'm just about as sweet as I can be. A nice lady with children felt bad for me and after seeing how sweet I was with her kids helped me to her home and took me to a vet. She got me into a rescue who started getting me healthy and ready for heartworm treatment and I am now negative and in a foster home!

I had called shotgun in my fosters car and was immediately her best bud. I kept popping her hand off the shift to stick my head under it so she could pet me better. I'm very considerate that way and still do that whenever I'm sitting next to someone and I think they've forgotten how to pet me. They got me neutered, up to date on shots, current on heartworm/flea prevention and microchipped. Unfortunately after a long time of being on the street with no one to take care of me I was heartworm positive but I have already been through treatment and am now negative!

I really love all people. Little ones, Big ones, tall ones and short ones it doesn't make any difference to me! I would love a home with just about anyone who would show me affection whether they've got kids or grandkids running around. I'm a little bit older boy so I don't need quite as much action as some of those young bucks out there but I still like to go for a walk down the road with my foster mom and I get super excited when I see people! I need to be and only dog. Other dogs rile me up too much and after being on the street for so long I don't know what to expect from them and unfortunately get overstimulated very quickly and I get upset! I also need to be in a single person home. I've always been good in my foster home but I've gone on two home trials and I've become protective of the woman of the home towards the males in the house. But my foster mom is still working with me all the time to make me the best boy I can be!

I am still located in Houston, Texas but am super excited to find my forever home and get transported to your area! Will you be my family? For more info on me please email Stephanie at nicole.whar94@yahoo.com.

animal.description:
Hi there!

My name is Sebastian! I am 7 years old and I weigh 70 pounds!
I was part of a group of dogs that a rescue started helping in a bad part of town. Rescues had come in and picked all the youngsters and left me and my ol' lady friend all by our selves on the street. Finally after alot of networking a rescue heard we were still there and came to get us. I hopped right in her car but my friend she had to get fancy and corner in someones yard! I was so friendly I was trying to help her get my buddy the whole time! Didn't she know good people when she saw one???

I had called shotgun in the car and was immediately her best bud. I kept popping her hand off the shift to stick my head under it so she could pet me better. I'm very considerate that way and still do that whenever I'm sitting next to someone and I think they've forgotten how to pet me. They got me neutered, up to date on shots, current on heartworm/flea prevention and microchipped. Unfortunately after a long time of being on the street with no one to take care of me I was heartworm positive but I have already been through treatment and am on the mend!

I really love all people. Little ones, Big ones, tall ones and short ones it doesn't make any difference to me! I would love a home with just about anyone who would show me affection whether they've got kids or grandkids running around. I'm a little bit older boy so I don't need quite as much action as some of those young bucks out there but I still like to go for a walk down the road with my foster mom and I get super excited when I see people! I would probably do best in a home as an only dog or maybe just with a submissive female. Male dogs rile me up to much and after being on the street for so long I don't know what to expect from them! But my foster mom is still working with me all the time to make me the best boy I can be!

I am still located in Houston, Texas but am super excited to find my forever home and get transported to your area! Will you be my family? For more info on me please email Stephanie at nicole.whar94@yahoo.com.

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Gibby. What's yours? Anyway, nice to meet ya!
Hey! Before you get attached to me, read all the way to the bottom. You will see that I am still in Houston, TX but I want to get OUT of Houston and OUT of Texas so I can have a really good life. I want to see Texas in my rear view mirror. A nice person came along and took me in and, now, I am ready to hit the road to your house! Uh, make that “our” house, OK? As soon as you adopt me, I’ll be on my way to you! I am very excited to find my forever home. I'm a good boy. You'll see!

I am a mixed breed boy. I am 2.5 years old and I weigh approximately 50 pounds. I am house-trained. I am crate-trained. I have had all of my shots and have been neutered and I'm ready to go to my new home with YOU! Those funny-looking 2-legged creatures also say that I am microchipped – whatever THAT is.

Wanna hear more good stuff about me? OK, here goes. I am a friendly boy. I love all people and other dogs. I am active and love to run and play. I have been in a foster home with other dogs so am very well socialized with other dogs of different sizes and ages and I temper myself very well to whoever I'm with. When I'm excited I still have a tendency to jump  up but my foster mom is working with me on that and I love learning new things especially for a treat! I have a hound dog type bark but I don't use it very often usually only when I think I'm being left out of something like a walk or if everybody is headed to the back yard and I'm stuck in my kennel. Its  puppy torture! But I'm very polite and don't carry on very long about it. 

I was brought to the rescue by a couple who had seen their next door neighbor move and leave me and a couple other dogs tied up in the yard in back. Luckily they knew we were there and came to give us food and water until they were sure no one was coming back for us. I ended up being in a long term foster home as I had to luxating patellas which is super common but unfortunately due to how active I am they were bothering me often so the rescue elected to fix both knees for me so I could run and play with out them bothering me!  I have been neutered, micro-chipped, vaccinated and kept up to date on heartworm and flea prevention. I am also heartworm negative!

My foster mom loves me SO much that she only wants me to fly to my new home even if a pet transport truck was available. See my adoption information below.

If you would like to take me home (and you know you do), please email nicole.whar94@yahoo.com and she can get me on my way to a new and loving home! My adoption fee is $450 USD and includes my vetting, neutering, microchip, health certificate, travel crate AND transportation on United Airlines from Houston, TX to areas in the Northeast U. S., North Central U. S., Northwest U. S., and Canada and will be arranged by the rescue group

animal.description:
Hi there!

My name is Blue! I am 10-11 months old and I weigh 40 pounds!
I was found running around a neighborhood. Many of the neighbors had seen me come up to their door but no one knew who I belonged to. Luckily I finally ran up to someone getting in their car and hopped right in with her! She volunteers for a rescue and works at a vet clinic so after posting me online, scanning me for a chip, and asking around the neighborhood for my owners with no success she decided to foster me and enter me into the rescue. I was such a sweet boy she just knew I would find a home! I was scared when I first had to go to the vet and had gotten my shots and everything done. But with enough treats I quickly came around and got used to being poked and prodded. I LOVE going to adoption events and get excited to see all the people. My foster mom is still working with me to get me to keep my confidence up as I approach groups of people as I can still get nervous and overwhelmed but I'm doing really well and warm up super fast! I instantly like other dogs though I just recently got neutered so we are still learning that humping human and dog friends alike is a rude intro! 

Now that I have settled into a foster home I could be shy with new people but I want to make friends so bad! And now I usually approach people very excitedly and confidently.  My foster mom is working on leash and potty training as I don't think I've ever had someone let me in the house and make me a part of the family before! I would do really well in a home with another dog especially one who wouldn't overwhelm me. I really like kids but the younger ones might be too much for me so we are looking for a home with teens or none at all.

I am neutered, up to date on shots, current on heartworm/flea prevention and microchipped. I was also heartworm negative! Yay!

I am still located in Houston, Texas but am super excited to find my forever home and get transported to your area! Will you be my family? For more info on me please email Stephanie at nicole.whar94@yahoo.com.

animal.description:
Hi there!

My name is Blue! I am 10-11 months old and I weigh 40 pounds!
I was found running around a neighborhood. Many of the neighbors had seen me come up to their door but no one knew who I belonged to. Luckily I finally ran up to someone getting in their car and hopped right in with her! She volunteers for a rescue and works at a vet clinic so after posting me online, scanning me for a chip, and asking around the neighborhood for my owners with no success she decided to foster me and enter me into the rescue. I was such a sweet boy she just knew I would find a home! I was scared when I first had to go to the vet and had gotten my shots and everything done. But with enough treats I quickly came around and got used to being poked and prodded. I LOVE going to adoption events and get excited to see all the people. My foster mom is still working with me to get me to keep my confidence up as I approach groups of people as I can still get nervous and overwhelmed but I'm doing really well and warm up super fast! I instantly like other dogs though I just recently got neutered so we are still learning that humping human and dog friends alike is a rude intro! 

Now that I have settled into a foster home I could be shy with new people but I want to make friends so bad! And now I usually approach people very excitedly and confidently.  My foster mom is working on leash and potty training as I don't think I've ever had someone let me in the house and make me a part of the family before! I would do really well in a home with another dog especially one who wouldn't overwhelm me. I really like kids but the younger ones might be too much for me so we are looking for a home with teens or none at all.

I am neutered, up to date on shots, current on heartworm/flea prevention and microchipped. I was also heartworm negative! Yay!

I am still located in Houston, Texas but am super excited to find my forever home and get transported to your area! Will you be my family? For more info on me please email Stephanie at nicole.whar94@yahoo.com.

animal.description:
This is Wylie! This sweet 10 year old mini Poodle has been with us since February, spending his time with an amazing foster.

Wiley came from a local shelter with two debilitated back legs. After multiple vet visits to seek out his diagnosis, it was identified that both of Wiley's knees have severely subluxated patellas. Based on the severity and his age, surgery is not recommended. He will be on Gabapentin and in a wheelchair for the rest of his life. He cannot go for long walks and cannot climb stairs.

Ever since Wiley came to our rescue, he has been in great spirits and has a very loving and friendly disposition with his human but he does not do well with other dogs. He would make the best companion to a single person or retired couple looking for a companion

If interested in giving this sweet boy a loving home, please message us! muellenbergerin@gmail.com #adoptdontshop

animal.description:
Coco and Fern came to us after their mom, a disable Navy Veteran, ran into tough times due to the Covid pandemic. She was figuring things out for herself and her daughter and felt it was in the best interest of these two bonded girls to find a new forever home. They were well-cared for and loved and we are happy to have them with us.
Coco is low energy, super cuddly and 22 lbs and Fern is medium energy and 12 lbs. Together, they are a great balance! They are UTD on vaccinations, microchipped, spayed and generally healthy. 
Coco is blind and Fern is her little seeing eye dog. Fern really seems to feel like she needs to take care of Coco and gets upset when they are separated. They often lay together, but Fern will get up on the couch whereas Coco stays safely on the floor. While they came to us as house trained, they will need just a little time to adjust to a new routine and new set-up. They both love to go on walks and are crate trained. And they are both good with other dogs, cats and children! Pretty perfect dogs!
These two really are the sweetest pair of buddies they look forward to spending forever and ever together.

animal.description:
Harlow has been in a foster home for 6 weeks. She was adopted and before the adopters even managed to get her inside of the home, she got away from them. Because of this, we are requiring that you have a fenced in yard and have experience with fearful dogs. Despite how beautiful she is, she is not a good choice for a first time dog parent. She is not willing to walk on a leash at this time, another reason why she will require a fenced in yard. She is great with other dogs and currently is fostered with a cat. She is a Diamond in the rough and will require patience and earning of her trust. You can apply for her at www.furkidrescue.org 

Harlow is a a small German Shepherd, only weighing around 50 pounds. She was rescued when she lived in a backyard in Memphis with another dog. Both dogs were heartworm positive, and she has been fully treated for heartworm at this point. She was neglected, and underweight. She was not treated as a family member, and hence probably why she is un-trusting of humans and skittish. She has flourished wonderfully in her current foster home, but she will most likely go back to square one when she goes to her new home. You must have some basic knowledge on fearful dogs or be willing to work with an approved behavior consultant.

animal.description:
What can we say about Thor except we are totally in love with him!!! He came to us in terrible condition from a neglected thyroid condition that simply needed an inexpensive daily pill. The worst symptom was his hair loss, but that is improving so much. This boy is beyond sweet. He loves people, is cooperative, and has an upbeat personality. Seriously, we have fallen hard for him because of his exceptional temperament. He is always cheerful! He especially enjoys car rides and stopping at Starbucks for a pupacino!

Thor would like a quiet home with people who will reciprocate the love and attention he will freely give to his humans. Children over 12 because this is a hefty boy. Likewise, we think an older female dog or no other dog would be his preference, so as not to have competition for his family's time or a younger dog who needs an agile playmate. Cats are unknown. 

**If you are serious about adopting , you must head to our website at www.kodisclub.org and submit a completed application . We will not do anything without an app. Due to the small size of our volunteer-run rescue, only the approved adopter may be contacted. It is not first come first served, but the best match **

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.German Shepherd dogs, as well as the other herding breeds that we have in rescue, are highly active, energetic, working breeds. They require considerable vetting, exercise, socialization, training, leadership and mental stimuli in order to be well-adjusted, well-balanced, and well-mannered dogs. Even if you exercise and play with your dog daily in your fenced yard, you MUST still take your dog out on daily walks and outings in order to work on his/her leash skills, manners, and social skills. These breeds make great additions to active families who will pamper them, but who will also work with them, as they are smart dogs who need leadership, structure, plenty of activity and mental stimulation. If you are new to German Shepherds (and other herding breeds), please research the breed to make sure this is the dog for you. We ask that you consider the time and financial commitment that your German Shepherd (or other herding breed) dog will require before applying for one. Please review the section on our website (www.heartlandgsrescue.org) 'Is a HUGS Dog Right for You?' for additional information.

Ysbrid (her name means "Spirit"), or Ysy for short, is a sweet, fun-loving, little girl. She loves to cuddle, play with other dogs of all ages, cats, and to run like the wind! She loves toys, running laps in the yard, and exploring. Ysy is still all puppy!

She is potty trained and crate trained. She sleeps on the bed with her foster mom and the other dogs (and cat) and has the run of the house. She prefers to hang out with the other dogs and can play all day. Ysy is very inquisitive and it is a delight to watch her explore! Sometimes, her desire to explore has got her into trouble. She has shown she can easily jump and climb a regular chain link fence so she will need a 6 foot fence to confine her explorations to a suitable area. She loves figuring out food-dispensing toys and gentle tug toys, and Ysy adores "Hide and Seek" plush toys - with squeakers in them. She is also fond of soft rubber chew toys and balls.

Ysbrid is very shy with new people and needs to have time to get to know them before her true personality comes through. It took months for her to let foster mom touch her. However, she now lets foster mom pet her and she sleeps cuddled up next to her foster mom as well. She now lets foster mom pick her up as well. She does love treats and that is a great way to help her warm up. She also dos not like loud people or when people move fast. When she is scared, she poops as she runs away inside or outdoors. Her fear default is to cower in her crate or the far corner of the yard; she has never offered to bite.

Due to the above information, Ysbrid needs a home with no tiny children or a lot of people going in and out. She can slip in and out of a door or gate very quickly and silently. She needs a home with lots of patience.

Ysbrid's adoption fee is $275, all of which goes back into offseting our high-cost vetting expenses and rescuing more dogs. Adoption fees include spay/neuter, current on age-appropriate vaccinations, fecal, deworming, flea/tick and heartworm preventative, heartworm tested if old enough (treated if positive), and microchipped. Learn more about the adoption process and requirements, and apply at: http://heartlandgsrescue.rescuegroups.org/info/adoption.

Please review the information in the 'About Us', 'Important Considerations' and 'Adopt' sections on our website menu, as it contains useful information about the breed, adoption fees, the adoption process and our requirements, and how meeting the dogs works.

animal.description:
Sebastian!!!! 

This love has come a long way in the 3 months that he's been with our rescue. He was a bit of hot mess when we busted him outta the shelter! 

He had an upper respiratory infection, unstable back legs, mammary tumors, teeth that have never seen the dentist, severely under weight and a nose deformity they think is from a prior trauma but the bloodwork will tell us if he could possibly have a tumor or something going on in his face.

So basically he was all that and a bag of chips. LOL!

The shelter said he was 16 but our vet thinks he’s 10-14 years old. We did a senior bloodwork panel and X-rays and X-rays showed Lumbosacral arthritis.

He’s been with an incredible foster, who has been working on his leash skills and his manners that our trainer has implemented.

We will be scheduling his surgery for his Neuter, Mammary tumor removal and Dental in the coming weeks!

In the meantime, this distinguished gentleman is single and ready to mingle! 

If you're interested in meeting this sweet and funny man, let us know.

animal.description: Connery is named after the dashing Sean Connery! He is so handsome and full of energy, just like 007! animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email US at adopt@k-9lifesavers.org
You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.
Dog's Name: Jackson
Estimated Breed : Flat Coated Retriever Mix
Approximate Age: 9 months
Approximate Weight: approx. 45 lbs
Currently Living at: Boarding
Adoption Fee: $300
DOG'S DESCRIPTION
Jackson is a smart guy who has sadly never received any training and didn't have the best experience in life with leash. He is looking for adult only family who has breed experienced with active, high energy dogs and can provide him with mental stimulation and exercise and set him up on obedience path. Jackson gets along well with dogs but he hates the leash and can be reactive on leash towards people and dogs. For that reason, he is looking for a home that can work with him on overcoming the fear of leash, but in the interim has a fully fenced in yard to give him enough exercise and where he is the only dog. Jackson is not a bad boy, he is just not trained and can get excited and mouthy when not properly exercised. Active household who can work with him to channel his energy in appropriate way is a must.
Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org
Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!
For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.
Please "like" our Facebook Page for the most current events and new dogs.
Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

Daisy requires a home with no steps. Anything higher than a threshold is a challenge. Her dream would be doggie wheelchair friendly, to give her freedom to walk on her own as she tires easily.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Toga and I am a one-year-old Husky. After being surrendered due to the hurricane I found myself on the euth list in Del Rio Texas due to overcrowded shelters. I am very friendly though still very young and do not appear to have ever been trained or taught any manners. I have been an outdoors dog and am working on feeling comfortable navigating indoors. I am very high energy and would love a family that can take me for long walks, runs, or hiking. I am still a puppy and need stimulation and engagement or I will find something to chew on. Being a Husky, I should have a 6ft fence to keep me safe in my yard. I love to give kisses and am not afraid to meet new people. I get along pretty well with other dogs my size, but have demonstrated a prey drive for smaller animals though I have not been cat tested. I really just want to love you and be with you and a part of the family!

The suggested adoption donation for Toga is $400.00. We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes.

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver. 

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months. 

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

Melo originally was in the care of the Bucks County ASPCA. Our rescue offered to take in this approx. ten-year old male basset. 
He is currently in a foster home for evaluation. Some of their observations include:
He seems unsettled - this may be due to the stress of having been separated from his original family.
Loves to go for a walk and is good on the leash
- eats and drinks well- but needs to gain weight.  Is suspicious about treats.
- gets along well with the dogs
- not afraid of men
- knows sit
- inconsistently sleeps through the night- he has to go out to go the bathroom
- not fully housebroken- not sure he cares about that
- does not to cuddle or sit with you but does want to be in the same room with you
- does not like when you go over to him to pet him (he will usually get up and leave) but will come to you and get your attention to be petted
- let us trim is super long nails 
- tolerated a bath
- have not seen any aggression from him
- barks when he wants to go for a walk or when he is hungry
- loves to be outside.
- he wants to counter surf
- sits on the furniture- a kitchen chair, the kitchen table, toilet or sofa (an unusual repertoire)
- drinks from the toilet


Because of the COVID situation, many rescues find themselves seeking dogs to adopt to families, with MidABHR ending up placing many of our hounds at the time of intake, or shortly thereafter,

Tammy is great with other dogs, but we have no idea how she is with cats. For this reason she will need a cat free home. Tammy has learned sit and is doing well walking on leash, but does pull. Tammy is an energetic pup who needs her daily exercise and playtime with other dogs. Tammy has excellent house manners. Tammy is not fostered with kids, so if there are kids in her forever home they should be 10 years and up. If there is a dog in her forever home, he/she should be young and playful. Tammy will need daily exercise and an adopter who is around a good portion of the day and who has recent bully breed experience. Tammy needs a large fenced-0in yard. Tammy is not suited to apartment/condo living.

She is spayed, up-to-date on vaccines and preventatives and eager to find a family to love! The adoption fee for this dog is $350 which includes routine vetting and spay/neuter.

***Please note that our first step is submitting an application (it does not commit you in any way but allows us to discuss with you if you and the dog are a good fit).

In addition, an important step in approving adoption applicants is to complete a vet check. Vetting of current and past pets is very important to us, thus we will be speaking with the vet(s) listed on your application to ensure that your current and previous pet(s) are kept up to date on vaccines (including rabies), spayed or neutered, maintained on appropriate monthly preventatives and examined annually by your vet.

*** If you would like to meet Tammy, please fill out our online application by clicking HERE and then email Kim at KLarimerLovepaws@gmail.com***

Please read the bio in full for answers to your questions. In the event you have a question that is not covered in the bio, please email info@seniordoghaven.org. If interested in adopting, please complete an adoption application which can be found at www.seniordoghaven.org under the Adoption Process tab. Please note that because all of our dogs live in foster homes, we are unable to set up meetings with a dog unless we have a completed adoption application on file. Adoptions must be about an hour of Wilmington, DE in order for our volunteers to be able to conduct an in person home visit. 

Meet our very own Benjamin Buttons! Louie and Gene, unbelievably, are both 15yrs old,  but seem to be aging in reverse! They came to us when their owner passed away , which sadly, led them to end up in a shelter.  They are the perfect mix for our chihuahua lovers out there who understand the big feisty personality that comes with these ‘little big boys’ ! Gene is super quiet, calm and very laid back - while Louie is the more energetic and boisterous one of the 2. They are extremely bonded so where you find one, the other is sure to follow. Both have been completely vetted including senior bloodwork, neutering and their dentals ( which left them just ONE tooth between them!) Louie has been diagnosed with seasonal allergies - which requires his daily medication (apoquil- approximately $30/month) , and both show early signs of elevated kidney values (often found in our seniors at this age) . The best home would include a very laid back environment with a very calm dog or they would love to just hang out with each other! Both appear to be housebroken when given scheduled potty breaks. They sleep quietly through the night, and can be a little picky with their dog food (but they LOVE human food) !

animal.description:
***Currently in a foster to adopt ***

Kora is in foster and is doing well. She is a sweet adoarable pup and has bonded with the young girl of the foster family following her and sleeping with her. She is just about house trained and does not use a crate. She stays home by herself sleeping, no problems.

Kora is timid and mellow. She shows no interest in the family cat. She might be frightened by little kids so older children are advised right now but we are confident that with love and patience Kora will continue to come out of her shell more and more each day.

Kora and her litter mates came to SoCo Rescue as owner surrenders. Their former owner took in a stray dog who ended up getting pregnant. As part of our agreement to take the pups in, the owner has agreed to have his female dog spay.

Kora is the shy pup of this litter, often staying behind her siblings when it comes time to play with the humans. She does, however, excel when she's allowed to play with other puppies and has even shown progress in becoming better socialized towards people.

Kora has already received 2/3 of her first year puppy vaccines with the final round coming due on Nov. 26. She's also received her rabies and bordetella vaccinations, been de-wormed and treated for parasites. Kora's adopter must agree to having her spayed by Feb 1, 2021 and provide proof of such to our rescue. Kora will need all of her basic training, which should come easy for this very smart girl.

To apply for the adoption of Kora, please submit an application at socorescue.com (no need to register or login).

animal.description:
Meet beautiful Bella Whimsy!!! Whimsy is a Lab mix, approximately 5 years old, and weighing around 80 pounds. She was originally found as a stray and was adopted four years ago after coming New Jersey. The adoptive family has loved her, but the longer she stayed, the more protective she became of the home against other animals. She would need to be the only dog in the house and there should not be other small animals of any kind. She has no problem with children she has met, though she has never lived with them and can sometimes play a little too rough. And older child with dog experience or all adult home would be best.

Whimsy is house trained, crate trained, and walks well on a leash. If she's doing something wrong, she is easily redirected and minds very well, and she loves to play in the yard. Because of her habit of guarding against other dogs, she would do best in a home with a solid privacy fence or a fenced area that is not right along any road or sidewalk. She would be a great hiking/running companion, but also knows how to enjoy a good lazy day lounging around the house.

If you are interested in meeting Bella Whimsy, go to EHRDOGS.ORG and submit an application. Don't forget to ask for BELLA WHIMSY LONESTAR!!!

animal.description:
**Looking for a temporary foster home - not up for adoption!**
**This animal is located near Santa Fe, NM**

Dew Paws Rescue assists in the care of dogs in local pueblos. Brownie is getting ready to get a "fast-kill" shot for heartworm treatment and will need a foster home in Santa Fe, El Dorado, or surrounding area that can host her for a month or so during recovery. The 30 days post-treatment is a very dicey time for dogs recovering from heartworm. Dogs must be kept resting with minimal activity; this means resting/crate time and only short walks and yard time to potty. They cannot do activities that will raise their heart rate or get them overly excited (no running, playing with other dogs, hiking, etc,). So we are looking for a quiet, restful home that can help keep Brownie restful and low energy during recovery.

Brownie is a sweet, somewhat shy dog, who is very easy to handle once she gets acclimated (she might take a few days to get used to new people/situations). A foster home with an enclosed yard would be ideal since she will need to go out for potty breaks but not long walks. Brownie is approx. 50 lbs. 

Crates, equipment, food provided. You just be the dog-nurse in a quiet home! If interested in fostering, please email infodewpaws@gmail.com

animal.description:
Last April we took in two dogs - Fischie and Maddie - whose owner had been killed in a traffic accident.

Maddie is WONDERFUL with us...loving, sweet, non-destructive, housebroken and dog-door trained. She truly is a GREAT dog...but we believe the large number of other dogs (primarily handicapped and senior) here is simply too much for Maddie to deal with. She is dog-selective and should be an only dog.

She would be happier as an only dog with one or two adult people who could give her time and affection....

Maddie is somewhere about 8 years old, a Newfoundland X Black lab...a big girl. 

When she arrived, Maddie had a major, neglected ear infection.Before she leaves we will be running through one more round of antibiotic ear medications just to insure her ear has finally healed.... 

Although we realize she needs a different home, we wanted to keep her here til she was healthy.

For Maddie's sake, so she can have "her" person or people (she is equally good with men or women) she needs to be adopted out to a loving no-animal home, experienced with large dogs.

An adult or two who are home a lot, or work from home, would be ideal. 

She needs a fenced yard and a dog door, but the yard doesn't have to be terribly large, just with comfortable shaded areas. 

We do home checks and reference checks with your Veterinarian, work and friends to insure she will have a safe home. Maddie is spayed and up to date with all shots. Medical records are available.

Again, she is a really wonderful, affectionate and loving dog....Maddie has had a very tough year.

animal.description:
Trooper here and, ohhhhhh, what a story I have! You may remember I landed at rescue from Barrow County Animal Shelter with a bad leg back in July of 2020. They sent me to the vet for an x-ray and OUCH! I’m not going to lie, it wasn’t pretty. But if you know this rescue, you know they also have an amazing vet who is good at putting little guys like me back together (you might remember Sawyer, Teddy and many more).

After extensive surgery to repair things, I spent a good month at Dr. Wright’s with his wonderful staff to recover. I was released in August and then needed to spend three months at the rescue ranch with the other dogs. I mostly had to rest in a crate (boo!), but once I started showing improvement, I got to run a lot and play. I especially love playing with this shy, cute girl here named Billie.

I begin hydrotherapy sessions on 11/10/20 here in Georgia (the first of a series that should be continued for a while), but doc has cleared me for adoption to someone who understands my situation and is willing to work with me. The rescue will be more than happy to work with you on that, too.

Because I’m so active again, I’ll definitely need that fenced yard. I also like most dogs, but I’d like to meet yours before we seal the deal.

Come see me at

http://www.jackrusselladoptions.org/

animal.description:
Meet Babygirl! Her name really is fitting for her personality. She is the sweetest girl you’ll ever meet! Babygirl loves everyone she meets and everyone loves her right back. 
Babygirl is a Weimaraner/pit mix around 1.5 years old and 70 pounds. She was found as a stray by Acadia Animal Control and at risk for euthanasia before being saved by Take Paws. 
Babygirl’s ideal day would be cuddling with her forever family on the couch and getting belly rubs - she loves to snuggle and will do anything to be right next to people. One of her favorite activities is playing with her foster mom’s 12yr old cousins and getting all the pets from them. 
Babygirl would do best in home with dogs her size or larger (but she’s also content being an only dog who gets all the attention). She loves to give hugs when she meets new people (which she is working on) and kisses. 
She has a calm and loving temperament and is low maintenance, but will also play with her foster brother and has done great at parties with people. She gets along with dogs and cats. She has met children as young as 8 and did fine, but has not been tested with anyone younger. 
Babygirl is great on car rides, she loves to sunbathe and snuggle. She has been doing great walking on her harness. 
She is house trained, working on basic commands, but prefers to eat separately from her foster brother. 
She is working on kennel training as well but would much rather not have the kennel separating you and her. 
Babygirl would make the perfect companion for any family however big or small. Her foster parents think she would do well in a home with other dogs but who has a submissive personality. She is up to date on all shots/vaccinations, spayed, and just started heartworm treatment.

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2020 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

Reba has an auburn/red short smooth coat with a patch of white on her chest, white socks on her paws, a long tail, and a lovely face with copper-colored eyes, a slender muzzle, a cute red/liver-colored nose, and large semi-erect ears.  

This little sweetheart has an affectionate, rather demure, disposition and a gentle easygoing personality.  Reba loved attention while she had her glamour photos taken and kept a watchful eye on cars pulling into the parking lot.

Our kennel techs have learned that Reba is ok with other dogs, but she does not do well with children or cats.

Reba weighs 57.8 lbs and walks fairly well on a leash.  She will be spayed before being adopted by her new family.

UPDATE: Reba was spayed on November 23, 2020 and was also given rabies vaccine.

animal.description:
These little siblings have lived their life outdoors.  Their surrendering owner is an older lady who wasn't able to find homes for this litter, and couldn't physically care for them.  They shed - for all those who have inquired.

With a guesstimated birthday in Aug. 2019, all of these pups are under 25 lb.  They're learning that being safe indoors is a blessing.  Each is shy, but catching on to house / crate / leash training.  The girls are scheduled for spay in late-Dec., so won't be ready for adoption until they recuperate.

Burr is house-trained if kept on a regular schedule (currently every 2 hours for a potty break).  He'll wait all night in his crate for the morning potty break.  He's given a final walk around 8 p.m., then wakes up with his foster mom around 5 - 6 a.m.  

He's showing confidence on leash walks around his foster's yard.  He likes living in the house now and will prance around the kitchen, playing with the other fosters.  He'll chase the cats if they'll run, but doesn't seem interested in hurting them.  He's comfy in a 30" crate to allow him to sprawl.  

April 2020:  We are not holding public adoption events at this time.  Qualified families are being invited to appointments to meet specific dogs.  There are currently no opportunities to view multiple dogs and adoption events aren't being held at Tractor Supply in Lenoir.

Whether dogs / puppies come in as strays or owner surrenders, we usually have to make our best guess as to birthdate and breed.   

If adopted into a home with other animals, particularly cats, your new pet should be crated or secured when you're not available to supervise to insure a harmonious relationship.  

A vet reference is required to confirm responsible pet ownership.  We suggest first time pet owners look for an adult dog for companionship and to gain experience through another rescue or your local government-run animal control..

Adoption fee covers two vaccinations plus spay / neuter if using our local low-cost spay/neuter clinic (overnight stay required) and surgery occurs as agreed upon in the adoption contract.  Convenience fee equal to refundable spay/neuter deposit may be added if using our veterinarian.  Additional fees for 3rd puppy vaccination, refundable spay/neuter deposit, etc. may apply.  

We are an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue.  We receive no funding from agencies.  Available animals can be seen most Saturdays at Tractor Supply in Lenoir from 10:00 a.m. to 2:00 p.m.  We recommend interested parties contact us to pre-qualify for adoption so their new furry family can go home once paperwork is complete.  Fees are required in cash.  For more information on our organization, our website is www.petpartnersrescue.org.

animal.description: Hi!  My name is Benji and I am a 12 week old  Aussie x border collie mix.  I am what is known as a "double merle" a genetic anomaly that occurs when two merles are bred together (either by accident or on purpose). The gene causes my coat to be mostly white and often causes varying degrees of deafness and/or blindness.  I am deaf and very slightly visually impaired.  But, don't let my hearing impairment stop you from adopting me!  I am really no different than any other puppy...well, my foster mom says I'm actually smarter than most puppies!  I am learning sign language and already know 5 different signs, including, "sit", "stay", "potty", "eat" and "come". I am a happy, spunky, playful boy that loves meeting new people and playing with other dogs.   When I'm not wrestling with my brother (Casey) or pouncing on stuffed toys, I am following my foster mom around the house singing to her. I love to sing!  I am doing really well on my crate-training, leash-walking and potty training and am up-to-date on my vaccinations.  If you are interested in completing an application for me, please contact kathie@herdinghaven.org

animal.description:
Hi I’m Ms Bernice (10-13yrs) and I’m looking for a relaxed retirement home with a family that will love me for me!  A little about me-
I like the great outdoors so short walks and outside play (ok play is a strong word) are important to me.
I need to wear a seresto collar because fleas are gross and I’m allergic. 
Medicated bathes every week or two keep my hair and skin beautiful. 
I eat proplan lamb and rice and I’m doing well on that. 
I ride great in the car and enjoy outings. 
I’m a pro at using the dog door to go out. 
I like to sleep with my people. I move kinda slow and have typical old dog struggles
My bloodwork shows that I have renal disease so a proper diet and I will sometimes need subq fluids. 
If you would love to meet me, adopt me, or maybe even foster me then please apply! 
If you find it in your heart and have the time and love to spare then-
Do a BIG thing and love an old dog!

animal.description:
Hi there, my name is McCartney! I am a very handsome 1-year old yellow lab that weighs 105 pounds. My goal weight is 130 pounds...yes, I'm a very big boy bander and will enjoy putting on those extra pounds! I am still a puppy even though I am very big so please keep that in mind. 

I am a very sweet and loving guy my foster mom says. I'm a gentle giant that doesn't have a mean bone in his body. In fact, I can be a little timid around other dogs until I get to know them. I really need a dog in my new home so that I can have someone to play with and run around with. I will just need to meet them first.  I love to chew on bones, so I hope I get to have some at my new home. It’s a must that I go to a home with a fenced-in yard, so that I can safely play outside.  I have been around teenagers and I do great with them but shouldn't have any kids younger than 8 in the house. I have a cat in my foster home and I don't bother it so a home with a cat will be okay too.  My foster mom says that I am very intelligent but that I will need obedience training and some leash training (due to my strength) so we can go on family walks to burn off my puppy energy.

I’m almost housebroken…I would say I’m at 98%.  I know that once I get used to a new routine I will get it down asap! I am already crate-trained so you won't have to worry about that either. If you are looking for a handsome and sweet boy to join your band...give me that audition!

If you are interested in meeting me, please contact LOLIN for a meet and greet.

If you are interested in adopting, please go to our website at www.lolin.org and click on Adoption Process along the left-hand side.  From there, you can submit an Adoption Application to be considered for this dog.  You MUST be an approved applicant to meet LOLIN dogs.  There is no central location or hours to meet dogs.
