animal.description:
Who is looking for a spry lass with a playful spirit ... look no further than me your little Abby Grace! I mean little is 60 pounds right? I'm a happy girl whether we are relaxing in the house or out hiking. As long as I'm by your side nothing could be better! I need slow intros with other pups and no cats please! Won't you give me a real shot.

Abby Grace is a 7 year old, 60 pound cataloula mix. She is UTD, spayed and chipped. She is also house broken and crate trained. She is not well socialized and would do best in a home without other pets but could do well in an experienced home with slow intros. 

Unfortunately, Abby does not get along with cats at all and is in a home with cats so the current owners would like to see her in a home better suit for her.

Adoption requirements are as such:


	No other pets or a submissive dog in a very experinced home willing to do slow intros 
	No children under 16 
	Large breed experience 
	Experience with insecure dogs 


Please note, Abby Grace is part of Happy Trails Animal Rescues rehoming program. She has not been tested or evaluated and the information gathered is from the current owners personal statements regarding health and temperament. The owner is subject to placement outside of our organization. We cannot guarantee availability.

animal.description:
Chubbs and Glorious are 3 year old Mastiff mixes that are a bonded pair. They are playful, loving, and make you laugh at how silly they are. They love affection and are the sweetest pups ever. They are food motivated and sure love to cuddle and give you kisses. They would do best in a home with older children. Please check back for updates as my foster family gets to know me. You can also watch for stories, pictures, and videos about me on JR's Pups-N-Stuff's Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/groups/40103261297/. Ask to meet us today!!
 
Adoption fee: $800 for the pair

Adoption fees for all dogs/puppies include a $50 refundable training deposit. Complete your basic training program and provide a copy of the certificate within 4 months (120 days) of adoption and we will refund $50 of the original adoption fee.
 
All dogs/puppies have been fully vetted including spay/neuter, micro-chipping, worming, heartworm testing and preventative treatment, flea/tick preventative, and all required age appropriate vaccinations. As required by Wisconsin Act 90, all dogs will have received a veterinarian exam (CVI) within the past 30 days.
 
Our adoption process requires the submission of an application. Applications and Adoption Rules can be found on our website, on the "HOW TO ADOPT" tab at JRsPupsNStuff.org. Upon receipt of the completed application, we will process the application including: contact with your veterinarian and completion of a home visit. Please be sure to include the contact information for your vet as we will call. If your vet requires an information release, please be sure to contact them as soon as you submit your application. We are a group of volunteers with families and jobs, so please be patient and allow a few days for our response.
 
JR's Pups-N-Stuff Dog Sellers License 270089-DS

My name is Rani. I am still just a big goofy pup. I have been working hard on my basic obedience and learning that it is not appropriate to jump on people to get their attention. Sometime I just get so excited that I still forget. I should probably not live with small children or pets until I learn to control my excitement a little better. I wouldn't want them to accidentally get hurt. My last family moved away hoping I could eventually be sent to them, but the transportation to get me there did not work out. So... here I am in the shelter waiting for a new family. Could it be you???

animal.description:
This adorable, happy boy is 2 year-old Teo.  Teo is not only suuuper handsome, but he’s very polite and well-mannered too!  Teo loves long walks and playing fetch almost as much as he loves treats!  However, he’s also totally content napping in a soft, comfy place in the house while he patiently waits for his people to play with him.  He’ll even very sweetly remind you that he’s there by gently resting his head on your lap and gazing up at you with his hazel eyes...how precious is that?! 

Teo is still learning to trust new people, so all that he asks is that you’re patient and understanding while he gets to know you.  And the payoff is AMAZING, as Teo is about as loving and loyal as they come!  Teo hasn’t had much training or socialization in the past, so he’ll need proper introductions and supervision with other dogs.  Additionally, his ideal family will be willing and able to provide him structure and continued training. 

Please help us get sweet Teo into a safe, loving forever home!  If you're unable to help by adopting, sharing this post or donating is always appreciated.  Don't forget, Passion for Pitties is a 501(c)(3), so all donations are tax-deductible!…every little bit helps!
 
If you would like to adopt loving Teo, please fill out an application at www.passionforpitties.com under the “Adorable Adoptables” heading.

animal.description:
This dashingly handsome older gentleman is Rocko, and he is an amazing senior looking for his forever home. He was down and out in North Carolina, and was underweight and had some skin issues and missing fur. He needed a second chance and some TLC so he was transported up to a foster home in New Hampshire where he has been getting healthier and is now ready to find his forever home.

Rocko was originally aged at 12 years old, but as he gets healthier he gets more active and vibrant so he might be younger than we first thought. He loves toys, playing fetch, walks, couch snuggles, and any kind of love and affection he can get from his humans. He could potentially live with a female dog, but a home without cats or  male dogs would be best. We think he would really enjoy being an only dog since he is all about his humans.

We are partnering with The Grateful Dog Animal Rescue to find Rocko some new digs. He is a total rockstar, and we just know the right home and human are out there waiting for this wonderful old guy! 

PLEASE NOTE - We will check your veterinary reference, to ensure that current and prior pets have a history of being kept up to date on vaccines, annual exams and recommended bloodwork. We also do home checks to make sure that your home environment meets the needs of the particular dog you are interested in.

If you’re interested in adoption, please fill out our online adoption survey at https://www.olddogsnewdigs.com/adoption-survey/

animal.description:
In November 2020,  Real Time Rescue was contacted by Banning Veterinary Hospital in the Hi-Desert area. They explained that an elderly woman had called asking about euthanizing her two dogs, who were under three years old and healthy. She let them know that the reason for her call was she could no longer care for them and didn’t know what to do. Instead of scheduling an appointment, they gave them our number. Their daughter reached out to explain that she had just moved back to help her parents- her father had been diagnosed with Parkinson’s 6mos earlier and recently her mother with fibromyalgia. All three were surviving on very limited funds and the dogs, Bella & Buddy, spent their lives outside. She further explained that when her mother called a local shelter and asked what would happen to them if they turned them in, she was told if not adopted quickly they would be euthanized due to an already over crowded shelter. Her next call was Banning Vet, feeling that euthanizing them there would be the better option over a shelter taking care of it. This is a woman who did really want what was best for her dogs but didn’t have any idea how to help them with the resources provided to her. RTR let the family know we could help, but we’d have to find fosters first… and thanks to the rescue gods, we did! 

Buddy  is around 2 years old. Both he and his sister Bella went directly to one of our trusted vets in Orange County and were given a clean bill of health and vaccinated. Both have now been safe and cozy in foster homes since then, decompressing and learning the ropes on how to live indoors. We are told that this boy is a sweet, playful and just generally always pretty happy. He has a goofy puppy way about him and LOVES belly rubs!

Buddy is still working with his fosters on a still new to him potty training routine, but  ready for adoption and hoping you’ll apply to be the next to meet him!

animal.description:
Casey is a senior, who doesn't act it. She is playful & loves walks..is easy to care for, will snuggle in bed or on the sofa w/ you. Shelter was told by the person 'dropping her off that she was 15 (even the vet doubts she is that old) & was not dieing "quick enough", so they wanted to leave her at the shelter to get a PUPPY. I feel sorry for the puppy who will be neglected & get heartworms & never feel real love by a human. Casey's SMILE got to me, & we hope for someone who wants a very senior lady to give that love for her senior time. She is such a happy dog..she is not as big as she looks! Casey is sleeping w/one foster & 3 homes are sharing her! She is a delight! She would be best w/not many stairs, as she has one hind leg she will  hold up, but x-rays so no evidence of a problem & as an only dog or with another older dog(she has lived w/ another dog & a bunny...She has not had experience w/ much & is so happy to be getting love & loves being a house dog!  ^^there is some discussion if she is an American Staff. Terrier (Pit) but the shelter thought the people CUT her ears (they did it themselves which is CRUEL to imagine for Casey to have endured) to make her look more like a 'bully breed' ....we never know the dna & should look into working w/ a company who would offer us a discount to find out !!!
***
Thank you for your interest in applying to adopt ! Events slowly being scheduled due to pandemic.....watch LOVE Mutts Rescue Facebook for all calendar events, & info. Meet by appointment w/ approved application.  Website, has current available pets, links to donation (we are non-profit) & to adopt & volunteer www.lovemuttsrescue.org  We will email you our process & fees. When in "foster to adopt", pets are taken off our website, but may be relisted w/in 2 weeks, if not a final adoption. The Love Mutts Rescue Team

animal.description: I am one of the doggies that has the biggest smile! Not everything started that bright though. My family abandoned their house a year ago and then brought me back during the cold spell and snow of April, chained me to the fence and left. When I first came in, I wasn’t quite sure what was happening and definitely did not have very good manners. I am a passionate dog and would often get overly excited so not the best way to interact with everyone. The Canine Care staff has spent a lot of time working with me, helping me understand positive ways to show when I am happy, playful or if something bugs me. I enjoy playing with toys and will sit nicely for some treats. All this is fine but I would really love to find a committed home, willing to continue working with me. I’m quite smart and loving so hope to find someone very special.

Meet Mama, a precious five-year-old, 44 lb. pit mix. She was found as a stray in North Carolina before ending up in a high kill shelter. It was immediately clear that this girl has been through a lot and we believe she was a throwaway backyard breeding mama. She is now in Connecticut ready to find her happily furever after!

Mama is an affectionate sweetheart who loves cuddles and being next to her people. Her wagging tail and beautiful smile will show you how happy she is! She would love to find a comfy couch to relax on and after a quick walk, she's ready to for more snuggles. If you're looking for a low energy dog and professional couch potato, this girl is the one for you! With all the trauma she has endured, Mama would prefer to be an only pet.

Her adoption fee is $350 and she is up to date on vaccines, microchipped, heartworm negative, and spayed. If you are interested in adopting Mama, please complete the application at form.jotform.com/200883908893166 or email info@happilyfureverafter.org.

animal.description:
Red is a very special boy, in need of a very special home. Red is almost completely deaf, he may pick up on some deep vibrations or high pitched sounds but for the most part should be considered deaf. His deafness is very manageable for even a home unfamiliar with deaf dogs, but potential families should be very experienced with Heeler behaviors.

The Good: Red becomes the single most loyal friend to those who earn his trust but Red's deafness makes meeting new people and dogs stressful for him. Once earned, there is truly not a more loyal dog. He loves 100% and gives everything to his person. He adores them and would always protect his family and home. Don't let his deafness fool you, this pup would make an excellent watchdog for those he loves. Red loves car rides, giving hugs, and belly rubs most in life. He is constantly watching for hand signals and therefore has great "recall", even off leash. Red is very smart. He also knows sit, down, come, and wait from hand signals.

The Bad: Red needs a VERY special family willing to give him a two week adjustment period just to acclimate to their schedule and movements. Red needs a very experienced home that "speaks dog" and can understand dog body lanaguage. After growing up deaf and startled too many times, Red doesnt trust hands, and even "good" touches like petting from someone he doesnt know are just too much for him at first. He needs 2 weeks of being completely ignored while he learns everything is okay to allow him to become comfortable at his own pace. 2 weeks of No touching- seriously. Just completely out right ignored so he can watch and learn. His anxiety largely stems from his deafness that he over compensates and can be overstimulated when he's uncomfortable. As a heeler, Red's instincts tell him to herd it away if his trust is violated by a stranger and as a heeler that can mean nipping. It's only when strangers overstep, that he results to that level. Once through the "trust building" period, Red becomes rock solid and is completely trustworthy, allowing feet, eyes, ears etc. to be touched with no problems whatsoever. 

Red needs a home without kids or other dogs who may not understand his needs, disability, and anxiety. Red has excellent cattle dog herding instincts but his hearing impairment currently prevents him from training with cattle directly but he would love any form of "work" or regular exercise (especially mental exercises).

Red needs a very unique and experienced home, but he's a very special dog himself. If you are looking for a truly loyal companion, then Red may be the dog for you.

animal.description:
Meet Jade!
Jade is a pretty calm gal but has spurts of puppy energy when she gets a toy or claims her spot on the couch. 
Jade is slow to warm up to strangers, especially men. When she is ready to trust you, she is 100% loyal and dedicated. She will love everyone in the house, but one person will become “her” hooman.
Jade had an injury to her left back leg in the past. But she doesn't let it slow her down. She has no pain or discomfort and she can get around, jump up, and balance like most other dogs. 
Jade enjoys short walks, soft couches/blankets/pillows, and any chance to soak up sunshine. She will follow the sunshine all day to ensure she doesn’t miss it.
The right person for Jade needs to be patient and willing to earn her trust. It will take time, but the love she has to give is worth it. 
Jade will need to be introduced slowly to new dogs and she is fine with cats. Jade goes out the doggy door without a problem. She will go in the crate if it’s set up as a cave with lots of soft bedding but she won’t be happy for long. She wants to be with her people.
If this sweet girl sounds like a great addition to your home, get your application in today!

PLEASE READ COMPLETELY 

All of our moms are being raised in volunteer foster homes, so we do not have a single location to visit. You will need to submit an application to be approved for a Meet and Greet.

If you are interested in adopting or more information please do the following before contacting Path of Hope: 

1. Go to our website www.pathofhoperescue.com 
2. Thoroughly read through the FAQ section on the "Adopt" page (this will answer most questions!)
3. If you are still interested, fill out an online application on our website and our Matchmaker will be in touch with you! 
4. Follow us on facebook, https://www.facebook.com/pathofhoperescue/ , to see lots of cute puppie photos. learn about puppy events, and get updates on the rescue!

Our adoption fee for mom dogs is $300 and includes age appropriate core vaccines, minimum two rounds of dewormer, microchip with free registration and spay/neuter surgery. A refund of $100 is available with completion of any training class.

animal.description:
? Meet Camo ?

3 year old Pit/hound mix at 65 pounds.

Camo will be three years old in December. He loves the taste of carot cake with peanut butter icing. His favorite treats include apples, carrots, jerky, biscuits, and peppers. He is not picky and will be sure to shake your hand for a treat.

Camo is house trained and is not a destructive boy, however he does like to chew up old toilet paper rolls and plastic bottles.

He loves walks, swimming, chasing squirrels, car rides, his vet, fetch, and training. He is also a lover of blankets and will climb into bed to snuggle all while wrapping himself up in a little pittie burrito.

Camo knows the commands give paw, high five, kiss, stand up, up there (for a couch), lay down, roll over, boop it, and focus on me.

Camo is a sweet boy, but he just loves his food and toys to much. He is a resource guarder around other animals and his future family needs to understand his needs. He would do best in a home as an only dog.

He is a loving boy who just needs to find a place of his own with a family who can give him the love and attention he deserves.

If the animal is under the age of 3 years old or has health issues, a vet reference is required which means you must own a pet or have owned a pet in your name.

Adoption fee of $250 covers all vetting including spay/neuter surgery, vaccines, microchip heartworm test and treatment if needed and any other medical that may be required while in rescue. 

We only do adoptions on Saturday and not all animals are able to attend so if you would like to see a specific animal please let us know so that we can make arrangements for it to be present at the event. Event locations do vary so please check the homepage to find out where we will be this week. Please do not ask us to reduce adoption fees since all fees help us to cover medical expenses for all of our animals, some of which can be very expensive.  Saving lives is not cheap so thank you for your understanding and helping us save as many as possible.

Please email lowcountryanimalrescue@ymail.com for an application.

animal.description: Hello beautiful humans!  Remember me, Chrissy? I was found on the side of the road a few months ago in very sad shape.  I’m sling great at my foster home.    Every morning I sing for my breakfast - and it's the only time you'll hear me at all.  My foster mom thinks it's funny because I have to tell her how to cook every day.  Just wanted to share a couple of things...I'm getting more confident everywhere.  I can let my foster mom be out of my sight for fifteen minutes now without following and I insist on visiting next door every evening at suppertime with my canine foster brother.  I get along fine with their three dogs and four cats.  I also wanted to let you know that I'm deaf.  Or at least I hear very little.  My foster mom is trying to learn how to communicate with me, especially since I don't look at her much, and we're working on signs for food and come.  At the risk of immodesty, I'll share that she's very, very proud of me and how much I've accomplished.  I survived, learned to move around again, smile, and hold my tail high, and have met sooo many scary situations and been a really good girl (a little warning growl doesn't count).  And I did it without hearing.  I am awesome.  Thank you for saving my life.

animal.description:
Harley is an adorable 2 year old pitbull terrier looking for a new forever home. 

Harley has a lot of energy and needs routine physical exercise along with mental enrichment. This cutie has some anxiety and confidence issues, causing her to be reactive towards other animals. Unfortunately for these reasons, she is being returned to us. 
Harley is looking for a forever home that loves adventure and exploring. She would do best in a home with a nice fenced in yard. Since she is reactive out in public, having a fenced in back yard would give her a safe space of her very own to exercise in. Small children are overwhelming for Harley and she would do best in a home with children age 12 or older. 
Due to Harley's behavior challenges, she's looking for an experienced adopter that has lots of time to put into building a bond with her. Harley is currently taking medication to help with her anxiety issues and we feel that with a well fit person, she will live a successful and full life. It is important that her new human or humans understand the importance of routine, positive reinforcement training, physical and mental exercise and setting her up for success.  She is eager to bond and is a very affectionate and loyal companion. 
 
Harley must be the only pet in her new home. 

If you feel that you may be a good match for Harley, please submit an adoption application on our website: www.offthechainmke.org

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Harley need to be the only pet in her forever home.

animal.description:
I'm a very friendly and energetic Pointer mix who loves to be loved. I was flown from Louisiana to Wisconsin by Wings of Rescue and I can't wait to find a home here in the land of beer and cheese! My personality is best described as "all about the love" and I adore giving and receiving affection. I am a very high energy dog so daily exercise is an absolute must for me. I will need physical activity (going for walks, running, playing) along with mental stimulation (learning new tricks, playing with puzzle toys, eating from puzzle feeders) to keep me happy and healthy. I can be picky about other dogs and would be perfectly pleased to be your only pet. I'm looking for an active and involved adopter who has plenty of time for a high energy dog. I'm approved for respectful children aged 10 and up and will be a fun addition to an active family. If you're looking for an exceptionally intelligent and loving companion, I'm ready to be your number one exercise and snuggle buddy! Reign is approved for families with respectful children aged 10 and up. He is a high energy dog who needs both physical and mental stimulation.

The online adoption listing websites require that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our dogs. Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We encourage you to select your new companion by considering each dog's individual personality and pet qualities instead of relying on a breed label that is only a guess. 2/2/21 3:20 PM

She was shaking scared when we picked her up from the shelter but within a few days at her loving foster home, she already started following the family around the house and enjoys lounging next to them on the couch. She's a sweet dog who is very mellow.

Marley was originally found on the streets by a local shelter along with her puppy. A different rescue took the puppy in the next day but left momma Marley behind :( She waited over 100 days in the shelter and was finally adopted but they returned her a year later bc they moved somewhere that didn't allow dogs. We took Marley into our care once we found out she was back at the shelter. We look forward to finding a loving forever family that will cherish her!

Marley's adoption fee is $225 plus tax and that covers her spay, microchip, vaccinations, heartworm test (she tested negative) and she is on heartworm/flea/tick prevention. She will make an awesome addition to a lucky family!

Here's the link to turn in an application and learn more about our adoption process:

https://www.thestreetdogproject.org/adopt

Please email placement@thestreetdogproject.org if you have any questions, thanks!

animal.description:
Posting for Cuzzo the goofball pity.

BIG DOG.  Fully vetted.  friendly with all. Sometimes my size intimidates other dogs.  He was left outside for long time by people who cared about him but
worked out of town 

Hi, y'all!!! Cuzzo, here. First and foremost, I'm a gentlemen.....well, most times. Sometimes, as my foster mom would say, I'm a GOOFBALL. What can I say? I'm just trying to enjoy life to the fullest after many years living in a cage. AND, it was OUTSIDE!!! BUURRRR!!!! So, please, no more sleeping outside for me, unless I'm working on my tan. 
Anywho, that life is behind me.

Now, I am ready for a new adventure and a family that will love me just as I am, (AWESOME and CUDDLY, of course!!!!). I do like attention, Ahem!..I mean, LOVE, attention from hoomans. I get along well with my other foster dogs, but we need to be introduce properly. Other dogs tends to be intimidated by my size (Foster mom is working on HELPING me lose a few pounds. She thinks I don't know that she feeds me HEALTHY WEIGHT food. But that's ok, I know it's outta love and, besides, it taste lots better than what I used to eat.) I am more than ok if you want me as the only one (hint, hint).
Moving on, as mentioned before, I love you hoomans, but it would be best if you are big hoomans and not little ones that I can "bump" into. Hey, sometimes I just get all excited and just NEED to express it by doing my version of zoomies, alright?

animal.description:
Zayla is bonded with another dog Tuxedo. They've been together every step of the way--from running at large as strays, to everyday walks and nightly cuddles. They are inseparable, so they need to be rehomed together. 

Who knows what this old couple have been through? The only thing clear is that they have survived it together. 
Zalya and Tuxedo are the unbelievably easy houseguests. They do not pay any attention to our old cat, are house trained and, while they love treats, they do not beg for food. In fact, their only bad habit is sleeping on the couch! 
Tuxedo likes short walks while Zayla is just relieved to have a soft bed for her old bones. They both get nervous if he is gone too long. Zayla's arthritis makes stairs and long walks difficult but she loves our fenced yard and enjoys hanging out in the sun and sniffing the grass. She still gets around well, just slowly and not far. Tux would rather be with people and often calls Zayla back into the house when he is ready to be with his humans again. He is all about affection and will sit with you for hours if you will just pet him. He would love to be a giant lap dog if you let him!
Zayla is still very scared of people and we struggle to get a leash on her. She cries when we try to touch her but she has been in foster care for less than two weeks and is already taking treats from our hands and sniffing our fingers if we move slowly. On the other hand, she is very expressive and often woofs and wiggles (her arthritis does not allow for more) to show how happy she is to see us. We are hopeful that in a quiet, safe home she will have the opportunity to learn to trust humans again. 
Tuxedo is her voice, he tells us when Zayla needs water, or food, or to go outside. I imagine taking these two might seem daunting, but they really are exceptionally bonded. And, this old pair are as easy going, gentle and kind as any prospective family could want. Generally, they are just so grateful for a calm home, regular meals, kind words and a warm bed for two. Or, better yet, a couch for two!

animal.description:
***Shelly is currently located at our Georgia facility. She is also available for adoption in the New Jersey and surrounding areas.***

When the SoCo staff arrived at work one morning, they found a yellow Lab sitting in the parking lot. "Shelly", as we later named her, had apparently been discarded at SoCo during our closed hours. There was no note or other communication to explain why Shelly had been left at our rescue.

Shelly wasted no time in showing us exactly how friendly and wonderful she was. She made friends with all of our staff rather quickly. She loves to play fetch, loves to run wide open and loves her playtime with people. She's smart, a quick learner and even already knows her basic commands.

Shelly's initial dog-friendly test didn't go very well but that may have been due to the commotion within the rescue. We would recommend a meet-and-greet with any other dogs that Shelly would share a home with, but she may need to be the only dog in the home. We don't think she'll be good with cats.

Shelly was heartworm positive when she arrived but has since been treated. She's also been spayed, received an update on her yearly vaccinations, de-wormed and kept on her monthly preventatives. While Shelly shows some house training experience, she may need a refresher course once in a new home

If interested in adopting Shelly, please submit an application at socorescue.com (no need to register or login)

animal.description:
Hi my name is Charming! I’m 5 years old and 13 lbs!  I would love a home where my owners are home a lot.  I experience separation anxiety when I am left home alone too often.

Bio for Charming:

Well hello. My name is Charming and for good reason. I am a sweet-natured, friendly little guy with a quirky personality that will make you laugh out loud. I am five years old and 13 pounds -- who knew this much charm could fit in such a little body? Here’s what my foster family has learned about me so far:

•	I love to be close to my humans! I do a full body wiggle and prance when I see my foster mom and I'm her loyal shadow. Snuggling on the couch with my people at the end of the day is one of my favorite activities. How about a scratch behind the ear or a belly rub too?

•	I’m gentle with the little kids in my foster home but their loud noises and rowdy movements sometimes make me a little nervous. I’d be happiest in a home with older kids who understand to give me space when I need it.

•	My big foster dog brother is so fun! We love to play, go for walks together and take naps on the couch near each other.

•	While my favorite place is wherever you are, I’m happy to hang out in my crate too. I eat meals there, sleep quietly through the night and take rest breaks there a couple times a day. I keep my crate clean and dry.

•	I’ve been doing really well with my potty manners in my foster home. I go out for backyard breaks every few hours. My favorite reward for doing all my business outside is to go right back inside where it’s warm. Brr!

•	I walk very well on a leash and I’m happy to go where you go. (But could you please not walk me through the snow? This cold, wet stuff is awful!)

•	Benebones and natural chews are great! I’m not a big chewer but every once in a while, I love to sink my teeth into a dog toy.

•	I’m not a barker--my foster mom has never heard me woof!--but that doesn’t mean I don’t make noise. When I get a good neck scratch from my human, I close my eyes and let out a long, happy hum. Mmmmm that feels great!

•	My foster mom thinks my cutest quality is the way I get comfortable on the couch. I like to fluff, test and circle my resting spot for a few minutes before I settle. Sometimes I get so into it that I do a silly little somersault.

If you’re looking for a loving, loyal and spunky little companion, I hope you’ll come meet me soon!




You can come adopt me or even join our foster program to help the humans learn all the awesome things about new dogs like me! Learn more on our website! 

Hope to see you soon! 

What breed am I? Mixed mutt! ODHS does not breed label (unless there’s official paperwork), as studies show it is nearly impossible to tell the exact breed of each dog based off of their appearance.

Educational article:
3/3/3 rule:
https://www.rescuedogs101.com/bringing-new-dog-home-3-3-3-rule/?fbclid=IwAR2iv5m7fqk3FieO7LOsstGeGsYYV_F1rJOd1BPxaImofLpcinpYsUbFRWs

Adoption Donations are $250 for an adult, $350 for puppies (a dog under one year of age), and $125 for a senior dog (based on the age of the dog). Adoption donations are to be made via cash, and credit/debit card. There is a $5 fee to run cards.

Please remember to bring a collar and leash (non-retractable) with you the day of the adoption. Note: Martingale collars and slip leads are strongly recommended.

Due to COVID19, we aren't having as many open, public adoption events.  Current schedule is pre-determined meet and greet appointments are Wednesday evenings and on Saturday from 12-2.  On Saturday's from 2-4pm, the events are open to the public. 
 Our adoption center is located at 3602 Lafayette Blvd, Suite 102, Fredericksburg, VA 22408. It's important that you keep an eye on your emails for any changes or updates during the adoption process.

Visit our website for an application to adopt. 
https://www.olddominionhumanesociety.org/adoption-application

Old Dominion Humane Society is a volunteer based organization. We are run completely by volunteers, who also have full time jobs, so we appreciate your patience.  Currently, the average timeframe for a response to your application is 1 week.

Like us on Facebook "Old Dominion Humane Society"
and be a part of promoting forever homes for dogs in need.
#Adopt #Donate #Foster #Volunteer 

Note: ODHS only adopts to Virginia and surrounding states (including D.C.). A $50 out of state fee applies.

animal.description: Marley IS AVAILALBE (updated 02-02-2021).To meet any of our dogs you must first complete our online adoption application on our website. For more information and the adoption application for Marley, please visit our website belowhttp://www.coastalgsr.org/dog_profile.php?ID=22315&name=MarleyWe saw a picture of a GSD at the shelter who looked absolutely broken: she couldn't stand, was in obvious pain, looked fearful, and needed help. We rescued her and immediately sent her to our vetThere we discovered it was pyometra, an infection in the uterus. Her uterus was huge and full of pus and her bladder was distended and the size of a volleyball. We can't imagine the pain she'd endured! She did well through surgery and was moved to the emergency hospital where she could receive 24/7 care. It was a few more days, but she was finally able to stand, kept improving, and was then released from the hospital. Marley is crate trained, good in the house, likes a car ride, and does well on a leash. She loves going for walks and can keep up with the best of them! Marley is going to need an experienced home, as she can get overprotective, and needs to be the only dog in the home. She will repay your kindness with lots of affection and ultimate loyalty.The minimum adoption donation for adults is $375 and the adoption donation for puppies is $500. This amount only partially covers the cost of veterinary care, boarding fees, and other miscellaneous expenses involved in the temporary care and adoption of our dogs and is tax deductible. The adoption donation provides that all dogs will be spayed or neutered, receive current vaccinations, and are microchipped. If not, arrangements will be made on an individual basis ( i.e., puppies who will need to be altered by 6 mos old). Special consideration may be given to those willing to adopt older dogs or dogs with physical problems.

If you have ANY QUESTIONS or are truly interested in adopting any animal from PAW Animal Shelter Please, fillout an adoption application FIRST! WE are a high intake No Kill Shelter ran by a staff of 4 and do not always have time to answer every question asked by so many. If you are a good fit for the animal you are interested in -we will call to speak with you, If we feel you are not a good fit , we will contact you about other pets that may be a good fit for your home. Many people are losing the opportunity to adopt the animal they want because they fail to put in an application and the pet was adopted before we could answer your email. .If you have applied for an animal in our facility and have not received a response within 7 days, PLEASE call or contact us again. Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility.

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

animal.description:
Have you met Mac?

8-year-old Mac was brought into the San Diego Humane Society by Humane Law Enforcement. He weighs 12 lbs. Poor little Mac needed to have his right eye removed due to injury and dental surgery to remove 15 yucky teeth. He was slow to trust when he got to Frosted Faces. He didn't like being reached towards in his kennel and would growl and snap if you came in too fast. Mac went on a two-week Frosted Fling for the holidays and wow, once he settles in, a whole little personality comes out!

Mac is house broken and crate trained! He sleeps overnight in his kennel without any midnight potty breaks and has never had an accident in the house! Mac did attempt to mark on his first day, but that behavior quickly stopped when he learned there was a yard for pottying. Mac has great energy and loves to go for walks. He has been to Fiesta Island and always makes it all the way around the loop with energy to spare. Mac lived with a dog and two cats during his Fling and got along great with everyone! He did occasionally chase his kitty Fling brother playfully, but it was never with malice and the cats always came back for more. Mac's major downfall is that he guards his food. His Flingers used a crate for mealtime, and everyone was happy - Mac felt secure without the need to guard, and everyone got to eat their meals in peace. He takes small treats nicely next to other animals.

His Flingers shared, "Mac loves car rides! He stands up so he can look out the window the whole time! When we are on slow roads and have someone to hold the leash (just in case!) we roll the windows down so he can smell the breeze and his little ears flap in the wind. It's so cute! He also loves to play with toys! Mac will bring you his stuffy and set it on your lap so you will throw it for him. Mac was a pro at the food puzzle and really enjoyed using his brain and his nose to find all the treats. Mac takes some time to settle in and feel fully comfortable. During this time, we mostly just let him come to us when he wanted to be interacted with. He lets out a low growl if you are making him feel uncomfortable. If you push it, he will snap, but it seems to be mostly a warning rather than a serious bite. Once he got more comfortable, this behavior went away and he showed his spunky and loving side. Mac loves to sit in your lap on sleep next to you on the couch. He will nest in blankies to make sure they are just the way he likes them and then roll over to show you his belly for some rubbing. He's a super silly guy once he settles in. The family that allows him the time and space he needs to feel safe will get a super fun and loving little buddy!"

Now that Mac has settled in, he gets to stay longer as a foster! He still is on the lookout for his forever family, though! Apply at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm.

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees, and we help with medical costs!

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

Updated 1/14/21 KG

animal.description:
GET OFF MY LAWN!!!!

Yup.  We have all had or currently have one of those cranky old neighbors who just want to be left alone to live their life in peace and quiet.  

Teefers is the embodiment of such a neighbor.

NOW WAIT......before you swipe left....give us a second.

Because what Teefers lacks in the warm fuzzy department, he makes up for in being pretty dang easy to be around.  Well, if you have a sense of humor, move quick and don't get your feelings hurt too easily, that is.  

You don't have to be around this ole guy very long to understand he has been around the block a time or two and has probably never had much of a relationship with humans.  For some dogs, this might mean fear or timid behavior but Teefers is different.  He exudes confidence and dignity and has an air about him that tickles the imagination.  Even the circumstances in which he found himself needing our help, are curious and heartbreaking at the same time.

We first saw Teefers' picture, when the photographer of our local Humane Society shared some "hard to adopt" dogs on a pet Facebook page.  

Hard to adopt?  Why....how could that be? I mean, look how stinking cute he is!!.

Our curiosity peaked, we contacted our shelter and asked if they needed help with him.  He would probably never make it to the adoption floor, given his age and crotchety behavior, so they willingly signed him over to us.   We are no strangers to the fear biters or those who act out because they are in a strange environment so we snatched Teefers up and brought him into our embrace.

We soon found out that Teefers does not suffer fools and baby talk is for sissies.  He's been fooled by baby talkers before so cute coo-ing and goo-ing, does not impress him.  From the very start, he established that touch is allowed with his permission only and if you don't ask first (and even sometimes if you do) he might nail you.  

Yet, we still find this old man charming.  

He is so dignified and sure of himself PLUS when he wants something from you, he is an absolute charmer.  Yep...this guy is no dummy and he's spent a lifetime playing humans like fiddles, to get what he wants.  

Fine...we can work with that.

We posted his picture on our FB page and the comments started to roll in.  Apparently he had been something of a curiosity on the community lost and found pet Facebook pages, where his pictured had been captured several times, as a stray, with a kitchen spatula dragging from his harness.  More comments rolled in about sightings of the funny dog dragging kitchen utensils around but some pretty sad comments said, his owners had been located and their response was, "you found him...you keep him"  

Our hearts broke but our understanding grew.

Maybe Teefers had a reason to be a crank pot.  Perhaps the spatula was how his former owners handled him and if so, what a loveless life he must have lived

We became even more fiercely respectful of him.  Had he ever known affection?  Had he ever been important to someone?   How was he supposed to trust and give when all he seemed to have known is how to get what he wants by using his own cunning.  

So we just let Teefers do his thing.  We fitted him with a harness and let him drag a leash so that we would not have to touch him, to direct him when needed.  To our surprise and thankfulness, this seemed to be an agreeable arrangement with him and he soon learned his daily routine and started to behave a bit less defensively.  He can now be picked up without setting him off and he love love loves his crate with it's snuggly bed and fuzzy blanket.  If he is not outside in the yard, this is where you will find him most of the time.  He also loves going for walks and is great on a leash.  He enjoys car rides and will even grace you with his presence in your lap, if you happen to be in the seat he wants.  Perhaps, if he is feeling super charitable, he might even let you pet him.  We can't tell you what an honor that feels like.  

Teefers is very food motivated too and this is a very fun part of the day for him and his foster.  This is when the relationship between dog and human, feels most normal.  Teefers will get very animated and his tail wags furiously, while he charms treats from the house humans.  He will put his paws on their knees and lays his head on their legs, looking impossibly cute and adorable, just to get a little bite of something tasty.  It's during these moments, where most of the trust between human and canine, has been built upon.

Because he has probably spent most of his life as an outdoor dog, he is a work in progress with housebreaking.  He does however, keeps a very clean crate largely because he does not want to potty in his beloved palace.  If you take him straight from his crate to the outside, he understands what is expected of him but all his years of marking where ever and whenever, have required the use of belly bands indoors, which have turned out to be a fabulous solution to this problem. He has grown accustom to the belly band ritual (taking them off to go outside and putting them back on, when he comes inside) without complaint or grouse.  We are even happy to report that more and more, his belly bands are dry, when taken off to go outside, so he is getting it down but it is a work in progress that may need to be continued in his forever home.  

Teefers is a pretty quiet guy too.  He vocalizes his desire to be out of his crate, to come back in the house or to be fed his dinner or snacks but he does not bark to hear himself bark.  He gets along great with all the dogs in his foster home, big and small, male and female and pretty much ignores the cats and has had no issue, one way or the other, with the horse.  We strongly feel that, where household or barnyard animals are concerned, if they leave him alone, he will leave them alone.   

So what do you think?  He's not conventional and he will make you work for every favor he bestows upon you.  He is open to friendship of convenience and will let you know when you are pushing too fast.  Compared to his attitude when he arrived, he has made respectable progress but we believe Teefers will always be a bit on the cranky, independent side and view humans as a means to an end, be that end, a good scratch where it itches, a tasty treat or a nice walk around the neighborhood.  

Can your ego take it?  Because he's pretty funny and easy company, if it can.

To meet Mr Teefers, please go to our website at www.allmuttsgreatandsmall.org/adoption and fill out the application.  Teefers is one of a kind and there is a special person out there who will understand him and maybe even find his soft spot, with time.

Teefers is between 10 and 12 years old, weighs a solid, 10 pounds, is neutered, has been treated and cleared of intestinal parasites, is up to date on his five way and rabies vaccinations, is microchipped and is scheduled for a dental on December 2nd.  After that, he will be ready to strut his unique, eccentric, dignified, proud, intelligent, sometimes cranky and always adorable little behind, right into your home....AND TAKE OVER!!!!

His adoption fee is $150

.

animal.description:
Libby is a beautiful 12 – 18 mos old, female, Papillion/Pomeranian mix who weighs 14lbs. 

Libby was found as a stray and ended up at the animal shelter, but no one came to take her home. She was scared, stressed and needed help getting adopted from a place with less commotion. H2H told the shelter we would be happy to help this little girl find her new home.

Initially, Libby is a little unsure of new people and situations, but she bonds quickly. Once comfortable, she seeks out attention, gets in your lap and wants to be right by your side. She is affectionate, attentive and a little sweetheart.

Libby can entertain herself by emptying the toy basket and running around playing with her toys. She sits by her foster mom & watches her work during the day and happily sleeps in the bed with her foster family.  

Libby walks well on a leash and is reliably house trained. Libby can be scrappy with other dogs, so she should be an only dog.  Libby requires an all-adult home (no children or grandchildren)  She requires an all adult home (no children or grandchildren) with a small, securely fenced yard (4 feet or higher).

The adoption range for this dog is limited to NC, SC and VA.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, contact h2hadoptions@gmail.com. An all adult home with a fenced yard (fence must be attached to the home) is required to adopt from Hart-2-Heart Rescue.

There is an application process and adoption fee. We are an all-volunteer organization, and in addition to saving dogs, we have other responsibilities, so we appreciate your patience and understanding during this process. Response time can take up to 5 business days.

Please inquire only if you are willing to come to Greensboro, North Carolina to meet the dog after we schedule your home visit. We do not ship dogs or put them on transports. Adoption fee is $400.

Veterinary Care: All Hart-2-Heart Rescue foster dogs are spayed/neutered, current on heartworm prevention, parvo/distemper, bordetella, and rabies vaccines and are professionally groomed. As needed, our foster dogs have teeth cleanings, extractions, bloodwork and other diagnostic testing.

animal.description:
Sydney came from the Oak Grove, MO animal shelter where she was surrendered by her owner. Sydney has had two owners already in her young life. Her first owners had a 1 year old child and surrendered her to the shelter because they said she was too big. They didn't have the time and space she needed. Sydney was then adopted by a family with 3 children. They had her for a week and then returned her to the shelter for nipping. We wonder if something happened with the first owner involving a leash/harness as that seemed to be the trigger. 

Sydney is a delightful girl! Very smart and sweet. She enjoys love and attention. Sydney is house trained, does well on a leash, and knows sit, stay, lie down, and come. She is playful and dog friendly at her foster home. Her foster dad says she gets excited when she sees him with her collar and leash and sits while he puts them on. Sydney weighs about 85 lbs and is still growing. She will come to you spayed, up to date on vaccinations, microchipped, and up to date on heartworm and flea/tick preventatives. 

Applicants must have a secure and visible fence. In order for your application to be approved, you must also pass a home check and a vet check which includes having at least a two year vet history. Sydney will NOT be adopted to a home with small children. Sydney can be adopted in Missouri and surrounding states: Illinois, Iowa, Kansas, Nebraska, and Arkansas. We are able to transport Sydney to those states. If you would like to give Sydney a furever home, please fill out an application on our website. 

Being fostered in Holden, MO

animal.description:
Mazie is such a lovely little lady. She was surrendered to the rescue after years of neglect and breeding. She only wanted love in her life and got a raw deal. Thank goodness she did because she had a ruptured eye and bleeding mammary tumors. She was a solid mat of fur but allowed us to bathe her and shave her down to get all that horrible stuff off of her. 
Then we went to the vet and got her all fixed up. She went through a huge surgery but they got all the tumors and they were biopsied to make sure she would be cancer free. As with any mammary tumor, there is a danger that someday she may develop tumors in other areas, but for now, she is cancer free and living the good life with her foster mom. 
Mazie would do best in a home with someone who can spend all their time with her. She tends to get whiney when you don't let her be with you. She's looking for a lap to spend the rest of her years on. 
Mazie has no vision in the eye that ruptured prior to her getting to us but has great vision in her other eye. She loves her stuffed toys and is a bit of a toy hoarder. She will get all her toys and put them around her on the couch and just act adorable. It's a wonderful thing to see a pup that was so neglected and unloved blossom into a happy little pup. 
Mazie is now fully vetted and healthy. She can be a little picky with her food but has her faves as her foster mom will tell you. She adores roasted chicken from the grocery store! 
Mazie is around 12 years old, weighs 8 or 9 lbs, and is housebroken. She is dog selective and would be best as an only dog or have a meet and greet prior to any adoption with another dog in the residence. 
She is located in Hicksville NY
Mazie's adoption fee is $400

animal.description: Ulysses is a 2-3 year old Plott boy waiting in southern Wisconsin for a new home after being picked up as a stray. He is now a strong, healthy boy weighing in at around 72 pounds. Ulysses has a typical Plott personality: goofy, dorky, sweet, and happy. He is very friendly with all humans he meets, but would do best in a home without small children. Ulysses would prefer to be the only male dog in the household and would also be fine as a solo dog as he loves being with his people. He has a strong prey instinct, so NO cats or small animals, please. He is housetrained and cratetrained, rides nicely in the car, and is working very hard on practicing his leash manners. In the house, he is very mild-mannered and quiet. Outside in the yard, he is in his element, and will sing you the song of his people when he catches the scent of something to be tracked. A fenced property would be best, as he will follow his nose given the opportunity. He would prefer a home that allows him the time and space to stretch his long legs and put his nose to work in a safe way; he is not cut out to be a city boy.

animal.description:
{s3829code380/}
If you would like to provide this dog a loving home, please fill out a pre-adoption application.

Have a question? Please read our Frequently Asked Questions and Adoption Processed Explained documentation.
_________ B I O ______________

Name:Mooney
Size: ~Large range: 61-100 lbs
Adoption Donation:$250 (applicable sales tax included).Adoption fees may be paid by cash or check.
Other:Neutered Male, Vaccinations current, Microchip, NO Children

Mooney would luv to have a great place to stay.

Foster Home Feedback

*
NO Children

*
Breed Experience Required

*
Mooney is currently on medication for allergies and itching. The cost of this medication is $98.00 per month. It is unknown if this medication will be required long term or just temporarily, but he currently requires it every day.

12/7/2020: Mooney has been continuing to settle into our home and we get to see more of his goofy personality every single day! He absolutely adores tennis balls and chuck-it balls. We have quite the hoard starting and Mooney can keep himself entertained for hours by pouncing on them, kicking them around, and playing keep-away with us. And beyond balls, he loves toys of just about any type! He is a destroyer, so stuffed toys don't last very long, but he has so much fun letting the fluff fly.

He has quite the 'Shepherd sass' as I am calling it. He is pretty vocal and likes to make himself known to those around. We also hear a lot of dramatic sighs around the house when Mooney doesn't get his way. We've been working hard on basic manners like not jumping up, loose leash walking, and waiting at the door. Luckily, he is very food motivated and has a strong drive to learn, so he has been a quick study in that department.

Mooney does great whenever we have to leave him alone. We kennel him and don't hear a peep the entire time. He isn't destructive to our things, so he would likely be okay left out of the kennel as well, but his wandering nose might find open trash cans or things on the counter if those get left out.

Structure and boundaries are a big part of life with Mooney. We make sure to meet his physical and mental needs, otherwise, he can get a little mouthy and wild. He gets along fantastic with our resident dog, but he doesn't always take the hint when she is done playing or when he is being too rough (he can be oblivious to his size and strength) so he needs a little supervision and some occasional structured breaks.

Strangers and new people are still very scary to Mooney. He does not react to strangers on walks or at a distance, but if someone were to try and approach him then he will. Every day we work on creating positive associations with strangers from a distance and are slowly increasing the circle of people he trusts. He needs a special forever home that understands he will need management and continued work in this area. Once you gain his trust, though, he does not disappoint. At home with us, Mooney is one of the most affectionate dogs I've ever met and has such a bright, funny personality that brings lots of smiles to our faces. I know someone out there will love him just as much as we do!

11/5/2020: Meet Mooney! If you have been searching for a 75 lb. lap dog, then he is your guy! He loves to cuddle and be affectionate, it is no joke that he is a total lap dog! He can never get close enough! Since having him in our home, we have gotten an endless supply of snuggling, kisses, and demands for petting. Mooney doesn't always pay attention to his size, so sometimes we have to set some boundaries for him.

He gets along great with other dogs, but likely needs playmates his size and energy level! Mooney wants to play all the time and can be very boisterous and loud when he does (he also doesn't always realize his size and strength). He listens well to my 50 lb. Pitty when she has had enough. I have had no issues with him sharing toys and bones with my resident dog, he loves to play tug with her! He is just a young guy who loves to go, go, go!

Mooney is fabulous in his kennel and happily runs in any chance he gets! It is his safe space and he loves to relax in there. He will also go in there for some calm time when he is getting too excited and sleeps through the night in there too.

We've been working very hard on walking nicely on the leash since he has been with us and he is getting much better! Mooney is very strong and will need some reminders to walk nicely. He is incredibly smart and treat-motivated, which makes him quick to learn new things. Mooney certainly has that Shepard drive to learn! He knows 'sit', 'down', 'stay', and 'shake' so far.

Mooney is a young dog with energy to burn and would love a family that will give him proper outlets for exercise and mental stimulation. On the flip side, he is also happy to relax and cuddle on the couch while watching TV in the evenings.

We don't know a lot about his past, but we do know that Mooney's forever family needs to be devoted to continue creating positive experiences in his life to show him that this world isn't scary. Mooney can get nervous around new people (especially men), but cheese is the way to his heart and once he trusts you then he will love you forever. Younger kids make him very uncomfortable and the busy "come and go" lifestyle of teenagers likely wouldn't mesh well with his personality. While he is still scared of various things in this great big world, his confidence has grown immensely after being with me for a couple of weeks and I know he can continue to thrive with the right people.To view additional dogs available for adoption, please see our website: www.4luvofdog.org

animal.description:
During the state mandated shelter-in-place order BACS has transitioned to virtual, socially-distanced adoptions.
If you have an interest in a particular BACS animal, please email KSwanson@cityofberkeley.info. The first step will be to set up a virtual meeting with their current foster family via phone, zoom, or facetime, to provide you with more detailed information about the animal. Following that, if you feel like it could be a good adoption fit, shelter staff will help coordinate a socially-distanced meeting in person so that you can meet your potential family member up-close and personal. Thank you for your patience during this time. We really appreciate your support!

Buddy Love is looking for someone with a heart as big as his. This senior pup, affectionately known as an "elderbull", spent the first 11 years of his life living in a backyard. He's looking forward to making up for lost time in his golden years! Buddy Love wants to be with people — from neighborhood walks, to supervising kitchen duties, to lounging while you read a book or watch TV.
 
Buddy Love's ideal adopter will have experience, patience, and time to help him through the transition into his forever home. He has dealt with a lot of change recently, which has been hard on him. Plus, his recent hearing loss has also made life more challenging. He loves routine, cuddles, meal time, and his walkies. But don't let his age fool you — Buddy Love will happily stroll the town with you for 30-60 minutes a couple times a day. 
 
He's already house trained and currently lives well in a foster home with an older, female dog and parrot, but he might prefer to be the only animal in his new home. He also has experience with young children and has earned his nickname "Buddy Bear" for his teddy bear-like qualities (gentle, caring, loyal).

animal.description:
A NEW LIFE AWAITS THIS CINDERELLA IN HER NEW HOME STATE!

My previous owner and I had a weekly routine; every Sunday she'd put me in the car and take me to Starbucks with her to get a treat! But then, one Sunday was different; instead of taking a left, the car went right. I wasn't sure where we were going, this wasn't our usual route. She stopped on a side street and opened my car door; I didn't recognize this area, but I jumped out of the car and waited by her to be leashed. But my owner didn't leash me. She got back in her car and began driving off without me. I quickly ran after the car. "Wait Mom, you're forgetting me!" I barked and ran as fast as I could, but the car didn't stop. I eventually accepted defeat when the tail lights of her car disappeared...

Unfortunately, Cinder's story is not unlike hundreds of others; all of which are deserving a loving forever family.

Cinder's eyes spoke to us and we hope she will speak to you too! She is a BEAUTIFUL 3 year old Labrador Retriever / American Staffordshire Terrier Mix. She weighs approximately 65lbs, is up-to-date on vaccinations, spayed, microchipped and heartworm negative. She has tested well with other dogs, rides well in the car and has gotten along well with people of all sizes (although her size and exuberance may not be the best match for very small children).

Please check back soon as we learn more about this amazing dog that has so much love to give to the right family. Home ownership is a requirement and BSL will apply to restricted areas (but she will be eligible to reside in Denver, come January)! Don't let your chance to love and be loved by this beautiful gal pass you by! Please complete an application to meet Cinder today!

*Homeownership Required & BSL applies.

	Spay/Neuter

animal.description:
Gucci is a sweet dog, born May 7, 2019. He is a shy, anxious boy who needs a home with someone who can help him build confidence and develop trust. Gucci loves to play with dogs of all sizes, but he is good at entertaining himself, when needed. He enjoys the attention of children. Being outside makes him happy, especially when it includes pool time and going for walks. He is housetrained, walks very well on a leash, and knows basic commands. This boy LOVES playing tag and is lightning fast so catching him is a challenge. He needs a yard with a 6-foot fence. In his new home, Gucci will need some time to warm up, but once he becomes comfortable, his is a calm and loving dog who just wants to lay on the couch with you. He is a very kind dog who doesn't have a mean bone in his body.

His prospective owner will be required to work with a trainer on his trust issues prior to adopting Gucci.

The suggested adoption donation for Gucci is $400. We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes.

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver.

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months.

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

He starts off instantly at a good pace and can get get ahead of you, but Spencer is also sweet-natured and mindful of correction.  Spencer’s pep isn’t just about pounding the pavement; he’s very active at home and seeks interaction and play.   Spencer enjoys the company of other dogs -- perhaps a little too much.  Whether he’s in a pack walk or in a playgroup, he is always on the lookout for a partner to play with.  This can be too much for some more serious or laid-back canines, so Spencer is best matched with a tolerant dog who enjoys romping but doesn’t get too rough and tumble.   A happy boy like Spencer seems enthusiastic about everything; however, what he’s most looking forward to is an active home with no cats but maybe with someone looking for a jogging buddy. animal.description:
Penelope is a 2 yr old Doxie mix who was rescued while pregnant from Mexico. She was wondering the streets and brought to the US for rescue. Penelope gave birth to 3 very healthy pups about 2 weeks later. Penelope appears to be a Doxie mix with longer legs. She is a super sweet girl who loves to be with people and playing with other dogs. She is housebroken but may take a week or so to get used to a new environment. The puppies are now weaned and she was ready to part ways so she is with a different foster to give her some peace. Penelope's milk is drying up and she will be spayed Feb 1st {unless we can get an earlier appt}.  

Penelope weighs about 13 lbs and absolutely loves walks! She does have some food aggression with other dogs so if there is another dog in the home she would need to be fed in a crate. She has no other aggressions and loves to snuggle in her blankets. 

Penelope would do best in a home where she has a secured yard to play and will not be alone too many hours a day. She does go looking for her people and will scale gates to search. She is crate trained so it is recommended that she be placed in the crate while alone. She really needs another small sized dog in the home to play/bond with.

If you would like to meet Penelope please fill out an adoption application at www;dogsinneedorg.com

The adoption fee for Penelope is $350 which includes all vaccines, rabies, flea control, deworming, microchip and spay

FAST FACTS:
*Cuddly, Affectionate Personality
*Dog Friendly
*Cat Friendly
*No Children In Home
*Quiet House Needed
*Calm Home
*Potty/Crate Trained
*Fenced Yard Preferred

BIO:
Ooh, la la! My name is Bikini, and my bright, sunshine personality will make every day feel like summer when I am by your side! I'm a big brindle-colored beauty - currently weighing about 100 pounds, but I would greatly benefit from losing a few - and my loving personality is even bigger! My favorite activity in the world is cuddling with my people, followed closely by receiving head massages, praise, and (of course) treats. I am generally pretty mellow and am a naptime expert so I would do best in a quiet, adult-only home without much activity (no children, please!) because too much excitement can stress me out. But I also have short bursts of energy and bounce around when I am feeling playful: I like to dance and reach out my paws to you. I get along well with the other doggie and cat in my foster home, and would enjoy a fenced yard at my forever home. I would also appreciate a family who will take me for daily strolls around the neighborhood so I can get some exercise and reach my healthier goal weight.

I have lovely house manners and you will be happy to have me as your forever roommate. I am potty trained and rest easily in a crate if you need to leave home for a few hours for work or errands. If I had to admit one minor flaw, it would be that my tail rarely stops wagging so I might accidentally knock a mug or wine glass off a coffee table as I pass by. I am a smart girl who is very treat motivated so if you wanted to teach me more commands I bet I would be a good student! If you have been on the hunt for an affectionate dog with endless love to give to her people, I think you have found your girl! I hope you fill out an adoption application soon because I am ready to make you smile with my big heart!

Love,
Bikini

ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS, NO EXCEPTIONS:
*ADOPTION FEE: $300
*Be at least 21 years of age
*Live in a 50-mile radius of Itasca, within the Illinois border
*Have the knowledge and agreement of all adults living in the household
*Have approval from owner of residence (written in lease)
*Have a valid ID with current address (please provide proof of address if ID address is not up-to-date)

animal.description:
Sundown is an approximately 2 year old hound mix. Found  by a good samaritan, emaciated (see "before" picture) and lying in the road, he was placed in a loving foster home where he has gained 12 pounds. Sundown has been fully vetted including neuter, vaccinations and microchip. He did test positive for heartworms and is being treated through the "slow-kill" method.  This requires him to be on heartworm prevention for life and his qualified family must have a history of monthly heartworm prevention.

This sweet boy is housebroken, loves his crate, and sleeps quietly in it all night. He likes to pull his blankets out of the crate for fun but isn't destructive while kenneled. He is not excessively vocal, he rarely barks unless it's supper time! And who could blame him for getting so excited?!

Sundown gets along with all the dogs in his foster home, even the small chi-weeniees. He's loves to play with his companions and would do best in a home with another dog or two. Not cat tested but does not show interest in prey like squirrels or birds.

Sundown adores his foster mom and checks in with her often when they are outside doing yard work and chores. He's truly a Velcro pup! He knows how to sit for his food bowl and gives howdy as thanks.

His perfect home would have a doggy friend and a human or two to continue working with him to be the best boy he can be. Good with kids, might be a bit exuberant for small ones. Overall this is a fantastic young fella who wants someone who will love him like he deserves.

April 2020:  We are not holding public adoption events at this time.  Qualified families are being invited to appointments to meet specific dogs.  There are currently no opportunities to view multiple dogs and adoption events aren't being held at Tractor Supply in Lenoir.

Whether dogs / puppies come in as strays or owner surrenders, we usually have to make our best guess as to birthdate and breed.   

If adopted into a home with other animals, particularly cats, your new pet should be crated or secured when you're not available to supervise to insure a harmonious relationship.  

A vet reference is required to confirm responsible pet ownership.  We suggest first time pet owners look for an adult dog for companionship and to gain experience through another rescue or your local government-run animal control..

Adoption fee covers two vaccinations plus spay / neuter if using our local low-cost spay/neuter clinic (overnight stay required) and surgery occurs as agreed upon in the adoption contract.  Convenience fee equal to refundable spay/neuter deposit may be added if using our veterinarian.  Additional fees for 3rd puppy vaccination, refundable spay/neuter deposit, etc. may apply.  

We are an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue.  We receive no funding from agencies.  Available animals can be seen most Saturdays at Tractor Supply in Lenoir from 10:00 a.m. to 2:00 p.m.  We recommend interested parties contact us to pre-qualify for adoption so their new furry family can go home once paperwork is complete.  Fees are required in cash.  For more information on our organization, our website is www.petpartnersrescue.org.

animal.description:
MEET ANTONIO!!

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in its possession.
To visit with this pup, please make an appointment here: https://mcaccappointments.as.me/adopt. NOTE: People who sign up for these appointments often no-show. We have been told that you can go straight to the shelter and let them know you are there to meet this particular dog. From what we understand, the shelter will squeeze you in. (Please know this is not a guarantee).

We hope your adoption process is smooth and full of happiness!

Look at Antonio's happy face!! Antonio has been at the shelter for almost 60 days now and he needs to go home. He's a friendly boy that likes to be petted, likes to play and loves his treats! He loves to go for a walk and he will pull hard on the leash at first because he's so happy to get out of his kennel but once he walks for a block, he slows down and takes a nice, leisurely walk. When a volunteer took Antonio for a walk and gave him some treats, he jumped up a bit because he was so happy to get them. But when he is told "no" and "down" he listens and sits right down. Other volunteers have said he loves getting his ears scratched and when he got a rock in his paw, he let the volunteer remove it with no issues.

When Antonio was taken out to the play yard to meet other dogs, he was quite dominant with them. If an adopter already has a dog at home, they need to bring them with to the shelter to meet Antonio to see if they can live together. If Antonio is the dog for you, then come and meet him today!!

This amazing pup is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4465390.

*Please Note: This animal is courtesy posted for the Maricopa County Shelter; UNDERDOG RESCUE DOES NOT HAVE THIS DOG. MCACC is located at 2500 S. 27th Avenue, Phoenix. animal.description:
PLEASE READ ENTIRE PROFILE BEFORE APPLYING.

Olga is a 135lb, 3-and-a-half year old English Mastiff, and like all mastiffs she is a giant, lazy baby! Unfortunately though, Olga has been let down in life and has some trust issues because of it. She was abandoned by her old owner, and ended up in the shelter. Whatever happened in her life before, it caused her to not trust a lot of people, especially men, and young ones who may not be well-versed in a dog's body language. For this reason we are only going to adopt her to a home without men, unless they have professional experience with dog training or behavior.

She is extremely loving and affectionate with women she trusts, it just might take a few meetings. If she doesn't like you, just give it time, and work with her. She's not mean, just uncertain, and will react accordingly. She is currently on Prozac for her anxiety. 

Due to her history she needs a good amount of structure and personal time to solidify the dog-owner bond. Because of this, it would be best that Olga goes to a quiet home of only one or two adults, preferably someone with experience owning very large dogs. Good news though - Olga is fine with most other animals!! Of course if you have a dog a meet-and-greet will be required, but she's lived with dogs and cats before and had no issues. 

If you give her a chance you won't be disappointed: she really is a sweet and gentle giant. She loves to sniff around the yard and scratch her back in the grass, and she is very gentle taking treats. She'll lean on you for ear rubs and neck scratches, and she likes to give slobbery kisses! So, won't you give Olgie a chance?
To adopt one of our animals, please visit our shelter, open Tuesday-Friday from Noon-6pm and Saturday from Noon-4pm. You may also submit an application online from our website at http://www.HelpTheAnimalsINC.com/adopt.

animal.description:
Hi there! I'm Boogie! Are you ready for a goofy boy to dance and wiggle into your life? I am a 2 year old, neutered male, pit bull. I weigh about 50 pounds. I have tons of young dog energy and love to be on the move! I am affectionate and love to get attention. I get very excited to see my favorite people and can get jumpy and rowdy, so my new family will need to help me spruce up my manners. To aid me in my goals, am required to go to basic obedience classes, which includes an additional cost at the time of adoption. I love treats and already know how to sit for one. My new family must be an adults only household or one with older teens. They should also have recent experience with large breed, high energy dogs like myself. If there is a resident dog in the home, I get along best with social, playful dogs around my size. Please be sure to bring in the entire household, dogs included, before adopting me to make sure we'll all get along.
If you're interested in learning more about me or setting up a time to meet, please submit your fully completed Adoption Profile Form to swerning@phs-spca.org or call 650-340-7022 x 316. You must be 18 or older to submit an application.
Application: https://phs-spca.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/AdoptionProfiles_dog.pdfUnless otherwise indicated, adoptable animals are located at our Lantos Center for Compassion at 1450 Rollins Road, Burlingame, CA 94010. Please note at this time we are doing adoptions by appointments only. Please call us at 650-340-7022 to schedule an appointment.Our hours are weekdays from 11am-6pm and weekends from 11am-5pm (closed major holidays). Interested adopters must arrive at least 1 hour before close. We do our best to update our listings regularly, but we can't guarantee every animal you see is still available. It's also typical for us to have animals who haven't had their photos taken yet, so you are welcome to visit our adoption center and have a look around!
To check on an animal's adoption status, please call 650-340-7022 during normal business hours to speak with an adoption counselor. Emails will be returned as soon as possible, but please allow up to 48 hours during busy adoption periods like weekends.
