animal.description:
Adorable Flint is being fostered in GA. He has not yet been exposed to children.

What we know about Flint:
* calm
*sweet
*doing well working on housebreaking
*blind

What Flint's foster mom has to say about Flint:

12/20/20 update:
Flint had Enucleation of both eyes and is healing well. 
Flint's loving personality and desire to be with others has not changed.
He loves several walks a day and is very active as he ages and is comfortable in his Foster home.
He loves to walk in the woods and loves a lot of outside time with walks and interaction.
Flint is still apprehensive in meeting new people and dogs.
Flint enjoyed his playtime with a neighbors Pitbull.
I would love to see Flint to be adopted to an active family with no younger children.
We feel Flint would do good with a home with a fenced yard.
Flint is going to be a big boy. 
He now weighs 40lbs.
He sometimes pulls on the leash and jumps we are working on this.
Flint is doing great with housebreaking with an occasional accident.
He loves toys and bully sticks.
Flint is a happy boy who loves his foster family and loves to be held even if he is a lap full.


Flint is a calm loving pup. He loves to be held and cuddled. Flint loves walks and outside time.
Flint is making progress on housebreaking. He is doing great with the leash and walks.
He is starting to enjoy play and loves his toys.
Flint is very happy when around his foster family.
He is apprehensive when meeting others as he has not been exposed to a lot of activity outside of his immediate world.  This is because he has been on medical hold due to a respiratory illness, from which he has greatly improved. 
Flint is also on heartworm and flea prevention.
BDRA has voted against the use of electrical fencing effective immediately.

They are both such a good doggies, likes other dogs, loves people, super sweet and fairly easy. They just loves companionship. If you have a yard, they would love it. They enjoy their walks.

They will bring meaning to your life as you will for them, losing his home at such a time in life. They are resilient and precious!

They are now updated on all shots and will be chipped. Their adopt fee is $395.

We cover the medical to prepare the pet for adoption and the adopt donations go directly to cover those costs and range from $295-$495. Thank you for stepping up to save a life!

To expedite to meet with this dog, please go to our site at www.savinggreatanimals.org and fill out an application. We look at the first applications to arrive, so we hope to hear from you soon!

animal.description:
Han is a superb cuddler and loves tug-o-war. He's really good at sitting and high five, and knows other commands like "spin" and "jump it". His recall is amazing, including when he tries to climb the trees at the fence line to catch the squirrel on the other side. He's been higher than the fence, but fortunately hasn't jumped over.

Han is available to the RIGHT home only. Han needs an experienced owner that is willing to work with him every day. He's a smart dog with limitless energy, but will become possessive if not corrected constantly. He needs a fenced in yard to get some of this energy out, but also requires mental stimulation through training, agility, or walks. Very long walks. He would be an excellent hiking partner. Han would do best as an only pet in the household.

ADOPT HAN!!!!! The adoption fee is $250.00 and we require a vet check and home visit. Han is neutered, chipped, vaccinated, heartworm tested and on monthly prevention for fleas/tick and heartworms.

animal.description:
Carolina Boxer Rescue is a volunteer run, 501(c)3 non-profit organization. Our mission: To balance the health, safety, and welfare needs of Boxers in the Carolinas (and parts of Virginia and Georgia) by providing a loving and safe environment for stray, abused, impounded and owner surrendered dogs by placing them in foster homes and ultimately - forever homes.

________________________________________________________________________________________

Dog's Name: Pearl

Dog's Approximate Age: 7 years old

Gender: Female

Dog's Size: Large (70lbs plus as adult and healthy weight)

Dog's Weight: 64 pounds

Good with small dogs?: Yes

Good with big dogs?: Yes

Good with cats?: Don't know yet

Good with kids?: Don't know yet

Any medical issues?:
NEEDS DENTAL CARE, NEEDS TO GAIN 15 LBS

Crate trained?: Yes

House trained?: Yes

Heartworms?: Yes

12/4/20: Hi, Friends!

Did you have a nice Thanksgiving? I sure hope so. The weather here was sunny and warm. Mom and I walked an entire mile very slowly, and I smelled so many smells. It was great. I love meeting new dogs of all sizes, and I am doing a great job of walking on my leash.

My appetite is good, but I am still a picky eater. I will definitely turn down treats or food even when I am hungry if it's not something that I like to eat. I'm still eating my healthy dog food, and special foods like scrambled eggs, cheese, and lunch meat.

Do you know what I love even more than my favorite foods? Affection! That's right. Pet my head or rub my tummy or let me snuggle up next to you on the couch. There is nothing better. I love snuggles and cuddles so much.

I am preparing for my heartworm treatment in January. In a couple of weeks, I will go in for my dental cleaning and to have some lumps and bumps removed. I'm looking forward to having all of the health stuff done, so I can concentrate on having fun with my dog friends.

I'm still having some accidents in the house. Don't worry. Mom and I are going to keep working on it, and I will figure it out. Did I tell you that I'm working on commands? I am so good at sit, and I'm learning some other commands, too. I don't like lay down, though. If I do, I may miss something!

Car rides? Yes! Crate sleeping for naps or nights? Yep! Best girl, ever? Mom says, definitely.

Happy Holidays! And just remember, you can always visit me on Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/pearl_pup_2020/

11/9/20: Hi, Friends! I cannot believe it's been an entire month since I have been in my foster home. The time has gone so quickly. In the past month, I have developed an appetite and started eating healthy dog foods! Don't get me wrong though--I still love lunchmeat and cheese as treats (or to take my medicines).

Getting out and about is ok. I don't really like the very short walks to go outside and potty, but I have had fun taking some rides in the car. There's so much to see and smell. I am making friends with the dogs who live in our building. My best friends right now are Smoky, a chocolate lab, Doris, the tiniest yorkie mix, Bear, a German Shepherd, and Lily, a black lab. I look forward to being strong so we can play for real.

My spay surgery is over and done with and I am almost entirely recovered. I can't wait for my stitches to be out next week. Hopefully then I will be well enough to start my heartworm treatment. I am getting healthier and stronger each day! After my surgery, Mom got me a surgery suit instead of a cone and it was great. I may even start expanding my wardrobe.

I continue to be excellent in my crate. I sleep there at night, and hang out when my parents are gone or it's the cat's turn to roam free. I do not chew things that I'm not supposed to, but I've had a number of potty accidents, so I don't spend time roaming free unattended. I spend lots of time with my mom as her assistant during the work day and cuddling to watch a tv at night.

My mom tells me what a sweet and beautiful girl I am. She says I am the very best snuggler and model! She takes so many photos of me every day.

You take care and have a Happy Thanksgiving if we don't talk before then. And just remember, you can always visit me on Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/pearl_pup_2020/

10/17/20: Hi, Friends! I'm Pearl, a bulldog/boxer mix. I have been in my foster home for almost a week now, and I'm starting to get adjusted.

I love people so much. I want to meet everyone I see, and if they want to give me pets--even better! Have you heard of snuggles? I love snuggles. Let's snuggle on the couch or on the floor or on my bed. Have you heard of belly rubs? I love them more than anything in the entire world. I will lay on my back and ask for a belly rub when I wake up in the morning and when I sit down to go outside. My foster mom gives me a belly rub a couple of times a day, and we snuggle so much.

I'm a grown-up gal, so I have many of the basics mastered! I sleep very well in a crate. If you put a treat in, I walk in with no objection and stay there for as long as you need me to. I am completely house-broken and learning that I will get regular breaks to go outside. I walk well on a leash, but I am learning to be more confident. I am learning which dog friends I can trust. I do not like bicycles or loud cars too close when I am on a walk. I have excellent ears. If a dog barks or someone whistles on tv, I will think they are talking to me, and I might even stand at attention. I know what come means, but I still need to learn sit, stay, and lay down. I am not a loud girl, and in a week, I have only barked three times. I will be honest, I do snore a bit when I sleep.

Have you heard of cheese? I'm still expanding my palate and figuring out which foods and treats that I like, but I really love cheese. I would share with you though. I do not chew on things that I am not supposed to like shoes, and I can be left safely to roam while you are out. My foster mom did catch me counter surfing last night though, so your treats may not be safe with me if you aren't looking. My mom says I need to gain some weight, so I will be working on that.

I live with a cat now. I am still trying to figure him out. When I am in my crate, I watch him, but do not bark and he is safe to roam the house freely without any worries about me. I wonder if he will want to play someday? That's all for now. I can't wait to talk with you again soon.

_____________________________________________________________________________

Come visit carolinaboxerrescue.org to learn more about me and see more pictures. Learn about our adoption process too!

_____________________________________________________________________________

animal.description:
Meet lovely Sara

This pretty girl came from a terrible place. 

She was left behind, abandoned, hurt and hungry, along the side of her dear brother Bruno. 

Sarah loves, adores her brother.
After having them both recover under my care, I have come to realize that she needs her brother so much, that I would like if an adopter would consider getting them both as a pair into a forever home! 

Yes, they could both go on separately.... Bruno can hold his own no matter what. 
But Sarah is sensitive... she is so happy by his side! 

You would love her!
She is fun, likes to play, her brother takes the best out of her?

Sarah likes to be a good girl. 
She benefits from good boundaries and a patient human that gives lots of positive reinforcement! 

She don’t want to disappoint. 

Please, consider Sarah and Bruno to give them a home for the holidays! 

You will not regret it!

animal.description:
Looking for IMMEDIATE foster or adopter in New England/East Coast for Mason. 

He is about two-years-old and weighs about 60lbs. 

We think he might be a Lab-Boxer mix.

Mason loves to be pet and shake. He would do well in a home where he can get lots of exercise and activity. He's lived in a home with another dog (littermate) since he was born, but they started not getting along.  Which can happen when two puppies stay together. 

We think for now Mason would do better in a home without adults and or adults and older teens without other dogs, he needs a bit of proper socializing in the doggo department. 

He'd do better in a home with a tall fence (he's a jumper) versus an apartment or condo, he will bark when he hears noises or someone pull up. 

Mason does best crated when home alone.  He should be supervised in any new setting as he sometimes likes to sneak off and chew things he's not supposed to.  We think in the right home when he's getting the right amount of exercise he will grow into a good boy. 

He is neutered, vaccinated, housebroken, and microchipped. 

Apply at www.luckylabrescue.com and message our Facebook page and let us know you applied. Thank you!

Hello Future Family! I’m a friendly, laid back dog with a sweet and playful disposition. I make friends quickly and love to play. My favorite games are play and run in the yard or park . I like to be around my humans when I’m not playing with my sister or napping.  I try to please and like to hear that I am a good boy. I enjoy having head rubbed. I love to eat and am very food motivated. 
I am potty training and sleep in a kennel very quiet all night.  Sometimes I do not  want to go in my kennel, but a snack will work for me.
He is about 2 years and weight about 56 pounds

PLEASE CONTACT THE FOSTER DIRECTLY 
Denisse at:

animal.description:
Spark is now in a foster home! We are happy Spark got out of the kennels because he was nervous and pacing in circles. He was great out in the yard, but being in the kennel made him anxious. So now he is in a home where he is more comfortable. Spark is a good boy with big smiles and lots of love to give. -------------- Update from foster: ""He's 6 or 7 yrs old. Good around other dogs though expects to be the alpha dog. Not so good around cats. Loves humans and his teddy bear. Wants to be near his master sleeping in your lap or slobbering on your face. He wants to be indoors sleeping on the couch but he doesn't mind sleeping in a crate at night. But needs a fenced yard for when he's outdoors. He's smart but needs someone that has the time and abilities to train him, right now he's just a big goofball. "" Come give this big hunk a hug! To meet Spark, please contact our foster coordinator at coordinator@moaspets.com and fill out an adoption application online at www.moaspets.com/adoptionapp. We would love to set up a meet and greet with you! -------------------------
Please call the shelter at (706) 795-2868 to schedule a meet and greet. Madison Oglethorpe Animal Shelter is a non-profit shelter serving over 720 square miles. We are open intake, meaning we can not turn away animals from either county we serve. Our shelter intakes double or triple it's capacity every month so it is essential we place animals quickly into adoptive homes. Since so many animals enter the shelter we often don't have enough volunteers to write an individual bio for each. Please feel free to call the shelter Wednesday-Sunday to inquire about the animal you are interested in. 706-795-2868. Viewing and adoption hours at our shelter are Wednesday through Sunday from 12 PM to 5 PM. All adoption fees include age-appropriate vaccinations, flea treatment, deworming, and spay or neuter, microchip, and adoption packet. Fees: Dogs over 4 months old: $100 Puppies under 4 months: $125. Cats and Kittens are $75 ($65 without microchip). For your convenience you can fill out an adoption application for any of our current residents at www.moaspets.com. Join us on Facebook at https://www.facebook.com/moaspets. It's a great way to stay up to the minute on the furry 4 legged friends we have looking for a loving forever home. We are located at: 1888 Colbert Danielsville Rd Danielsville, GA 30633 706-795-2868 NOTE: Our adoptions are first come first served, simply filling out an application does not mean the animal will be held for you, you must come meet the animal in person in order to be considered for adoption. If you rent you must bring your lease or a letter from your landlord stating you may adopt.

animal.description:
Hi there! My name is Mona. I'm a sweet, affectionate gal looking for a forever home to live out the rest of my golden years. One of my favorite things to do is cuddle; I just can't enough quality time with the special people in my life. I'd love to spend every minute with you and be your forever sidekick. I'm a bit of a people pleaser, and I really know my stuff, like... sit, stay, wait, kennel, lay down, and more. I'm a very fast learner and love to please my family with all my smarts. At 8 years old, I still have a bit of an energetic and playful streak in me, but I also like to stay calm and curl up in a ball and take a good nap. Really, I'm the best of both worlds. Some of my favorite pastimes include: going for walks, going on car rides, licking the ice cream bowl clean for you, snuggling on the couch, stealing your spot once you've warmed it up, sitting in the window and sunshine, napping, burrowing under blankets, and playing tug of war. My ideal home would be with someone who doesn't have any other pets and who is home most of the day; maybe someone who works from home or a good ol' retiree like me would be perfect! We could keep each other company, so neither one of us will ever be lonesome. I promise I'll go anywhere with you! What do you say, do I sound like the girl for you? Set up a time to meet me today! P.S. Did you know if you're a senior just like me, my adoption fee is FREE for you through our Senior-to-Senior program?! Check out more info here: https://www.homewardonline.org/adoption-foster-info/adoption-discounts-for-seniors-military.html.
.
.
All animals are current on vaccinations and microchipped prior to adoption. All cats and kittens are Feline Leukemia and FIV tested. All dogs and puppies 6 months and older are heartworm tested. All animals 6 months and older are spayed/neutered prior to adoption. Any kittens/puppies will have refundable spay/neuter deposits included in their adoption fee; spaying/neutering will be the responsibility of the adopter and a refund will be issued upon proof of the surgery being completed by the adopter's veterinarian of choice.
.
.
Kitten adoption fees are $150 (includes a $40 refundable spay/neuter deposit). Cat adoption fees are $120, unless otherwise noted. Dog adoption fees may vary between $200-250. Puppies adoption fees may vary between $300-350 (includes a $100 refundable spay/neuter deposit). All adoption fees are taxable (tax is not included in the prices listed above).
.
.
""Sponsored"" means that a donor has covered a portion of the adoption fee for that animal. ""Fully sponsored"" means that a donor has paid the full adoption fee for the animal.

animal.description:
Available for adoption in Texas meet MEDDA!

Sooo, yeah, we just tell her she's a Lab!  Go with it! :) We could not resist saving Medda when she needed us.  She was dumped as a pregnant mom with her puppies and needed a lifeline quickly!

Now she's spayed, all fixed up, and her puppies are all adopted. It's time for Medda to find a forever home. 

Medda is approximately two-years-old and weighs about 56lbs.  Medda is an outgoing and adventurous girl who has never met a stranger! 

Medda loves to play with her foster siblings. She's great with all dogs outside, but can be choosy about her female dog friends.   

Cats are unknown. 

She will attempt to jump up upon meeting but is easily corrected.  For that reason, a home with older kiddos or only adults is needed.

She loves to cuddle and jump on the couch for pets. Medda is completely kennel and house trained and sleeps through the whole night without a peep! 

Medda loves to explore the backyard and look for sticks to chew on, her brother to pounce on, or squirrels to chase. 

She loves walks but does need some minor correction when she pulls.  Medda is also always ready for a nap.  

Medda doesn't care for loud cars or trucks, especially Amazon vans, and will bark if she hears or sees one. She will watch TV and bark at other animals or grizzly looking people (long shaggy beards). Medda has even barked at her own reflection in the window. (She's very alert at all times!)

Medda is vaccinated, spayed and microchipped, and ready for her forever home!  

If you're interested in making Medda a member of your family, please go to www.luckylabrescue.com and complete an adoption application for her.

animal.description:
Bambi is our new addition to our adoptable floor. She is a 7 year old  shepherd X who is friendly. She is looking for her loving home and someone to hang out with her. If you are interested in meeting Bambi please call us at 780-826-3230 to book an appointment. also if you are interested in adopting her go to our web site for adoption application. www.bonnyvilllespca.com

UPDATE: Hi my name is Bambi! I am an older girl around 7 years old. My face may show my age, but my spirit and love for life says differently. I still have lot's of play and energy in me and love to go for walks and run through the snow. I also love people of all ages, so much so that I want to keep the attention all to myself and not share it with another dog.  Can't say for sure how I feel about cats just yet, but the girls hope to test me soon. I do have a secret, one I have just recently shared with the girls here. At some point in my life, someone was not very kind to me. It was discovered that someone had shot at me, quite a few times. I have lot's of tiny pellets in my chest. Luckily, nothing has punctured any major organs. As there is so many bullets, removing all of them is out of the question. I may suffer from lead poisoning later on, which may shorten my life, it's impossible to say. But for my remaining years I would love to find a home where I could be the Queen! If you are looking for a medium size shepherd mix dog who will give you eternal friendship and love look no further then me! I hope to meet my family soon. Love Bambi. ??

UPDATE #2 from her Foster Family: 

Are you looking for a sweet and loyal companion? Then Bambi is the dog for you!

Bambi is a senior dog, but her foster mom says you can’t tell! She loves her walks, belly rubs, and being with her humans. She is still working on her jumping manners, and can be a little excitable until she settles in... but she is an eager-to-please sweetheart that loves everyone she meets.

Bambi would do well in a home as the only pet, or with a non-dominant dog with proper introductions.

This loving sweet girl very much deserves her second chance and a furever family to call her own ?

While she listens to commands to sit and be still outside, she can be aggressive toward big dogs, so she’d benefit from a strong person who can handle her when she’s on the leash. Pearl is housebroken and is not food aggressive, and she listens to commands and is food motivated. She absolutely aims to please and will be by your side as much as she can, looking up at you adoringly and giving her love. Her vaccinations are all up to date and she has some arthritis issues that are being regulated with Dosequin. Please call 718-666-8097 for more information

animal.description:
Howdy my name is Justine. I am a 2 year old Chihuahua / Mini Pin mix. I weigh 13 lbs. & you can say I’m all legs.

Some of my favorite things are playing with toys, treats & sitting in your lap. I get along with other dogs but my preference is small dogs. I do great riding in the car. I enjoy wearing doggy clothes especially a warm sweater when its cold outside. I get excited to go on walks.

When I first meet new people I am shy but I warm up quickly. I’m good around older kids & a little nervous around littles. I am also cat friendly I mostly just ignore them.

I enjoy spending time outside when others are out with me (my canine friends or my humans). I’m not overly chatty but it’s just too tempting when other dogs start barking that I must join in. Playing chase is so much fun for me. I also enjoy playing fetch.

At night my favorite place to sleep is in your bed anywhere you’ll let me. When it’s cold I like to burrow underneath a blanket. Where I am not good sleeping is in a crate. I will keep the entire house awake.

I am crate, leash & potty trained. My foster home has a doggy door so I may require some patience as I adjust to a home without a doggy door since I’ve become accustomed to letting myself out to go potty whenever I need to go. Oh, my foster mom said I must tell you that I’m not a fan of the crate thing. I am quiet while you are gone but if you are home & I’m crated I will let you know all about it. 

I am spayed, up to date on vaccinations, HW negative, current on HW preventative and micro chipped. My adoption fee is $175.   

If you would like to adopt Justine and make her a part of your family, please contact ForeverYoursOKC@gmail.com.

Hi friends my name is Raffie. I’m an 11 month old Hound Mix so I still have lots of energy. I’m crate trained and potty trained. Since I’m from Massachusetts I’m WICKED SMAHHT so I already know sit, down, stay, off, paw, other paw, catch, drop it, fetch, wait, take it. I’m also pretty good on leash.  I love to learn so just teach more me please. I enjoy some zoomies and playing in the backyard but my favorite activity is going for walks and outdoor adventures. I’m really good at agility too. 

I have shown some resource guarding around my food bowl and some favorite toys and bones, but my foster mom has lots of ways to safely take things from me with no issues, for example, just toss some kibble when you pick up my food bowl.  As a precaution, I need to go to a home with no young children. I can live with a confident 4 legged female dog or I’m also happy being the only dog. I’m confident and not to brag, but I’m handsome too.  Who’s ready for me cause I’m ready for my fur-ever home!!

All dogs are up to date on vaccines, heartworm tested, microchipped and spayed/neutered prior to adoption. Please visit www.bulliedbreedsrescue.org for adoption policies and adoption application. The adoption application is the first step to be considered: http://bulliedbreedsrescue.org/adopt/adoption-application/

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Raffie has a prey drive around small animals, like most hound type dogs.

animal.description:
Age: 8 ish

Weight: 35 lbs

Up to date on shots?:Yes;

Leash trained: Yes 

Crate trained: Mostly, he is fed in a crate. Graham goes in willing for mealtime but never goes in on his own at other times.

House trained: Yes, Foster has a doggy door, Graham takes care of this himself. If the adopter does not have a doggy door, there may be a training period where the human learns Graham's signals.

Good with dogs: yes

Good with cats: no

Good with kids: not likely due to his age, he has not been around children while in foster care.

Requires Fence: yes, requires a physical fence

Update 11/30:
Sweet Graham's wish as Christmas approaches is for a forever home. He is a delightful companion who would enjoy having his very own person. He's great with other dogs but his real focus is on YOU. 
You may remember Graham's story: 8 years tied to a tree which led to arthritis in his elbows, spine and hips. While many of us are eager to put the year 2020 behind us, it has been the best year of Graham's life! OESR rescued him and has been most generous in giving him the care he needs to become active and, by appearances, pain free. 
No more slow starts for Graham in the morning! He is up and ready to go! His favorite past time is goose "hunting" in a nearby park, followed by breakfast and a good nap. If I'm cooking, he naps in front of the refrigerator, If I'm at my desk, he's asleep on my foot (best way to monitor any potential activity that might mean food or an outing). We go to the woods or other parks in the afternoon to squirrel "hunt". 

Graham is all about hanging out with his person or chasing anything that moves (no homes with cats please).   Due to his structural problems, Graham is quite content with walks of a tenth to a quarter of a mile a couple of times a day.  He'd be the perfect companion for a retired senior who wants an adoring pal. When he does occasionally go out in the fenced yard, he stalks the squirrels and bunnies. In pleasant weather he likes to nap under the bird feeder but is uninterested in anything more than watching the song birds. Because his life before rescue was so limited, he deserves to live the rest of it with as much stimulation and freedom to do fun doggy things as is possible.

Graham needs a very special home: 
1- no more than one step (going down steps would hurt his elbows)
2 - an adopter able to lift him in and out of the car. Like going down steps, it would be too painful for his elbows to step down on them. His ideal weight should be about 40 pounds. 
3 - fenced yard (because he won't poop when on leash). I have a doggy door so he takes care of business himself. 
4 - an adopter willing to take him on short interesting walks (under one half mile b/c longer makes his left leg quiver), preferably where there are novel smells. Walking on ground rather than pavement is easier on his joints. According to the shelter, Graham spent 8 years tied to a tree. He is entitled to live out his days in an environment rich in scents, gentle experiences and love.
5 - someone committed to continuing Graham's pain management program. He takes several supplements that are essential to supporting bone and tissue. He also receives a NSAID, gabapentin, weekly laser treatments and monthly Adequan injections (which I give to keep cost down). Anyone applying as Graham's forever home needs to know that this regimen costs about $260/month and they need to commit to paying this for the next several years.

animal.description: Hunk is a 4 year old male mixed breed. He weighs 55 pounds. Hunk was transferred from a county shelter so we do not have information about his previous household. When Hunk arrived at our shelter he was heartworm positive and had a large head wound that required surgery. He has since recovered from the head trauma which has left him with a scar on his forehead. But we think it gives this handsome hunk some character! Hunk is still going through heartworm treatment. He will have to remain on crate rest until February 4th. After that his treatment is completed except for his heartworm re-test. Because Hunk is heartworm positive and on crate rest, we have not done any dog or cat testing because he needs to be kept calm. We always recommend a meet and greet with any resident dogs. We have no information on how Hunk behaves around children. We would recommend a meet and greet with any children in the household or children that visit often, such as grandkids. Please call for more information or to make an appointment to meet Hunk. (Updated 1/30/21).

animal.description:
201442. Chicken McNugget is one of four male Pit Bull/Lab looking mix pups surrendered to us by their owner. They are six- months old as of early January, 35 lbs, and just great pups in search of active, loving and responsible homes.
ADOPTION FEES Dogs & Puppies.....$100.00. This Adoption fee includes: mandatory spay/neuter which will be done before you can take your dog or puppy home with you; basic canine immunizations (DHPP-CPV & Bordatella Intranasal); de-wormings; one-year rabies vaccination if old enough; heartworm test if over five months old; microchip from 24-Pet Watch; certificate for free health examination at your participating veterinarian; and a goodie bag chocked full of information, toys, and more.
The first step to do an adoption is to do our Adoption Application here: https://www.elmorehumane.org/adoption-application-online-form2.html
IMPORTANT - we respond to your emailed applications and queries via email back to you. Please make sure you have either added our email (hselco@bellsouth.net) to your contact list or that you routinely check your SPAM folder for our response just to be safe. If we do not receive a timely response we simply move on to another applicant.
Yes, there are sometimes exceptions to our normal fee for older dogs or special cases. Some of our pets have also been lovingly sponsored by caring people and we will let the approved adopter know about that at the point of adoption. Visit our Website at: http://www.elmorehumane.org The staff would also like to remind you that for faster response to inquiries about adoptable animals to have the animals ID#, name & description. This way your questions will be answered in a timely manner.
All pet adoption websites & our shelter management software require that we choose a primary and/or secondary breed for our dogs. While our staff is quite breed knowledgeable, in many cases we are truly making our best guesses as to their breed(s) based on many factors but cannot promise that what we have said is accurate. So taking into account your own parameters for things such as size, coat care, activity level, etc please come and get to know our dog(s) as individuals to see if their personalities and yours are a forever match.
Phone: (334) 567-3377 Fax: (334) 567-8774 E-mail: hselco@bellsouth.net

animal.description: Cato is a 12 year old male mixed breed. He weighs 65 pounds. He is still an active boy for his age. Unfortunately, Cato has been in and out of the shelter several times. Often for issues out of his control such as landlord or HOA restrictions. From our time with Cato and input from previous homes we have learned quite a bit about him. Cato can be friendly with other dogs although he is very fond of humping and needs a dog friend or friends that can give him appropriate corrections when they've had enough. Dogs that are not fond of being humped or that are prone to overcorrections may not make good dog friends for Cato. We always recommend a meet and greet with any resident dogs. If you are unsure about your pup's feelings on this type of play, our staff can help by supervising a meet and greet and explaining the behaviors they observe. Cato can not be in a home with cats including feral cats that may go in and out of the yard. Cato has been around children of varying ages and the only complaint we have received is that he can be a little rambunctious for smaller children, especially due to his size. We always recommend a meet and greet with any children in the household or children that visit often, such as grandkids. Please call for more information or to make an appointment to meet Cato. (Updated 1/30/21).

Visit our Website at: http://www.elmorehumane.org The staff would also like to remind you that for faster response to inquiries about adoptable animals to have the animals ID#, name & description. This way your questions will be answered in a timely manner.
All pet adoption websites & our shelter management software require that we choose a primary and/or secondary breed for our dogs. While our staff is quite breed knowledgeable, in many cases we are truly making our best guesses as to their breed(s) based on many factors but cannot promise that what we have said is accurate. So taking into account your own parameters for things such as size, coat care, activity level, etc please come and get to know our dog(s) as individuals to see if their personalities and yours are a forever match.

animal.description:
3 years old Blitzen  needs a great person or family to bond with for the rest of his life. No cats and no other dog. Blitzen has lived all his life as an only pet and has not learnt how to behave with other animals.
His owner is gravely ill and had to surrender him. Blitzen is sad and confused, due to his owner's long illness, he was not exposed to many activities, and he really needs to move on with someone who understands the breed, is ready to spend a lot of time with him and give him lots of love and attention. He is currently on medication for anxiety/separation anxiety and will need a person or family who has a lot of time for him. Preferably a retired person or someone working from home. Aside from being absolutely stunning he is an affectionate snuggle bug, good on a leash, housetrained and not at all aggressive
Blitzen loves to play ball and to swim, he is learning new skills very fast. Blitzen is healthy, up to date on all vaccines and getting neutered and microchipped. He weighs 110 lbs, 
To adopt or foster, please submit a fully completed application on our website at www.nalasrescue.org/adoption-application.
We are located in Palm City, FL and we adopt mostly in a 50 miles radius. However, for this particular case, we would like to adopt him out in Martin, St Lucie or North palm Beach County. We always do home visit, and personalized met and greet, to insure that your new companion will be a great match for your family.

animal.description:
Hi! I’m Ethel and I’m ready to find my forever family. My rescuers found me on the street hobbling around on a broken leg and in pretty rough shape. They think I was hit by a car, possibly more than once. But after a few months, I’m on the mend and back to running and playing! 

My vets think I’m about a year and a half old. Which means I still have some puppy energy…especially in the mornings. Thankfully, I love enrichment activities like playing with balls and foraging. I also have a foster brother that loves to run and play tag with me in the back yard, and would do best if my forever family had another dog and a yard because I really love spending time outside.  But no kitties though…I am reactive. 

I have pretty good manners for only being off the streets a few months. I know to go potty outside. And how to sit. I will also sit and wait for my meals, though sometimes still forget that one! My foster family has also taught me to go to my “place” during mealtimes so I’m not begging at the table. 

I’m getting more comfortable spending time in my crate when my fosters leave, but I can have a little separation anxiety at times since they’re home so much right now. Giving me something to work on when they’re leaving really helps though! I also may need a little more leash training, but I love going for walks! Lastly, I’m a bit of a talker when you aren’t paying attention to me. But otherwise I don’t really bark.  

I have so much love to give. And when I’m not playing, my favorite place is next to you and your kids on the couch. I’m a GREAT snuggler! Who’s ready to give me a forever home?
animal.name: Ethel

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Alma is a young pit bull mix gal who came to us from the city pound. She currently weighs around 50 pounds and is around 2 years old. She is a very friendly girl who loves people and gets very excited when she meets them. She will definitely need exercise and basic training. She's a good girl and does have a lot of potential. She has been vet checked and spayed and her fee is $125.

We do think that Alma would do best in a home without young kids. She does need a somewhat calm home without a lot of people visiting and coming in and out. An experienced owner who can provide her with calm and consistent positive reinforcement training would be best. Alma does need to be the only pet in the home.

NOTE: We are not open to the public. Adoptions are done via private appointment once an application has been completed and approved. An application can be submitted at our website, mchs.rescuegroups.org.

We are located at 101 22nd St. SE in Austin, right next to the airport. It's exit 180B off of I-90, right off of 218 South.

We do require that potential adopters be at least 21 years old and that any resident dogs be up to date on vaccinations, heartworm testing/preventative, and spayed or neutered.

Georgia Ann is ready for her FOREVER home! She looks to be  a Boxer mix, with a huge heart, lots of energy, and would love to find her human family
 She is spayed, current on vaccinations, current on heartworm & flea prevention, and tested negative for heartworms. She is about four years old and 93 pounds of pure beauty. 
She would do best in a home with at least one canine sibling and a securely fenced yard to run and play in. She walks well on a leash, is not food or food aggressive and shares her space in her foster home with the other dogs like the sweet lady she is. 
 She is great with children, good with cats, and great with other dogs. Please email: jlopez42782@gmail.com if you are interested in adopting the girl. Adoption fee is $150.00.

animal.description: Bristol Babe is in northeastern IN, waiting for that super duper home that she knows she deserves! Well, when you are as nice a dog as Bristol then you do deserve the best. Bristol is a bundle of curiosity and affection and she is an adorable 40# Dalmatian Wannabe. Bristol loves it when her belly is rubbed, laying quietly with her legs straight in the air. How cute!! She is generally fine with the foster dogs, but she does prefer the boy dogs. Probably best with only male dogs, although she can be okay with quiet female dogs. On walks she does love to meet new dogs coming along. The neighborhood girls (8-11 yrs) are her favorite young people and they love her too. Her fun time is going to the woods to run. She does have a naturally high prey drive when it comes to wildlife critters and with cats she is unknown. Bristol walks well on the leash and our queen prefers fluffy beds but all she really wants is to be with "mom". Bristol is a very smart girl with PERFECT house manners. She is not a dog toy fanatic and she does not chew what she shouldn't, but she does love tennis balls and will return with them! Our girl is vocal about things outside, as nothing gets by her guarding instinct. One hind leg was injured before we met Bristol but the vet said that it is healed now and it works just fine. Bristol sits for meals or whatever she might want. Good girl! For more information, contact Chris at dalpal@rocketmail.com. Adoption $300. If interested in this dog, please go to www.dalmatianrescueco.org and submit an application for adoption. Under Adoptions, please read our adoption policy. We must have an application before we can begin the adoption process and each dog does have foster contact listed.

animal.description:
PLEASE READ ALL OF THE INFORMATION BELOW!

Meet Gemma, a small 6 year old Japanese terrier and such sweet girl! Gemma was recently rescued from a puppy mill in Pennsylvania. Gemma weighs about 12 pounds.

She’s a very sweet girl who is a bit timid in new situations particularly around loud sounds. She does well with other dogs and will do best in a home where there is another dog to help her feel safe. She will require a secure fenced in yard and a home with no young kids. She’s great with the other dogs in her foster home and intrigued with the cat, but doesn’t bother it. She’s learning to play with toys good with older kids.

Gemma is currently fostering in eastern PA.

We currently adopt in the states of NY, NJ, Eastern PA, DE, and some areas in MD. We can not accept applications from other states at this time.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our adoption application which you can find on our website at www.dutchcountryanimalrescue.org/adopt.html 

Our adoption fees are on our application.

All of our rescues are spayed/neutered, up to date on rabies and DHPP, heartworm tested, treated for worms and fleas and most are microchipped.

We are not a shelter, we are 100% volunteer public charity. All of our dogs are in foster homes until they are adopted. Since we are not a shelter, we do not receive government funding. We are a public charity that relies solely on funds through our adoption fee, fundraisers, and private donations. Since we are 100% volunteer based, all funds collected go directly towards the rescue and vet costs of our dogs.

We take each rescue personally and spend a lot of effort trying to match the right dog to the right family. Thank you for considering one of our rescued dogs.
